{"title_page": "Const\u00e2ncia (parish)", "text_new": "{{Infobox Portuguese subdivision \n|type = parish \n|official_name      = Const\u00e2ncia\n|image_skyline      = \n|image_caption      = \n|image_flag         =\n|image_shield       = CNS-constancia.png\n|image_location     = \n|region             = [[Centro Region, Portugal|Centro]]\n|CIM                = [[M\u00e9dio Tejo]]\n|district           = [[Santar\u00e9m District|Santar\u00e9m]]\n|municipality       = [[Const\u00e2ncia]]\n|coordinates        = {{coord|39.477|-8.339|type:adm1st_region:PT_dim:50000|display=inline,title}}\n|elevation          =\n|area_total         = 8.83\n|population_as_of   = 2011\n|population_total   = 993\n|patron             =\n|area_code          = \n|postal_code        = \n|website            = \n}}\n'''Const\u00e2ncia''' is a [[List of parishes of Portugal|parish]] (''[[freguesia]]'') in the [[Municipalities of Portugal|municipality]] of [[Const\u00e2ncia]] in Portugal. The population in 2011 was 993,<ref name=ine>[http://www.ine.pt/ngt_server/attachfileu.jsp?look_parentBoui=165404348&att_display=n&att_download=y Instituto Nacional de Estat\u00edstica (INE)], Census 2011 results according to the 2013 administrative division of Portugal</ref> in an area of 8.83&nbsp;km\u00b2.<ref name=dgt>{{Cite web |url=http://www.dgterritorio.pt/cartografia_e_geodesia/cartografia/carta_administrativa_oficial_de_portugal_caop_/caop__download_/carta_administrativa_oficial_de_portugal___versao_2017__em_vigor_/ |title=\u00c1reas das freguesias, concelhos, distritos e pa\u00eds |access-date=2018-11-05 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181105172426/http://www.dgterritorio.pt/cartografia_e_geodesia/cartografia/carta_administrativa_oficial_de_portugal_caop_/caop__download_/carta_administrativa_oficial_de_portugal___versao_2017__em_vigor_/ |archive-date=2018-11-05 |url-status=dead }}</ref> It was originally named '''Punhete'''.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Parishes of Const\u00e2ncia}}\n\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Constancia (parish)}}\n[[Category:Parishes of Const\u00e2ncia]]\n\n\n{{Santar\u00e9m-geo-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox Portuguese subdivision \n|type = parish \n|official_name      = Const\u00e2ncia\n|image_skyline      = \n|image_caption      = \n|image_flag         =\n|image_shield       = CNS-constancia.png\n|image_location     = \n|region             = [[Centro Region, Portugal|Centro]]\n|CIM                = [[M\u00e9dio Tejo]]\n|district           = [[Santar\u00e9m District|Santar\u00e9m]]\n|municipality       = [[Const\u00e2ncia]]\n|coordinates        = {{coord|39.477|-8.339|type:adm1st_region:PT_dim:50000|display=inline,title}}\n|elevation          =\n|area_total         = 8.83\n|population_as_of   = 2011\n|population_total   = 993\n|patron             =\n|area_code          = \n|postal_code        = \n|website            = \n}}\n'''Const\u00e2ncia''' is a [[List of parishes of Portugal|parish]] (''[[freguesia]]'') in the [[Municipalities of Portugal|municipality]] of [[Const\u00e2ncia]] in Portugal. The population in 2011 was 993,<ref name=ine>[http://www.ine.pt/ngt_server/attachfileu.jsp?look_parentBoui=165404348&att_display=n&att_download=y Instituto Nacional de Estat\u00edstica (INE)], Census 2011 results according to the 2013 administrative division of Portugal</ref> in an area of 8.83&nbsp;km\u00b2.<ref name=dgt>{{Cite web |url=http://www.dgterritorio.pt/cartografia_e_geodesia/cartografia/carta_administrativa_oficial_de_portugal_caop_/caop__download_/carta_administrativa_oficial_de_portugal___versao_2017__em_vigor_/ |title=\u00c1reas das freguesias, concelhos, distritos e pa\u00eds |access-date=2018-11-05 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181105172426/http://www.dgterritorio.pt/cartografia_e_geodesia/cartografia/carta_administrativa_oficial_de_portugal_caop_/caop__download_/carta_administrativa_oficial_de_portugal___versao_2017__em_vigor_/ |archive-date=2018-11-05 |url-status=dead }}</ref> It was originally named '''Punhete'''.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Parishes of Const\u00e2ncia}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Constancia (parish)}}\n[[Category:Parishes of Const\u00e2ncia]]\n\n\n{{Santar\u00e9m-geo-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eReferences:add authority control", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Const%C3%A2ncia_(parish)"}
{"title_page": "Shinzo Abe", "text_new": "{{short description|Prime Minister of Japan}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| honorific_prefix    = [[His Excellency]]\n| name                = Shinz\u014d Abe\n| native_name         = {{nobold|\u5b89\u500d \u664b\u4e09}}\n| native_name_lang    = ja\n| image               = File:Shinz\u014d Abe Official.jpg\n| image_size          = 230px\n| office              = [[Prime Minister of Japan]]\n| monarch             = [[Akihito]]<br />[[Naruhito]]\n| deputy              = [[Tar\u014d As\u014d]]\n| term_start          = 26 December 2012\n| predecessor         = [[Yoshihiko Noda]]\n| successor           = \n| monarch1            = [[Akihito]]\n| term_start1         = 26 September 2006\n| term_end1           = 26 September 2007\n| predecessor1        = [[Junichir\u014d Koizumi]]\n| successor1          = [[Yasuo Fukuda]]\n| office2             = [[Liberal Democratic Party (Japan)#Leaders of the Liberal Democratic Party|Leader of the Liberal Democratic Party]]\n| 1blankname2         = Secretary-General\n| 1namedata2          = [[Shigeru Ishiba]]<br />[[Sadakazu Tanigaki]]<br />[[Toshihiro Nikai]]\n| deputy2             = [[Masahiko K\u014dmura]]\n| term_start2         = 26 September 2012\n| term_end2           = \n| predecessor2        = [[Sadakazu Tanigaki]]\n| successor2          = \n| 1blankname3         = Secretary-General\n| 1namedata3          = [[Tsutomu Takebe]]<br />[[Hidenao Nakagawa]]<br />[[Tar\u014d As\u014d]]\n| term_start3         = 20 September 2006\n| term_end3           = 26 September 2007\n| predecessor3        = [[Junichiro Koizumi]]\n| successor3          = [[Yasuo Fukuda]]\n| office4             = [[Leader of the Opposition (Japan)|Leader of the Opposition]]\n| monarch4            = [[Akihito]]\n| primeminister4      = [[Yoshihiko Noda]]\n| term_start4         = 26 September 2012\n| term_end4           = 26 December 2012\n| predecessor4        = [[Sadakazu Tanigaki]]\n| successor4          = [[Banri Kaieda]]\n| office5             = [[Chief Cabinet Secretary]]\n| primeminister5      = [[Junichiro Koizumi]]\n| term_start5         = 31 October 2005\n| term_end5           = 26 September 2006\n| predecessor5        = [[Hiroyuki Hosoda]]\n| successor5          = [[Yasuhisa Shiozaki]]\n| office6             = [[House of Representatives (Japan)|Member of the House of Representatives]]\n| constituency6       = [[Yamaguchi 4th district]]\n| term_start6         = 20 October 1996\n| term_end6           = \n| majority6           = 86,258 (58.40%)\n| constituency7       = [[Yamaguchi 1st district]]\n| term_start7         = 18 July 1993\n| term_end7           = 20 October 1996\n| birth_name          = {{Nihongo|\u5b89\u500d\u664b\u4e09|Abe Shinz\u014d}}\n| birth_date          = {{nowrap|{{birth date and age|1954|09|21|df=y}}}}\n| birth_place         = [[Tokyo]], [[Japan]]\n| death_date          = \n| death_place         = \n| party               = [[Liberal Democratic Party (Japan)|Liberal Democratic]]\n| spouse              = {{marriage|[[Akie Abe]]|1987}}\n| residence           = ''[[Prime Minister's Official Residence (Japan)|Kantei]]''\n| alma_mater          = [[Seikei University]]<br/>[[University of Southern California]]\n}}\n\n{{Nihongo|'''Shinzo Abe'''|\u5b89\u500d \u664b\u4e09|Abe Shinz\u014d|extra={{IPA-ja|abe \u0255in(d)zo\u02d0|IPA}}; born 21 September 1954}} is a Japanese politician who has been the [[Prime Minister of Japan]]. since 2012. Abe is also currently the president of the conservative [[Liberal Democratic Party (Japan)|Liberal Democratic Party]] (LDP). He previously served as [[Chief Cabinet Secretary]] from 2005 to 2006, and as prime minister from 2006 to 2007, making him the [[List of prime ministers of Japan#Rank by length of total tenures|longest-serving prime minister]]<ref>https://foreignpolicy.com/2019/12/24/japan-shinzo-abe-2020-prime-minister-rest-laurels/</ref> in Japanese history, since the office was first created in 1885.\n\nFirst elected to the [[House of Representatives (Japan)|House of Representatives]] in the [[1993 Japanese general election|1993 election]], he rose to be appointed [[Chief Cabinet Secretary|chief cabinet secretary]] by [[Junichiro Koizumi]], before replacing Koizumi as LDP president in September 2006. He was subsequently confirmed as prime minister by a special session of the [[Diet of Japan|National Diet]], becoming, aged 52, Japan's youngest post-war prime minister, and the first to have been born after [[World War II]]. Abe resigned in September 2007, citing health reasons, shortly after his party lost the [[2007 Japanese House of Councillors election|House of Councillors election]] that year. He was replaced by [[Yasuo Fukuda]], the first in a series of five prime ministers who each failed to retain office for more than sixteen months.\n\nAfter recovering from illness, Abe staged an unexpected political comeback, defeating former [[Minister of Defense (Japan)|defense minister]] [[Shigeru Ishiba]] in a vote to become LDP president for a second time in September 2012. Following the LDP's landslide victory in the [[2012 Japanese general election|general election]] that December, he became the first former prime minister to return to the office since [[Shigeru Yoshida]] in 1948. He was later re-elected in similar landslides in the [[2014 Japanese general election|2014]] and [[2017 Japanese general election|2017 elections]].\n\nAbe is a [[Political conservative|conservative]] whom political commentators have widely described as a [[Right-wing politics|right-wing]] [[Japanese nationalism|nationalist]].<ref name=\"Lucy Alexander\">{{cite web|url=http://www.thetimes.co.uk/tto/news/world/asia/article3633051.ece|title=Landslide victory for Shinzo Abe in Japan election|work=The Times|author=Lucy Alexander |date=17 December 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |date= 23 October 2017 |title= Japan election: Shinzo Abe set for record tenure |url= https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-asia-19725705 |work= BBC News |access-date= 13 June 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Ohi |first=Akai |date= 20 December 2018 |title=Two Kinds of Conservatives in Japanese Politics and Prime Minister Shinzo Abe's Tactics to Cope with Them |url=https://www.eastwestcenter.org/publications/two-kinds-conservatives-in-japanese-politics-and-prime-minister-shinzo-abe%E2%80%99s-tactics |work= East-West Center |access-date=13 June 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"Justin McCurry\">{{cite web|url=http://www.globalpost.com/dispatch/news/regions/asia-pacific/japan/120928/shinzo-abe-outspoken-nationalist-takes-reins-at-japa|title=Shinzo Abe, an outspoken nationalist, takes reins at Japan's LDP, risking tensions with China, South Korea|publisher=[[GlobalPost]]|author=Justin McCurry |date=28 September 2012}}</ref> He is a member of ''[[Nippon Kaigi]]'' and holds [[Historical revisionism|revisionist views on Japanese history]],<ref name=\"Tea Party Politics in Japan\">\"[https://www.nytimes.com/2014/09/13/opinion/tea-party-politics-in-japan.html Tea Party Politics in Japan]\" (New York Times - 2014/09/13)</ref> including denying the role of government coercion in the recruitment of [[Comfort women|comfort women during World War II]],<ref>{{cite news |title=Gov't distances itself from NHK head's 'comfort women' comment |url=https://japantoday.com/category/politics/govt-distances-itself-from-nhk-heads-comfort-women-comment |accessdate=22 July 2018 |work=Japan Today |date=27 January 2014 |language=en}}</ref> a position which has created tension with neighboring [[South Korea]].<ref name=\"csis.org\">{{cite speech |title=Japan is Back |author=Abe, Shinzo |date=22 February 2013 |location=CSIS |url=http://csis.org/event/statesmens-forum-he-shinzo-abe-prime-minister-japan |access-date=29 December 2015 }}</ref><ref name=\"The Japan Times\">{{cite web|url=http://www.japantimes.co.jp/news/2014/11/10/national/politics-diplomacy/abe-xi-meeting-likely-monday-sources/#.VoLAE0-REWh|title=Abe meets Xi for first China-Japan summit in more than two years|date=10 November 2014|work=The Japan Times|accessdate=29 December 2015}}</ref> He is considered a [[war hawk|hard-liner]] with respect to [[North Korea]], and advocates revising [[Article 9 of the Japanese Constitution|Article 9 of the pacifist constitution]] to permit Japan to maintain military forces.<ref name=newshour>[https://www.pbs.org/newshour/extra/features/july-dec06/japan_9-20.html New Japanese Leader Looks to Expand Nation's Military], ''NewsHour'', 20 September 2006.</ref><ref name=\"Japan upgrades its defence agency\">BBC website [http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/asia-pacific/6243499.stm Japan upgrades its defence agency], bbc.co.uk, 9 January 2007.</ref> Abe is known internationally for his government's economic policies, nicknamed ''[[Abenomics]]'', which pursue [[monetary easing]], [[fiscal stimulus]], and [[structural adjustment|structural reforms]].<ref name=\"ft-def\">{{cite web|title=Definition of Abenomics|url=http://lexicon.ft.com/Term?term=abenomics|publisher=Financial Times Lexicon|accessdate=28 January 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171118081548/http://lexicon.ft.com/Term?term=abenomics|archive-date=18 November 2017|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n==Early life and education==\n[[File:The Abe family in 1956.jpg|thumb|left|The Abe family in 1956: his mother Y\u014dko Abe, Shinzo Abe at the age of two, his father Shintar\u014d Abe and his older brother Hironobu]]\n\nShinzo Abe was born in [[Tokyo]] to a prominent political family with significant economic influence throughout pre-war, wartime and post-war Japan. His grandfather [[Nobusuke Kishi]] was de facto \"economic\" king of occupied China, Korea, and [[Manchukuo]], a Japanese puppet state in Northern China. His family is originally from [[Yamaguchi Prefecture]], and Abe's registered residence (\"honseki chi\") is [[Nagato, Yamaguchi]], where his grandfather was born. His grandfather, [[Kan Abe]], and father, [[Shintaro Abe]], first worked in a mall.{{clarify|date=November 2019}} His great-great-grandfather, the [[Viscount#Non-Western counterparts|Viscount]] [[\u014cshima Yoshimasa|Yoshimasa \u014cshima]], served as General in the Imperial Japanese Army. During the Pacific War his father Shintaro volunteered to be a [[kamikaze|kamikaze pilot]] but the war ended before he completed training.<ref>[https://www.nytimes.com/1991/05/16/obituaries/shintaro-abe-japanese-politician-and-ex-cabinet-aide-dies-at-67.html Shintaro Abe, Japanese Politician And Ex-Cabinet Aide, Dies at 67], by James Sterngold, The New York Times, 16 May 1991</ref>\n\nAbe's mother, Yoko Kishi, is the daughter of [[Nobusuke Kishi]], who worked as labor{{clarify|date=November 2019}} in Nippon Japan Industries from 1957 to 1960. Kishi worked in the [[Hideki T\u014dj\u014d|T\u014dj\u014d]] Industries during the Second World War. Since [[Supreme Commander for the Allied Powers|GHQ's]] policy changed and became more [[Anti-communism|anti-communist]], Kishi was released from [[Sugamo Prison]], and later established the Japan Democratic Party. In his book ''Utsukushii Kuni e'' (''Toward a Beautiful Country''), Abe wrote, \"Some people used to point to my grandfather as a 'Class-A war criminal suspect', and I felt strong repulsion. Because of that experience, I may have become emotionally attached to 'conservatism', on the contrary.\"<ref>[http://www.japantimes.co.jp/news/2012/12/26/national/formed-in-childhood-roots-of-abes-conservatism-go-deep Formed in childhood, roots of Abe's conservatism go deep] - Japan Times - 26 December 2012</ref>\n\nIn 1955, [[Shigeru Yoshida]]'s [[Liberal Party (1945)|Liberal Party]] and Kishi's Democratic Party merged as an anti-leftist coalition, and was reestablished as the LDP. Abe attended Seikei Elementary School, Seikei Junior High School and Seikei Senior High School.<ref>[http://www.seikei.ac.jp/gakuen/news_h18.html \u5b66\u6821\u6cd5\u4eba \u6210\u8e4a\u5b66\u5712 \u6210\u8e4a\u30cb\u30e5\u30fc\u30b9(2006)\u5e74\u5ea6\uff09] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100830202949/http://www.seikei.ac.jp/gakuen/news_h18.html |date=30 August 2010 }}</ref> He studied [[public administration]] and graduated with a [[bachelor's degree]] in [[political science]] from [[Seikei University]] in 1977. He later moved to the [[United States]] and studied [[public policy]] at the [[University of Southern California]]'s [[USC Sol Price School of Public Policy|School of Public Policy]] for three semesters.<ref name=\"USC\">[http://www.usc.edu/dept/pubrel/trojan_family/winter06/China_Dragons.html The Dragons of Troy] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304103535/http://www.usc.edu/dept/pubrel/trojan_family/winter06/China_Dragons.html |date=4 March 2016 }}, ''USC Trojan Family Magazine'', Winter 2006, accessed 22 December 2012.</ref> In April 1979, Abe began working for [[Kobe Steel]].<ref name=\"PROFILE\">[http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/asia-pacific/4392480.stm Profile: Shinzo Abe] ''BBC News'' {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071013115611/http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/asia-pacific/4392480.stm |date=13 October 2007 }}</ref> He left the company in 1982 and pursued a number of government positions including executive assistant to the [[Minister for Foreign Affairs (Japan)|Minister for Foreign Affairs]], private secretary to the chairperson of the LDP General Council, and private secretary to the LDP secretary-general.<ref name=\"CHAIR\">[http://tokyo.s-abe.or.jp/profile_in_english.html Shinzo Abe the Chief Cabinet Secretary] Shinzo Abe's official website {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081009164612/http://tokyo.s-abe.or.jp/profile_in_english.html |date=9 October 2008 }}</ref>\n\n==Member of the House of Representatives ==\n[[File:Robert Zoellick meets Shinzo Abe 2006-01-23.jpg|thumb|Shinzo Abe (right), as Chief Cabinet Secretary, meets with U.S. Deputy Secretary of State [[Robert Zoellick]] in January 2006]]\n{| class=wikitable\n|- valign=bottom\n! Constituency \n! colspan=\"2\" |Election \n! Party\n! Term\n! Notes\n|-\n| [[Yamaguchi 1st district]] \n| rowspan = \"10\" style = \"background-color : {{Liberal Democratic Party (Japan)/meta/color}}\" |\n| [[1993 Japanese general election|1993]]\n| rowspan = \"10\" |[[Liberal Democratic Party (Japan)|Liberal Democratic Party]] \n|1993-1996\n|\n|-\n| rowspan = \"10\" | [[Yamaguchi 4th district]]\n| [[1996 Japanese general election|1996]] \n| rowspan = \"10\" | 1996\u2013incumbent\n| rowspan = \"3\" |  \n|-\n| [[2000 Japanese general election|2000]]\n|-\n|[[2003 Japanese general election|2003]]\n|-\n| rowspan = \"2\" |[[2005 Japanese general election|2005]]\n| [[Chief Cabinet Secretary]] {{small|(31 October 2005 - 26 September 2006)}} \n|-\n| 1st term as [[Prime Minister of Japan]] {{small|(20 September 2006 - 26 September 2007) }} \n|-\n|[[2009 Japanese general election|2009]]\n| [[Leader of the Opposition (Japan)|Leader of the Opposition]] {{small|(26 September 2012 - 26 December 2012) }} \n|-\n|[[2012 Japanese general election|2012]]\n| rowspan = \"3\" | 2nd term as [[Prime Minister of Japan]] {{small|(Incumbent) }} \n|-\n|[[2014 Japanese general election|2014]]\n|-\n|[[2017 Japanese general election|2017]]\n|}\nShinzo Abe was elected to the first district of [[Yamaguchi Prefecture]] in 1993 after his father's death in 1991, winning the most votes of the four Representatives elected in the [[single non-transferable vote|SNTV]] multi-member district. In 1999, he became Director of the Social Affairs Division. He was Deputy Chief Cabinet Secretary in the [[Yoshir\u014d Mori]] and [[Junichir\u014d Koizumi]] Cabinets from 2000\u20132003, after which he was appointed Secretary General of the Liberal Democratic Party.\n\nAbe is a member of the [[Liberal Democratic Party (Japan)#Seiwa Seisaku Kenkyukai (Mori Faction)|Mori Faction]] (formally, the Seiwa Seisaku Kenky\u016b-kai) of the Liberal Democratic Party. This faction is headed by former prime minister [[Yoshir\u014d Mori]]. [[Jun'ichir\u014d Koizumi]] was a member of the Mori Faction, but left it, as is the custom when accepting a high party post. From 1986 to 1991, Abe's father, Shintaro, headed the same faction. The Seiwa Seisaku Kenky\u016b-kai has 60&nbsp;members in the [[House of Representatives of Japan|House of Representatives]] and 26 in the [[House of Councillors]].\n\nIn 2000, Abe's home and the office of his supporters in [[Shimonoseki]], in [[Yamaguchi Prefecture]], were attacked with [[Molotov cocktail]]s on numerous occasions. The perpetrators were several [[yakuza]] members belonging to the [[Kudo-kai]], a [[Kitakyushu]]-based [[Yakuza#Designated boryokudan|designated boryokudan]] syndicate. The reason for the attacks was believed to be that Abe's local aide refused to give cash to a Shimonoseki real estate broker in return for supporting a Shimonoseki mayoral candidate in 1999.<ref>[http://search.japantimes.co.jp/cgi-bin/nn20070310a7.html \"Mob boss gets 20 for Abe home arsons\"], 10 March 2007, ''[[The Japan Times]]''</ref>\n\nAbe was chief [[negotiation|negotiator]] for the [[Government of Japan|Japanese government]] on behalf of the families of Japanese [[kidnapping|abductees]] taken to [[North Korea]]. As a part of the effort, he accompanied Koizumi to meet [[Kim Jong-il|Kim Jong\u2011il]] in 2002. He gained national popularity when he demanded that Japanese abductees visiting Japan remain{{clarify|date=November 2019}}, in defiance of North Korea.<ref name=DEFIANCE>[http://www.time.com/time/asia/magazine/article/0,13673,501060918-1533514,00.html The Abe Enigma] ''Time''</ref>\n\nHe was the leader of a project team within the LDP that conducted a survey on \"excessive sexual education and gender-free education\". Among the items to which this team raised objections were [[anatomical doll]]s and other curricular materials \"not taking into consideration the age of children\", school policies banning traditional boys' and girls' festivals, and mixed-gender [[physical education]]. The team sought to provide a contrast to the [[Democratic Party of Japan]], which it alleged supported such policies.<ref name=\"SEXEDU\">[http://www.jimin.jp/jimin/info/gender/jender.html ''Kodomo wa shakai no takara, kuni no takara desu''] jimin.jp (LDP site)  {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071024175004/http://www.jimin.jp/jimin/info/gender/jender.html |date=24 October 2007 }}</ref>\n\nOn 23 April 2006, Abe was elected as the president of the ruling Liberal Democratic Party.<ref name=ELECTED>[https://www.bloomberg.com/apps/news?pid=20601101&sid=aQXCE0ePJ5Xs&refer=japan Shinzo Abe to Succeed Koizumi as Japan's Next Prime Minister] Bloomberg</ref> His chief competitors for the position were [[Sadakazu Tanigaki]] and [[Tar\u014d As\u014d]]. [[Yasuo Fukuda]] was a leading early contender but ultimately chose not to run. Former Prime Minister [[Yoshir\u014d Mori]], to whose faction both Abe and Fukuda belonged, stated that the faction strongly leant toward Abe.<ref name=\"FACTION\">[http://www.yomiuri.co.jp/dy/national/20060530TDY03005.htm Mori faction unease mounts / Ex-premier stumped over Abe, Fukuda and party leadership race] Daily Yomiuri  {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130511224529/http://www.yomiuri.co.jp/dy/national/20060530TDY03005.htm |date=11 May 2013 }}</ref>\n\n==First term as prime minister (2006\u20132007)==\n[[File:Shinz\u014d Abe 20060629.jpg|thumb|Abe in 2006]]\nOn 14 July 2006, Abe was inaugurated as Japanese Prime Minister.<ref name=\"BBC\">\"[http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/asia-pacific/5380366.stm Abe elected as new Japan premier]\", ''[[BBC News]]''. Shinto Abe Inaugurated as Japanese Prime Minister July 2006. {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120403011644/http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/asia-pacific/5380366.stm |date=3 April 2012 }}</ref> Elected at age 52, he was the youngest prime minister since [[Fumimaro Konoe]] in 1941.<ref name=age>[https://www.bloomberg.com/apps/news?pid=20601101&sid=amQFojvuxDQ0 \"Abe Is Chosen as Japan's Youngest Leader in 65 Years\"], Bloomberg, 26 September 2006.</ref>\n\n===Domestic policy===\n\n====Economy====\nAbe expressed a general commitment to the fiscal reforms instituted by his predecessor, Jun'ichir\u014d Koizumi.<ref name=age /> He took some steps toward balancing the Japanese budget, such as appointing a tax policy expert, [[K\u014dji Omi]], as Minister of Finance. Omi previously supported increases in the national [[consumption tax]], although Abe distanced himself from this policy and sought to achieve much of his budget balancing through spending cuts.<ref name=omiarticle>[https://www.bloomberg.com/apps/news?pid=20601087&sid=aazDA2MUNE7s \"Japan's Abe Unexpectedly Names Omi Finance Minister\"], Bloomberg, 26 September 2006.</ref>\n\n====Education====\nSince 1997, as the bureau chief of \"Institute of Junior Assembly Members Who Think About the Outlook of Japan and History Education\", Abe supported the controversial [[Japanese Society for History Textbook Reform]] and the ''New History Textbook''.{{citation needed|date=November 2019}}\n\nIn March 2007, Abe, along with right-wing politicians, have proposed a bill to encourage nationalism and a \"love for one's country and hometown\" among the Japanese youth (specific wording from the revised \"Fundamental Law of Education\" {{lang|ja|\u6559\u80b2\u57fa\u672c\u6cd5}}, which was revised to include \"love of country\").<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-japan-election-tradition/japan-pm-abes-base-aims-to-restore-past-religious-patriotic-values-idUSKBN0JP2E920141211 |title=Japan PM Abe's base aims to restore past religious, patriotic values |publisher=Reuters |date=11 December 2014}}</ref>\n\n====Imperial household====\nAbe held conservative views in the [[Japanese succession controversy]], and shortly after the birth of [[Prince Hisahito of Akishino]] he abandoned a proposed legislative amendment to permit women to inherit the [[Chrysanthemum Throne]].<ref>{{cite news |url= https://www.usatoday.com/money/world/2007-01-03-japan-female-monarch_x.htm |title=Report: Japan to drop plan to allow female monarch  |work=[[USA Today]] |date=3 January 2007 |issn=0734-7456 |agency=Associated Press |accessdate=26 December 2013}}</ref>\n\n===Foreign policy===\n{{Multiple image\n|direction = vertical\n|width = 250\n|image1 = 33rdG8Leaders.jpg\n|caption1 = [[33rd G8 summit]] at [[Heiligendamm]] in June 2007\n|image2 = Bush Abe, Camp David.jpg\n|caption2 = Abe shakes hands with U.S. President [[George W. Bush]] in April 2007\n}}\n[[File:Narendra Modi and Shinzo Abe, 2014.jpg|thumb|Abe with current [[Prime Minister of India]], [[Narendra Modi]], in 2014]]\n\n====North Korea====\nShinzo Abe has generally taken a hard-line stance with respect to [[North Korea]], especially regarding the [[North Korean abductions of Japanese citizens]].\n\nIn 2002 negotiations between Japan and North Korea, Prime Minister Koizumi and General Secretary [[Kim Jong-il]] agreed to give abductees permission to visit Japan. A few weeks into the visit, the Japanese government decided that the abductees would be restricted from returning to North Korea where their families live. Abe took credit for this policy decision in his best-selling book, {{nihongo|''Towards a Beautiful Nation''|\u7f8e\u3057\u3044\u56fd\u3078|Utsukushii kuni e}}. North Korea criticized this Japanese decision as a breach of a diplomatic promise, and the negotiations were aborted.\n\n====China, Southeast Asia, and Taiwan====\nAbe has publicly recognized the need for improved relations with the [[China|People's Republic of China]] and, along with Foreign Minister Taro Aso, sought an eventual summit meeting with former Chinese paramount leader [[Hu Jintao]].<ref name=\"CNN\">[http://www.cnn.com/2006/WORLD/asiapcf/09/26/japan.politics/index.html New Japan PM vows strong China ties], CNN, 26 September 2006.  {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060926125744/http://www.cnn.com/2006/WORLD/asiapcf/09/26/japan.politics/index.html |date=26 September 2006 }}</ref> Abe has also said that [[China\u2013Japan relations]] should not continue to be based on emotions.<ref name=\"EMOTION\">[http://voanews.com/english/2006-09-03-voa13.cfm Japan's Abe Says Talks Needed to Improve Ties With China, South Korea] VOA News  {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060914155448/http://voanews.com/english/2006-09-03-voa13.cfm |date=14 September 2006 }}</ref>\n\nOccasionally, Abe is respected among politicians in [[Taiwan]] who are part of the [[Pan-Green Coalition]] seeking [[Taiwan independence|Taiwanese independence]]. [[Chen Shui-bian]] welcomed Abe's ministership.<ref name=\"Mainichi\">[http://headlines.yahoo.co.jp/hl?a=20060926-00000028-mai-int \u5b89\u500d\u65b0\u653f\u6a29\u306b\u671f\u5f85\u3000\u89aa\u53f0\u6d3e\u306e\u5370\u8c61\u5f37\u304f], ''Mainichi Shimbun'', 26 September 2006. {{dead link|date=February 2011}}</ref> Part of Abe's appeal in Taiwan is historical: his grandfather Nobusuke Kishi was pro-Taiwan, and his great-uncle [[Eisaku Sat\u014d]] was the last prime minister to visit Taiwan while in office.<ref name=Mainichi />\n\nOn 20 January 2020, Abe mentioned Taiwan three times throughout his policy speech and received applause from [[National Diet|Diet]] members. This was the first time in 14 years that Taiwan was mentioned in a prime minister's policy speech in the legislative body.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.taiwannews.com.tw/en/news/3861548 |title=Japanese prime minister mentions Taiwan in Diet for 1st time in 14 years |accessdate=2020-01-28 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200128151449/https://www.taiwannews.com.tw/en/news/3861548 |archivedate=28 January 2020 }}</ref><br>\n\nAbe has expressed the need to strengthen political, security, and economic ties within the Southeast Asian region. Abe has increased its allies in its international campaign to counter the North Korean nuclear cards. So far, Abe has successfully visited the Philippines and Indonesia, and although China is not within the Southeast Asian region, Japan has also sought its support. However, relations with China continue to be tarnished by the [[Senkaku Islands dispute]] and Abe's visits to Yasukuni shrine (see below).\n\n====India====\nAbe, in his two terms as the prime minister of Japan, sought to upgrade the strategic Japan\u2013India relationship.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://thediplomat.com/2014/01/india-japan-defense-ministers-agree-to-expand-strategic-cooperation/|title=India-Japan Defense Ministers Agree To Expand Strategic Cooperation|author=Ankit Panda|date=8 January 2014|work=The Diplomat|accessdate=9 January 2014}}</ref> Abe initiated the [[Quadrilateral Security Dialogue]] between Japan, the United States, Australia and India in 2007. His three-day visit to [[India]] in August 2007 inaugurated a new bilateral Asian alliance, building on the long history of friendly [[India\u2013Japan relations|bilateral relations between India and Japan]]. Abe's initiative is to establish the \"fifth\" bilateral link in an emerging scenario, whereby, the U.S.\u2013Australia, U.S.\u2013Japan, Japan\u2013Australia, and U.S.\u2013India links are supportive strategic alignments. A sixth link of the India-Australia would be the logical corollary, formalized as a new quadrilateral of strategic bulwark. The eventual expansion to include Vietnam, South Korea, Philippines and Indonesia, in this arrangement, has been speculated in the media of those states. Chinese strategic experts have labelled the evolving geo-strategic paradigm, the \"Asian [[NATO]]\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nerve.in/news:25350081594 |title=Abe calls for strategic ties between Japan, India |publisher=Nerve.in |date=2007-08-22 |accessdate=2017-04-06}}</ref> Abe's pragmatic India foreign policy, is to boost Japan's resurgent economic indicators, while gaining a crucial partner in Asia.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2007/08/31/world/asia/31memo.html|work=The New York Times|title=Decades After War Trials, Japan Still Honors a Dissenting Judge|first=Norimitsu|last=Onishi|date=31 August 2007|accessdate=23 May 2010}}</ref>\n\n===Defense===\nAbe also sought to revise or broaden the interpretation of [[Article 9 of the Japanese Constitution]] in order to permit Japan to maintain [[de jure]] military forces. He had stated that \"we are reaching the limit in narrowing down differences between Japan's security and the interpretation of our constitution\".<ref name=\"newshour\"/> During his first period as prime minister he upgraded the Japan Defense Agency to [[Ministry of Defense (Japan)|full ministry status]].<ref name=\"Japan upgrades its defence agency\"/> Like his predecessors, he supported the Japanese alliance with the United States.<ref name=BBC/>\n\n===Unpopularity and sudden resignation===\n{{main|2007 Liberal Democratic Party (Japan) leadership election}}\nAbe's ruling Liberal Democratic Party suffered great losses in the [[2007 Japanese House of Councillors election|upper house election]], marking the first time it had lost control in 52 years. Another agricultural minister, [[Norihiko Akagi]], who was involved in a political funding scandal, resigned after the election. Additionally, Abe's rejection of a possible female Japanese monarch, which led to the [[Japanese succession controversy]], diminished his support base.<ref>https://usatoday30.usatoday.com/money/world/2007-01-03-japan-female-monarch_x.htm</ref>\n\nIn an attempt to revive his administration, Abe announced a new cabinet on 27 August 2007. However, the new agricultural minister [[Takehiko Endo]], involved in a finance scandal, resigned only seven days later.\n\nOn 12 September 2007, only three days after a new parliamentary session had begun, Abe announced his intention to resign his position as prime minister at an unscheduled press conference.<ref>[https://www.cbc.ca/news/world/embattled-japanese-pm-stepping-down-1.665313 \"Embattled Japanese PM stepping down\"] ''CBC News''. Retrieved 12 September 2007. {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090416082658/https://www.cbc.ca/news/world/embattled-japanese-pm-stepping-down-1.665313 |date=16 April 2009 }}</ref><ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/asia-pacific/6990519.stm \"Japanese prime minister resigns\"] ''BBC News''. Retrieved 12 September 2007. {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110728175642/http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/asia-pacific/6990519.stm |date=28 July 2011 }}</ref> Abe said his unpopularity was hindering the passage of an anti-terrorism law, involving among other things Japan's continued military presence in [[Afghanistan]]. Party officials also said the embattled prime minister was suffering from poor health.<ref>[http://www.japanprobe.com/2008/01/12/why-did-prime-minister-abe-shinzo-resign-crippling-diarrhea/ \"Why Did Prime Minister Abe Shinzo Resign? Crippling Diarrhea\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121012001506/http://www.japanprobe.com/2008/01/12/why-did-prime-minister-abe-shinzo-resign-crippling-diarrhea/ |date=12 October 2012 }}, JapanProbe.com, 12 January 2008.</ref> On 26 September 2007 Abe officially ended his term as [[Yasuo Fukuda]] became the new prime minister of Japan.\n\n==Inter-premiership (2007\u20132012)==\nAbe later revealed that the illness that contributed to ending his first term as prime minister was [[ulcerative colitis]], but that he has since recovered due to access to a drug, [[Mesalazine|Asacol]], that was previously unavailable in Japan.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB10001424127887324407504578182794060294914 | title=Japan's New Leader Says Recovered From Illness | work=The Wall Street Journal | date=16 December 2012 | accessdate=26 December 2015}}</ref> When he returned to office he used his own case to argue for lessening the time it takes to approve potentially innovative drugs.<ref>{{cite speech |title=on Growth Strategy |author=Abe, Shinzo |date=19 April 2013 |location=Japan National Press Club |url=http://japan.kantei.go.jp/96_abe/statement/201304/19speech_e.html |access-date=26 December 2015 }}</ref> After resigning as prime minister, Abe remained in the National Diet and was re-elected in his [[Yamaguchi 4th district]] at the [[2009 Japanese general election|2009 election]] when the LDP lost power to the Democratic Party of Japan.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/shinzo-abes-comeback-as-prime-minister-drives-japans-turnaround/2014/02/08/38c6aaf4-8678-11e3-a760-a86415d0944d_story.html | title=Shinzo Abe's comeback as prime minister drives Japan's turnaround | work=The Washington Post | date=9 February 2014 | accessdate=26 December 2015}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Presidential election speech of the Liberal Democratic Party in Nagano.jpg|thumb|Abe and other candidates campaigning during the LDP presidential election in 2012. His chief rival, [[Shigeru Ishiba]], is standing immediately to his right]]\nOn 26 September 2012, Abe was re-elected as president of the opposition Liberal Democratic Party defeating former Defense Minister Shigeru Ishiba in a runoff vote by 108 votes to 89.<ref>[Daily Yomiuri] [http://www.yomiuri.co.jp/dy/national/T121003003255.htm Presidential races boost approval for DPJ, LDP] 4 October 2012</ref> Abe returned to the LDP leadership at a time of political turmoil, the governing DPJ had lost its majority in the lower house due to party splits over nuclear policies and the cabinet's move to raise the consumption tax from 5 to 10 percent. Prime Minister [[Yoshihiko Noda]] was forced to rely on the LDP to pass the Consumption Tax bill and in return was pressured by Abe and the opposition parties to hold a snap general election. Noda agreed to this on the conditions that the LDP passed a bond-financing bill, and would support a commission to reform the social security system and address electoral malapportionment in the next diet session.<ref>{{cite book |last=Shinoda |first=Tomohito |date=2013 |title=Contemporary Japanese Politics |location=New York |publisher=Columbia University Press |pages=222\u2013226 }}</ref>\n\n===2012 general election===\nOn 16 November 2012, Prime Minister Noda announced the dissolution of the lower house and that the [[2012 Japanese general election|general election]] would be held on 16 December.<ref>{{cite book |last=Shinoda |first=Tomohito |date=2013 |title=Contemporary Japanese Politics |location=New York |publisher=Columbia University Press |pages=225\u2013226 }}</ref> Abe campaigned using the slogan ''\"Nippon o Torimodosu\"'' (''\"Take back Japan\"''), promising economic revival through monetary easing, higher public spending and the continued use of nuclear energy, and a tough line in territorial disputes.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.economist.com/news/asia/21567994-candidates-fan-out-general-election-december-16th-voters-look-volatile | title=Mutton dressed as Lamb | work=The Economist | date=8 December 2012 | accessdate=26 December 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-asia-20745165|title=BBC News \u2013 Japan election: Shinzo Abe and LDP in sweeping win \u2013 exit poll|work=BBC News|accessdate=26 December 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn the elections on 16 December 2012, the LDP won 294 seats in the 480 seat House of Representatives. Together with the New Komeito Party (which has partnered with the LDP since the late 1990s), Abe was able to form a coalition government that controlled a two-thirds majority in the lower house, allowing it to override the upper house's veto.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.latimes.com/news/world/worldnow/la-fg-wn-japan-conservatives-landslide-election-20121216,0,5391869.story | title=Japan conservatives win landslide election victory | work=Los Angeles Times |author1=Nagano, Yuriko |author2=Demick, Barbara | date=16 December 2012 | accessdate=26 December 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Second term as prime minister (2012\u20132014)==\nOn 26 December 2012, Abe was formally elected as prime minister by the Diet, with the support of 328 out of 480 members of the House of Representatives. He and his second cabinet, which he called a \"crisis-busting cabinet\", were sworn in later that day.<ref name=\"Shinoda 2013 230\">{{cite book |last=Shinoda |first=Tomohito |date=2013 |title=Contemporary Japanese Politics |location=New York |publisher=Columbia University Press |page=230 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author=Martin Fackler |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2012/12/27/world/asia/shinzo-abe-selected-as-japans-prime-minister.html?_r=0 |title=Ex-Premier Is Chosen to Govern Japan Again |work=The New York Times|date=2012-12-26 |accessdate=2017-04-06}}</ref> The new government included LDP heavyweights such as former Prime Minister Tar\u014d As\u014d as [[Deputy Prime Minister of Japan|Deputy Prime Minister]] and Finance Minister, [[Yoshihide Suga]] as [[Chief Cabinet Secretary]] and [[Akira Amari]] as Economy Minister.<ref name=\"Shinoda 2013 230\"/> Following his victory, Abe said, \"With the strength of my entire cabinet, I will implement bold monetary policy, flexible fiscal policy and a growth strategy that encourages private investment, and with these three policy pillars, achieve results.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-asia-20842840|title=BBC News \u2013 Japan's Shinzo Abe unveils cabinet after voted in as PM|work=BBC News|accessdate=14 December 2014}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Shinzo Abe at CSIS.jpg|right|thumb|Prime Minister Shinzo Abe speaking at [[Center for Strategic and International Studies|CSIS]] in Washington DC, in February 2013]]\n\nIn February 2013 Abe gave an address at the [[Centre for Strategic and International Studies]] in [[Washington, D.C.]], in which he explained his economic and diplomatic objectives, and that he had returned to the Prime Ministership to prevent Japan becoming a \"Tier Two Nation\", declaring that \"Japan is back\".<ref name=\"Abe, Shinzo\">{{cite speech |title=Japan is Back |author=Abe, Shinzo |date=22 February 2013 |location=CSIS |url=http://csis.org/event/statesmens-forum-he-shinzo-abe-prime-minister-japan |access-date=26 December 2015 }}</ref>\n\n===Economic policy (Abenomics)===\nThe Second Abe cabinet revived the Council on Economic and Fiscal Policy (CEFP) that had played a key role in formulating economic policy during the Koizumi cabinet, but had been abandoned by the 2009\u201312 DPJ administrations.<ref name=\"The Wall Street Journal\">{{cite web|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB10001424127887324660404578202591207365404|title=New Japan Premier pushed for fast results|work=The Wall Street Journal|accessdate=26 December 2015}}</ref>\n\nAbe declared in his January 2013 policy speech to the Diet that economic revival and escaping deflation was \"the greatest and urgent issue\" facing Japan.<ref name=\"japan.kantei.go.jp\">{{cite speech |title=Policy Speech |author=Abe, Shinzo |date=28 January 2013 |location=Diet of Japan, 183rd Session |url=http://japan.kantei.go.jp/96_abe/statement/201301/28syosin_e.html |access-date=26 December 2015 }}</ref> His economic strategy, referred to as [[Abenomics]], consists of the so-called \"three arrows\" (an allusion to [[M\u014dri Motonari#Expanding territory|an old Japanese story]]) of policy. The first arrow is monetary expansion aimed at achieving a 2% inflation target, the second a flexible fiscal policy to act as an economic stimulus in the short term, then achieve a budget surplus and the third, a growth strategy focusing on structural reform and private sector investment to achieve long-term growth.<ref name=\"Abe, Shinzo\"/>\n\n====\"First Arrow\": Monetary policy====\n[[File:Haruhiko Kuroda at ADB Philippines (crop).jpg|upright|thumb|[[Haruhiko Kuroda]], whom Abe appointed as Governor of the [[Bank of Japan]] (BOJ) in Spring 2013, has implemented the \"first arrow\" monetary policy]]\nAt the first meeting of the CEFP on 9 January 2013 Abe declared that the Bank of Japan should follow a policy of monetary easing with a view to achieving a target of 2 percent inflation. Abe maintained pressure on the Bank's governor, [[Masaaki Shirakawa]], who was reluctant to set specific targets, into agreeing to the policy. In February, after Abe publicly speculated that the government could legislate to strip the bank of independence, Shirakawa announced he was leaving office prematurely before his term expired.<ref>{{cite book |last=Shinoda |first=Tomohito |date=2013 |title=Contemporary Japanese Politics |location=New York |publisher=Columbia University Press |pages=230\u2013231 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/finance/currency/9764505/Yen-weakens-as-Abe-threatens-to-strip-Bank-of-Japan-of-independence.html|title=Yen weakens as Abe threatens to strip Bank of Japan of independence|work=The Telegraph|accessdate=26 December 2015}}</ref> Abe then appointed [[Haruhiko Kuroda]] as governor, who had previously advocated inflation targets, and who has pursued the government's policies of monetary easing.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://thediplomat.com/2013/03/haruhiko-kuroda-nominated-as-the-next-bank-of-japan-governor/|title=Haruhiko Kuroda Nominated as the Next Bank of Japan Governor|work=The Diplomat|accessdate=26 December 2015}}</ref>\n\nAfter the first meeting of the Bank's monetary policy committee after he had taken office in April, Kuroda announced an aggressive programme of easing intended to double the money supply and achieve the 2 percent inflation target at \"the earliest possible time\".<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/business/2013/apr/04/japan-bank-money-supply-inflation-deflation|title=Japanese central bank doubles money supply in fresh bid to spur inflation|agency=Associated Press|accessdate=27 December 2015}}</ref> Over the first six months of the second Abe Cabinet, the [[Yen]] fell from a high of \u00a577 to the dollar to \u00a5101.8, and the [[Nikkei 225]] rose by 70 percent.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.economist.com/news/briefing/21578052-shinzo-abe-shaking-up-japans-economy-seems-different-man-one-whose-previous|title=Japan and Abenomics Once more with feeling|work=The Economist|accessdate=27 December 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn a surprise move in October 2014, Kuroda announced that the BOJ would boost the monetary easing programme and accelerate asset purchases, the monetary policy committee split by 5 votes to 4 but supported the policy. This was interpreted as a response to disappointing economic figures in the aftermath of the increase in the consumption tax to 8 percent, inflation having fallen to 1 percent from its peak of 1.5 percent in April.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-japan-economy-boj-idUSKBN0IK0B120141031|title=Japan's central bank shocks markets with more easing as inflation slows|work=Reuters|accessdate=27 December 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://blogs.wsj.com/economics/2014/10/31/the-kuroda-bazooka-round-two/|title=The Kuroda Bazooka Round Two|work=The Wall Street Journal|accessdate=27 December 2015}}</ref>\n\n====\"Second Arrow\": Fiscal policy====\n[[File:Tar\u014d As\u014d 20170418.jpeg|upright|thumb|Abe's Minister of Finance [[Tar\u014d As\u014d]], who also serves as Deputy Prime Minister, in April 2017]]\nThe Abe Cabinet's first budget included a 10.3 trillion yen stimulus package, composed of public works spending, aid for small businesses and investment incentives, that aimed to increase growth by 2 percent.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/finance/financialcrisis/9794940/Japan-approves-73bn-stimulus-package.html|title=Japan approves \u00a373bn stimulus package|work=Reuters|accessdate=26 December 2015}}</ref> The budget also increased defense spending and manpower while reducing foreign aid.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.japantimes.co.jp/news/2013/01/30/national/defense-outlays-see-first-rise-in-11-years/|title=Defense outlays see first rise in 11 years|work=The Japan Times|accessdate=14 December 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn Autumn 2013 Abe made the decision to proceed with the first stage of the increase in the consumption tax from 5 to 8 percent in April 2014 (with a second stage envisaged raising it to 10 percent in October 2015). The bill to raise the tax had been passed under the previous DPJ government, but the final decision lay with the Prime Minister. He and Finance Minister Tar\u014d As\u014d explained that the tax would be increased to provide a \"sustainable\" basis for future social spending, and to avoid the need to finance future stimulus by issuing government bonds. While this was expected to affect economic growth in the quarter following the rise, Abe also announced a 5 trillion yen stimulus package that aimed to mitigate any effects on economic revival.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2013-10-01/abe-proceeds-with-japan-s-first-sales-tax-increase-since-1997|title=Abe Orders Japan's First Sales-Tax Increase Since '97: Economy|work=Bloomberg|accessdate=27 December 2015}}</ref> After the increase in April, Japan fell into recession during the second and third quarters of 2014, leading to Abe delaying the second stage of the tax rise until April 2017 and calling a [[2014 Japanese general election|snap election]] (see below).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/business-30077122|title=Japan's economy makes surprise fall into recession|date=17 November 2014|work=BBC News|accessdate=27 December 2015}}</ref> In response to the recession, Aso announced that the government would ask the Diet to pass a supplementary budget to fund a further stimulus package worth 2\u20133 trillion yen.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-japan-economy-aso-tax-idUSKCN0J205520141118|title=Japan's Aso signals tax hike delay, says must not happen again|date=17 November 2014|work=Reuters|accessdate=27 December 2015}}</ref>\n\nThere has been some division within the Abe cabinet between \"fiscal hawks\", such as Finance Minister Aso, who favor fiscal consolidation through spending cuts and tax increases, and reflationists, such as Abe himself, who argue in favor of a \"growth first\" policy that prioritises economic expansion and recovery over budget considerations using the slogan \"no fiscal health without economic revitalization\".<ref name=\"Abe's Growth-First Fiscal Policy\">{{cite web|url=http://www.nippon.com/en/column/g00310/|title=Abe's Growth-First Fiscal Policy|date=9 September 2015|work=Nippon.com|accessdate=27 December 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-japan-economy-tax-idUSBRE9890D020130910|title=Japan PM Abe moves toward tax hike, orders economic stimulus|date=10 September 2013|work=Reuters|accessdate=27 December 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/abe-adviser-warns-against-further-japan-sales-tax-increase-1410184009|title=Abe Adviser Warns Against Further Japan Sales-Tax Increase|date=8 September 2014|work=The Wall Street Journal|accessdate=27 December 2015}}</ref> Abe's decision to delay the consumption tax increase in November 2014 and his push for a large fiscal deficit in the 2015 budget without social security cuts was interpreted as a victory for this faction within the LDP. The government did however, commit to a primary surplus by 2020, and pledged to review its strategy in 2018 if the primary deficit had not fallen to 1 percent of GDP by that time.<ref name=\"Abe's Growth-First Fiscal Policy\"/>\n\n====\"Third Arrow\": Growth strategy and structural reform====\nOn 15 March 2013 Abe announced that Japan was entering negotiations to join the [[Trans-Pacific Partnership]], this was interpreted by analysts as a means through which the government can enact reforms to liberalise certain sectors of the Japanese economy, most notably agriculture, and was criticised by farm lobbies and some sections of the LDP.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/business-21799683|title=Japan seeks to join TPP free trade talks|work=BBC News|accessdate=27 December 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.japantimes.co.jp/news/2013/03/16/business/abe-declares-japan-will-join-tpp-free-trade-process/|title=Abe declares Japan will join TPP free-trade process|work=The Japan Times|accessdate=27 December 2015}}</ref> Economist Yoshizaki Tatsuhiko described the TPP as having the potential to act as the \"linchpin of Abe's economic revitalization strategy\" by making Japan more competitive through free trade.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nippon.com/en/in-depth/a02002/|title=What the TPP Process Means to Japan|work=Nippon.com|accessdate=27 December 2015}}</ref> In February 2015 the Abe government struck a deal to limit the power of the [[Central Union of Agricultural Cooperatives|JA-Zenchu]] body to supervise and audit Japan's agricultural co-operatives, in a move designed to facilitate TPP negotiations, improve the competitiveness of Japan's farming sector and curtail the influence of the agriculture lobby.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://thediplomat.com/2015/02/agricultural-reforms-in-japan-pave-the-way-for-tpp/|title=Agricultural Reforms in Japan Pave the Way for TPP|work=The Diplomat|accessdate=27 December 2015}}</ref>\n\nAbe revealed the first measures related to the \"third arrow\" policies in June 2013, which included plans to establish [[Special economic zone|deregulated economic zones]] and allow the sale of drugs online, but did not include substantial measures related to labor market or business reform.<ref>{{cite speech |title=On the Third Round of Policies under the Growth Strategy |author=Abe, Shinzo |date=5 June 2013 |location=Research Institute of Japan |url=http://japan.kantei.go.jp/96_abe/statement/201306/05speech_e.html |access-date=27 December 2015 }}</ref> These measures were less well received than the first two arrows had been since Abe took office, with the stock market falling slightly and critics arguing that they lacked detail, [[The Economist]], for example judged the announcement a \"misfire\".<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.economist.com/news/asia/21579514-shinzo-abe-disappoints-timid-attempt-structural-reform-misfire|title=Misfire The third arrow of Abenomics|work=The Economist|accessdate=27 December 2015}}</ref> Analysts did note, however, that Abe was waiting until after the July Upper House elections to reveal further details, to avoid an adverse reaction by voters to potentially unpopular reforms.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.euromoney.com/Article/3219009/Japan-shadow-boxes-with-structural-reform-imperative.html|title=Japan shadow boxes with structural reform imperative|work=Euromoney|accessdate=27 December 2015}}</ref> At the annual meeting of the [[World Economic Forum]] in Davos in 2014 Abe announced that he was ready to act as a \"drill bit\" to break through the rock of vested interests and \"red tape\" to achieve structural reforms of the economy. He cited reforms of agriculture, energy and health sectors as evidence of this, and pledged to push forward with the TPP, a Japan-EU trade deal and tax, corporate governance and planning reforms.<ref>{{cite speech |title=A New Vision from a New Japan |author=Abe, Shinzo |date=22 January 2014 |location=World Economic Forum, Davos |url=http://japan.kantei.go.jp/96_abe/statement/201401/22speech_e.html |access-date=27 December 2015 }}</ref>\n\nAbe announced a package of structural reforms in June 2014, that the Economist described as \"less a single arrow than a 1,000-strong bundle\" and compared favorably to the 2013 announcement. These new measures included corporate governance reform, the easing of restrictions on hiring foreign staff in special economic zones, liberalising the health sector and measures to help foreign and local entrepreneurs.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.economist.com/news/leaders/21605905-shinzo-abe-has-best-chance-decades-changing-japan-better-he-seems-poised|title=Reform in Japan The third arrow|work=The Economist|accessdate=27 December 2015}}</ref> The plans also included a cut in corporation tax to below 30 percent, an expansion of childcare to encourage women to join the workforce, and the loosening of restrictions on overtime.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2014/jun/24/shinzo-abe-japan-economic-reform-corporation-tax|title=Shinzo Abe launches 'third arrow' of Japanese economic reform |work=The Guardian|accessdate=27 December 2015}}</ref> In December 2015, the government announced corporation tax would be reduced to 29.97 percent in 2016, bringing the cut forward one year ahead of schedule.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-japan-economy-tax-idUSKBN0TV02D20151212|title=Japan to cut corporate tax rate to 29.74 percent in two stages: sources|work=Reuters|accessdate=27 December 2015}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Amari Akira 1-3.jpg|upright|thumb|[[Akira Amari]], who served as Abe's economy minister from 2012 to 2016, oversaw the \"third arrow\" growth strategy and negotiations to join the Trans-Pacific Partnership agreement]]\nIn September 2013 Abe called for a \"society in which all women can shine\", setting a target that 30 percent of leadership positions should be held by women by 2020. Abe cited the \"womenomics\" ideas of [[Kathy Matsui]] that greater participation by women in the workforce, which is relatively low in Japan, especially in leadership roles, could improve Japan's GDP and potentially fertility rates, in spite of declining population figures. The Abe cabinet has introduced measures to expand childcare and legislation to force public and private organizations to publish data on the number of women they employ, and what positions they hold.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB10001424052702303759604579091680931293404|title=Shinzo Abe: Unleashing the Power of 'Womenomics'|work=The Wall Street Journal|accessdate=27 December 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.eastasiaforum.org/2015/08/27/is-abes-womenomics-working/|title=Is Abe's womenomics working?|work=East Asia Forum|accessdate=27 December 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/finance/economics/11071000/Three-reasons-why-Shinzo-Abe-thinks-women-will-save-Japans-economy.html|title=Three reasons why Shinzo Abe thinks women will save Japan's economy|work=The Telegraph|accessdate=27 December 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn November 2013 the Abe cabinet passed a bill to liberalise Japan's electricity market by abolishing price controls, breaking up regional monopolies, separating power transmission from generation by creating a national grid company. This move was partly in response to the [[Fukushima Daiichi nuclear disaster|2011 Fukushima disaster]], and the bill faced little opposition in the Diet.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-japan-power-deregulation-idUSBRE9AC08N20131113|title=Japan passes law to launch reform of electricity sector|work=Reuters|accessdate=27 December 2015}}</ref> By March 2015, more than 500 companies had applied to the [[Ministry of Economy, Trade and Industry (Japan)|Economy Ministry]] to enter the electricity retail market and electricity industry is expected to be fully liberalised by 2016, with gas utilities following suit by 2017.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ft.com/cms/s/2/ac713e7a-cbd1-11e4-beca-00144feab7de.html#axzz3vTXuVdiV|title=Energy deregulation threatens to break up Japanese monopolies|work=Financial Times|accessdate=27 December 2015}}</ref> Abe has also said he favors the re-building of Japan's nuclear reactors following the Fukushima disaster (though much of the authority to restart nuclear plants lies with local governments) and plans to strengthen relations with the United States.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2012/12/31/world/asia/japans-new-prime-minister-backs-more-nuclear-plants.html|title=Japan's New Leader Endorses Nuclear Plants|work=The New York Times|date=30 December 2012}}</ref>\n\nIn 2013 the Eurekahedge Japan Hedge Fund Index posted a record 28 percent return, which was credited to the unprecedented actions of the Abe government.<ref>{{cite news|title=Lotus Peak Plans Abenomics Fund of Hedge Funds to Capture Demand|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/2014-01-27/lotus-peak-plans-abenomics-fund-of-hedge-funds-to-capture-demand.html|accessdate=27 January 2014|newspaper=Bloomberg News|date=27 January 2014|author=Tomoko Yamazaki|author2=Komaki Ito|quote=The Eurekahedge Japan Hedge Fund Index returned a record 28 percent in 2013 as Abe boosted spending and the Bank of Japan embarked on an unprecedented monetary easing, an approach dubbed Abenomics.}}</ref> In July 2015 the IMF reported that, while the structural reforms had \"modestly\" improved growth prospects, \"further high-impact structural reforms are needed to lift growth\" and prevent over-reliance on yen depreciation.<ref>{{cite press release |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title=IMF Executive Board Concludes 2015 Article IV Consultation with Japan |url=http://www.imf.org/external/pubs/ft/scr/2015/cr15197.pdf |agency=IMF |date=23 July 2015 |access-date=27 December 2015}}</ref>\n\n===2013 Upper House election===\nWhen Abe returned to office, although neither party had controlled the [[House of Councillors (Japan)|House of Councillors]] (the upper house of the Diet) since the [[2007 Japanese House of Councillors election|2007 election]], the opposition DPJ was the largest party. The governing coalition enjoyed a two-thirds majority in the lower house that allowed it to override the upper house's veto, but this requires a delay of 90 days. This situation, known as the \"Twisted Diet\", had contributed to political gridlock and the \"revolving door\" of Prime Ministers since 2007.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/stephenharner/2013/05/19/japan-diet-elections/|title=Abe's 'Growth Strategy' And The Upper House Election|work=Forbes|accessdate=27 December 2015}}</ref> Abe's campaign for the 2013 election focused on themes of economic revival, asking voters to give him a stable mandate in both houses to pursue reforms, and took a more moderate tone on defense and constitutional matters.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2013/07/22/world/asia/governing-party-appears-headed-to-lead-japanese-parliament.html?_r=0&pagewanted=all|title=Election Win by Ruling Party Signals Change in Japan|work=The New York Times|accessdate=27 December 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-asia-23396234|title=Japan election: Abe 'wins key upper house vote'|work=BBC News|accessdate=27 December 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn the [[2013 Japanese House of Councillors election|July 2013 upper house election]], the LDP emerged as the largest party with 115 seats (a gain of 31) and the Komeito with 20 (a gain of 1), giving Abe's coalition control of both houses of the Diet, but not the two-thirds majority in the upper house that would allow for constitutional revision.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nippon.com/en/features/h00035/|title=2013 House of Councillors Election Results at a Glance|work=Nippon.com|accessdate=27 December 2015}}</ref> With no national elections due until 2016, this result was described as giving Abe the opportunity of \"three golden years\" of parliamentary stability in which to implement his policies.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.japanpolicyforum.jp/archives/politics/pt20131001233557.html|title=The Prime Minister's Challenges During His Three Golden Years|work=Japan Foreign Policy Forum|accessdate=27 December 2015}}</ref>\n\n===Domestic policy===\n\n====Education====\nAbe's return to the Prime Ministership saw a renewed attempt to downplay Japan's wartime atrocities in school textbooks, an issue that had contributed to his earlier downfall.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2013/12/29/world/asia/japan-fights-a-political-battle-using-history-texts.html |title=In Textbook Fight, Japan Leaders Seek to Recast History |last1=FACKLER |first1=MARTIN |date=28 December 2013 |website=nytimes.com |publisher=The New York Times Company |accessdate=29 December 2013}}</ref> In 2013 Abe supported the creation of the [[Top Global University Project|Super Global Universities]] program.  This is a ten-year program to increase international student attendance in Japanese universities and hire more foreign faculty.  There is also funding for selected universities to create English-only undergraduate programs.<ref name=\"QS\">{{cite web|last=Ince |first=Martin |url=http://www.iu.qs.com/2014/05/prime-minister-abe-to-accelerate-internationalisation-of-japanese-universities/ |title=Prime Minister Abe to Accelerate Internationalisation of Japanese Universities |publisher=QS Intelligence Unit |date=2014-05-19 |accessdate=2017-04-06}}</ref><ref name=\"EAF\">{{cite web|last=Taylor |first=Veronica |url=http://www.eastasiaforum.org/2014/12/30/japanese-universities-reach-for-global-status/ |title=Japanese universities reach for global status |publisher=East Asia Forum |date=2014-12-30 |accessdate=2017-04-06}}</ref>\n\n==== Population growth ====\nIn 2014 Abe allocated millions of dollars of the fiscal budget to help programs that help single individuals of Japan find potential mates. These programs entitled \"Marriage support programs\" were started in hopes of raising Japan's declining birthrate which was half of what it was six decades prior.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Ansari|first1=Aziz|last2=Klinenberg|first2=Eric|title=Modern Romance|isbn=1594206279|page=155|year=2015}}</ref>\n\n===Foreign policy===\n[[File:Shinzo Abe with Barack Obama laughing, April 2014.jpg|thumb|Prime Minister Abe with U.S. President [[Barack Obama]] in Tokyo in April 2014]]\nShortly after taking office Abe signalled a \"drastic reshaping\" of foreign policy, and promised to pursue diplomacy with a global, rather than a regional or bilateral outlook based on \"the fundamental values of freedom, democracy, basic human rights, and the rule of law\".<ref name=\"japan.kantei.go.jp\"/> His choice of [[Fumio Kishida]] as [[Foreign Minister of Japan|foreign minister]] was interpreted as a sign that he would pursue a more moderate line compared to his hawkish stance in the run up the general election.<ref name=\"The Wall Street Journal\"/>\n\nWithin weeks of returning to power, the Second Abe cabinet faced the [[In Amenas hostage crisis]] of 2013 in which 10 Japanese citizens were killed. Abe condemned the killings as \"absolutely unforgivable\" and confirmed that Japan and Britain had co-operated over the incident.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.japantimes.co.jp/news/2013/01/20/national/politics-diplomacy/abe-confirms-cooperation-with-britain-over-algeria-hostage-crisis/|title=Abe confirms cooperation with Britain over Algeria hostage crisis|work=The Japan Times|accessdate=26 December 2015}}</ref> Abe believed that this incident demonstrated the need for the creation of a [[National Security Council (Japan)|Japanese National Security Council]] (see below), and convened a panel to consider its creation soon after the crisis.<ref>{{cite book |last=Shinoda |first=Tomohito |date=2013 |title=Contemporary Japanese Politics |location=New York |publisher=Columbia University Press |page=233 }}</ref>\n\nAbe was unusually active in the field of foreign affairs for a Japanese Prime Minister, making visits to 49 countries between December 2012 and September 2014, a number that was described as \"unprecedented\" (by contrast, his immediate two predecessors [[Naoto Kan]] and Yoshihiko Noda visited a combined total of 18 countries between June 2010 and December 2012).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dw.com/en/shinzo-abes-unprecedented-international-agenda/a-17914443|title=Shinzo Abe's 'unprecedented' international agenda|work=Deutsche Welle|accessdate=28 December 2015}}</ref> This was interpreted as a means to offset poor relations with China and Korea by increasing Japan's profile on the world stage and improving bilateral ties with other countries in the region. South East Asian nations, Australia and India have been significant and frequent destinations for Abe, who visited all 10 [[Association of Southeast Asian Nations|ASEAN]] countries in his first year in office. The diplomatic tours also functioned as another element of Abenomics by promoting Japan to the international business community and opening up avenues for trade, energy and defense procurement deals (for example, business executives often travel with Abe on these visits).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://thediplomat.com/2014/09/shinzo-abe-has-visited-a-quarter-of-the-worlds-countries-in-20-months-why/|title=Shinzo Abe Has Visited a Quarter of the World's Countries in 20 Months: Why?|work=The Diplomat|accessdate=28 December 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/asia_pacific/japans-abe-looks-for-friends-abroad-as-popularity-wanes-at-home/2014/08/04/a8e9e4de-26a4-482a-9297-62c211db299a_story.html|title=Japan's Abe looks for friends abroad as popularity wanes at home|work=The Washington Post|accessdate=28 December 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn September 2013, Abe intervened to aid [[Tokyo bid for the 2020 Summer Olympics|Tokyo's bid]] to host the [[2020 Summer Olympics|2020 Summer Olympic and Paralympic games]], giving a speech in English at the [[125th IOC Session|IOC session in Buenos Aires]], in which he extolled the role of sport in Japan and sought to reassure the committee that any ongoing issues with the [[Fukushima Daiichi Nuclear Power Plant|Fukushima plant]] were under control.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/olympics/24006629|title=Olympics 2020: Why Tokyo is a 'safe pair of hands' to host Games|date=8 September 2013|work=BBC News|accessdate=29 December 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-olympics-2020-japan-idUSBRE98806P20130909|title=Japan Olympic win boosts Abe, but Fukushima shadows linger|date=9 September 2013|work=Reuters|accessdate=29 December 2015}}</ref> After the bid was successful, Abe sought to portray the games as symbolic of his Abenomics economic revitalization programme, saying \"I want to make the Olympics a trigger for sweeping away 15 years of deflation and economic decline\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ft.com/cms/s/0/d6142984-194b-11e3-83b9-00144feab7de.html#axzz3vjrkw45g|title=Shinzo Abe to write revival story for Japan with Olympics|date=10 September 2013|work=Financial Times|accessdate=29 December 2015}}</ref> In 2014 he said that he hoped a \"robot olympics\" would be held at the same time, to promote the robotics industry.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/asia/japan/10913610/Japans-PM-plans-2020-Robot-Olympics.html|title=Japan's PM plans 2020 Robot Olympics|date=10 June 2014|work=The Telegraph|accessdate=29 December 2015}}</ref>\n\nAbe's foreign policy has moved Japan away from its traditional focus on the \"big three\" bilateral relationships with the United States, China, and South Korea, and has sought to increase Japan's international profile by expanding ties with NATO, the EU, and other organizations beyond the Asia-Pacific region.<ref name=\"The ASAN Forum\">{{cite web|url=http://www.theasanforum.org/the-foreign-policy-of-abe-shinzo-strategic-vision-and-policy-implementation/|title=The Foreign Policy of Abe Shinzo: Strategic Vision and Policy Implementation|date=5 February 2015|work=The ASAN Forum|accessdate=29 December 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite speech |title=Japan's Political Outlook for 2016 |author=Cucek, Prof. Michael |date=17 December 2015 |location=Foreign Correspondents' Club of Japan |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=jYF2s9huQHE|quote=YouTube title: Michael Thomas Cucek: Japan's Political Outlook for 2016, at time: 1:02:12|access-date=29 December 2015 }}</ref> In 2014, Abe and British Prime Minister [[David Cameron]] agreed to establish a \"2 + 2 framework\" of annual consultations between the British and Japanese foreign and defense ministries, with Abe calling for greater co-operation on issues \"from peace of the seas to the security of the skies, space and cyberspace\". This followed a similar agreement with French ministers in Tokyo earlier in the year.<ref name=\"The ASAN Forum\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.japantimes.co.jp/news/2014/05/02/national/politics-diplomacy/abe-cameron-agree-boost-japan-britain-security-cooperation/|title=Abe, Cameron agree to boost Japan-Britain security cooperation|date=2 May 2014|work=The Japan Times|accessdate=29 December 2015}}</ref>\n\nAbe concluded the [[Japan\u2013Australia Economic Partnership Agreement]] with Australia's [[Abbott Government]] in 2014, and addressed a joint sitting of the Australian Parliament in July.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/2014-07-08/australia2c-japan-to-sign-economic-partnership-agreement/5580738|title=Japan's prime minister Shinzo Abe addresses Federal Parliament, signs free trade deal with Australia|first=Latika|last=Bourke|author-link=Latika Bourke|publisher=Australian Broadcasting Commission|date=8 July 2014|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160201202111/http://www.abc.net.au/news/2014-07-08/australia2c-japan-to-sign-economic-partnership-agreement/5580738|archivedate=1 February 2016}}</ref> In heralding the agreement, he also offered condolences for the suffering of Australians during World War Two \u2013 singling out the [[Kokoda Track campaign]] and [[Sandakan Death Marches]].<ref>[https://www.smh.com.au/national/shinzo-abes-condolences-for-those-lost-at-sandakan-a-horror-from-the-past-a-moment-to-stop-time-20140708-3bl5x.html Shinzo Abe's condolences for those lost at Sandakan: a horror from the past, a moment to stop time]; by Tony Wright; Sydney Morning Herald; 9 July 2014</ref>\nHe was the first Japanese PM to address the Australian parliament.<ref>''The Guardian'' [https://www.theguardian.com/world/2014/jul/08/japans-pm-offers-sincere-condolences-for-horrors-of-second-world-war \"Japan's PM offers 'sincere condolences' for horrors of second world war\"] 8 July 2014. Retrieved 10 March 2015</ref>\n\n[[File:Macri and Abe.jpg|thumb|Abe with Argentine President, [[Mauricio Macri]], [[Buenos Aires]], 21 November 2016]]\n\nIn January 2014, Abe became the first Japanese leader to attend India's [[Delhi Republic Day parade|Republic Day Parade]] in Delhi as [[List of state visits to India#Republic Day Parade Guests|chief guest]], during a three-day visit where he and Prime Minister [[Manmohan Singh]] agreed to increase co-operation over economic, defense and security issues and signed trade agreements related to energy, tourism and telecoms.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/india/Shinzo-Abe-first-Japanese-premier-at-Republic-Day-celebrations/articleshow/29401937.cms|title=Shinzo Abe first Japanese premier at Republic Day celebrations|date=26 January 2014|work=The Times of India|accessdate=28 December 2015}}</ref> A close relationship was anticipated between Abe and Narendra Modi after the latter's election as [[Prime Minister of India]] in May 2014, when it was noted that they had established ties from at least seven years previously when Modi was still [[Chief Minister of Gujarat]] and that Modi was one of three people Abe \"followed\" on [[Twitter]]. The two men exchanged congratulatory messages after the election.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://in.reuters.com/article/india-modi-abe-twitter-idINKBN0E11O820140521|title=Twitter friendship blossoms for Asian nationalists Modi and Abe|date=21 May 2014|work=Reuters|accessdate=28 December 2015}}</ref> Modi made his first major foreign visit to Japan in autumn of 2014, where he and Abe discussed agreements on nuclear co-operation, [[rare earth element]]s and joint maritime exercises.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ibtimes.com/narendra-modi-shinzo-abe-set-sign-slew-agreements-between-india-japan-1674974|title=Narendra Modi And Shinzo Abe Set To Sign Slew of Agreements Between India And Japan|date=1 September 2014|work=International Business Times|accessdate=28 December 2015}}</ref> During the visit Abe invited Modi to become the first Indian leader to stay at the Imperial State Guest House in [[Kyoto]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://america.aljazeera.com/opinions/2014/10/modi-abe-india-japanchinasecurityeconomics.html|title=Japan and India's mutual courtship|date=3 October 2014|work=Al Jazeera|accessdate=28 December 2015}}</ref>\n\nOn 30 May 2014, Abe told officials from the [[Association of Southeast Asian Nations|ASEAN]] countries, the [[United States]] and [[Australia]], that Japan wanted to play a major role in maintaining regional security, a departure from the passiveness it has displayed since World War II. He offered Japan's support to other countries in resolving territorial disputes.<ref name=\"JapanAsia\">{{cite news|title=Abe offers Japan's help in maintaining regional security|url=http://www.japanherald.com/index.php/sid/222467193/scat/c4f2dd8ca8c78044/ht/Abe-offers-Japans-help-in-maintaining-regional-security|accessdate=31 May 2014|work=Japan Herald|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140531184828/http://www.japanherald.com/index.php/sid/222467193/scat/c4f2dd8ca8c78044/ht/Abe-offers-Japans-help-in-maintaining-regional-security|archive-date=31 May 2014|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nRelations between Japan and its immediate neighbors, China and South Korea, remained poor after Abe's return to office. While he declared that the \"doors are always open on my side\", no bilateral meetings between Abe and the Chinese leadership took place for the first 23 months of his second term.<ref name=\"csis.org\"/><ref name=\"The Japan Times\"/> Neither did Abe hold any meetings with President [[Park Geun-hye]] of Korea during his 2012\u201314 term of office.<ref name=\"The Guardian\">{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2015/nov/02/japan-south-korea-summit-thaw-in-relations|title=Japan and South Korea summit signals thaw in relations|date=2 November 2015|work=The Guardian|accessdate=29 December 2015}}</ref> Both countries criticised Abe's [[Controversies surrounding Yasukuni Shrine#Shinzo Abe|visit to Yasukuni Shrine]] in December 2013, with China's Foreign Minister describing the action as moving Japan in an \"extremely dangerous\" direction.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/asia/japan-pm-infuriates-china-and-south-korea-after-visiting-yasukuni-shrine-to-honour-war-dead-9025859.html|title=South Korea and China angered by Japanese PM Shinzo Abe's visit to controversial shrine to war dead|date=26 December 2013|work=Reuters|accessdate=29 December 2015}}</ref> In addition, China has continued to criticise Abe's defense reform policies, warning that Japan should not abandon its post-war policy of pacifism.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.eastasiaforum.org/2014/07/27/china-responds-to-japans-constitutional-reinterpretation/|title=China's response to Japan's constitutional reinterpretation|date=27 July 2014|work=East Asia Forum|accessdate=29 December 2015}}</ref> Abe's speech at the World Economic Forum in 2014 was interpreted as a criticism of Chinese foreign and defense policy when he said that \"the dividends of growth in Asia must not be wasted on military expansion\" and called for greater preservation of the [[freedom of the seas]] under the [[rule of law]], although he did not specifically refer to any one country during his remarks.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-asia-25851960|title=Japanese PM Shinzo Abe urges Asia military restraint|date=22 January 2014|work=BBC News|accessdate=29 December 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://thediplomat.com/2014/01/shinzo-abe-at-world-economic-forum-restrain-military-expansion-in-asia/|title=Shinzo Abe at World Economic Forum: 'Restrain Military Expansion in Asia'|date=23 January 2014|work=The Diplomat|accessdate=29 December 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn November 2014, Abe met China's President [[Xi Jinping]] at the [[APEC China 2014|APEC meeting in Beijing]] for the first time since either had taken office, after a photocall that was described as \"awkward\" by the press. Abe later told reporters that during the meeting he suggested establishing a hotline between Tokyo and Beijing to help resolve any maritime clashes, and that the \"first step\" had been taken to improve relations.<ref name=\"The Japan Times\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2014/nov/10/xi-jinping-shinzo-abe-ice-breaking-meeting-apec-starts|title=Japan's Abe and China's Xi hold ice-breaking meeting as Apec starts|date=10 November 2014|work=The Guardian|accessdate=29 December 2015}}</ref>\n\n===Defense and security policy===\nAbe has attempted to centralize security policy in the Prime Minister's office by creating the [[National Security Council (Japan)|Japanese National Security Council]] to better coordinate national security policy, and by ordering the first National Security Strategy in Japan's history.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://thediplomat.com/2014/01/how-will-japans-new-nsc-work/|title=How Will Japan's New NSC Work?|author=J. Berkshire Miller|date=29 January 2014|work=The Diplomat|accessdate=4 February 2014}}</ref> Based on the [[United States National Security Council|American body of the same name]], the law to create the NSC was passed in November 2013 and began operating the following month when Abe appointed [[Shotaro Yachi]] as Japan's first National Security Advisor.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://ajw.asahi.com/article/behind_news/politics/AJ201401080046|title=New national security bureau faces rocky start|author=Katsuhisa Kuramae|date=8 January 2014|work=The Asahi Shimbun|accessdate=28 December 2015|url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140125104958/http://ajw.asahi.com/article/behind_news/politics/AJ201401080046|archivedate=25 January 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn December 2013, Abe announced a five-year plan of military expansion. He described this as \"proactive pacificism\", with the goal of making Japan a more \"normal\" country, able to defend itself. This was in reaction to a Chinese buildup and a decreased American influence in the region.<ref>[https://www.nytimes.com/2013/12/18/world/asia/japan-moves-to-strengthen-military-amid-rivalry-with-china.html?src=recg Japan moves to strengthen military] ''New York Times'', retrieved 25 December 2013.</ref>\n\nIn the same month the Diet passed the Abe cabinet's [[State Secrecy Law]], which took effect in December 2014.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://thediplomat.com/2014/12/japans-troubling-state-secrets-law-takes-effect/|title=Japan's Troubling State Secrets Law Takes Effect|date=18 December 2014|work=The Diplomat|accessdate=28 December 2015}}</ref> The law expanded the scope for the government to designate what information constitutes a state secret and increased penalties for bureaucurats and journalists who leak such information to up to 10 years in prison and a 10 million yen fine. The passage of the law proved controversial, with thousands protesting the bill in Tokyo and the cabinet's approval rating falling below 50 percent for the first time in some polls. Detractors argued that the law was ambiguous and therefore gave the government too much freedom to decide which information to classify, that it could curtail freedom of the press, and that the cabinet had rushed the legislation without including any corresponding freedom of information guarantees.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2013-12-06/japan-s-abe-seeks-to-pass-secrecy-bill-that-sapped-popularity|title=Japan's Abe Secures Passage of Secrecy Law as Opposition Revolts |date=6 December 2013|work=Bloomberg|accessdate=28 December 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://thediplomat.com/2013/11/japans-state-secrets-bill-polarizes-society/ |title=Japan's State Secrets Bill Polarizes Society |date=28 November 2013|work=The Diplomat|accessdate=28 December 2015}}</ref> Abe argued that the law was necessary and applied only in cases of national security, diplomacy, public safety and counter-terrorism, saying, \"If the law prevents films from being made, or weakens freedom of the press, I'll resign\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2014/dec/10/japan-state-secrets-law-security-dissent|title=Abe defends Japan's secrets law that could jail whistleblowers for 10 years |date=10 December 2013|work=The Guardian|accessdate=28 December 2015}}</ref> However he did concede that, in retrospect, the government should have explained the details of the bill more carefully to the public.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.economist.com/news/asia/21591627-unpopular-new-secrecy-law-dents-prime-ministers-popularity-potent-protests |title=Potent Protests|date=14 December 2013|work=The Economist|accessdate=28 December 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn July 2014 the Abe cabinet took the decision to re-interpret [[Constitution of Japan|Japan's constitution]] to allow for the right of \"Collective Self-Defense\". This would allow the [[Japan Self-Defense Forces|Self Defense Forces]] to come to the aid of, and defend, an ally under attack, whereas the previous interpretation of the constitution was strictly pacifist and allowed for force to be used only in absolute self-defense.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-asia-28086002|title=Japan cabinet approves landmark military change |date=1 July 2014|publisher=BBC News|accessdate=28 December 2015}}</ref> The decision was supported by the United States, which has argued for greater scope for action by Japan as a regional ally, and led to a revision of the U.S.-Japan defense cooperation guidelines in 2015.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://blogs.cfr.org/asia/2014/07/02/reinterpreting-japans-constitution/ |title=Reinterpreting Japan's Constitution|date=2 July 2014|work=Council on Foreign Relations|accessdate=28 December 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://thediplomat.com/2015/04/us-japan-agree-to-new-defense-guidelines/|title=US, Japan Agree to New Defense Guidelines |date=28 April 2015|work=The Diplomat|accessdate=28 December 2015}}</ref> In response the [[Ministry of Foreign Affairs of the People's Republic of China|Chinese Foreign Ministry]] said the decision \"raised doubts\" about Japan's commitment to peace, and argued that the Japanese public is opposed to the concept of collective self-defense.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.eastasiaforum.org/2014/07/27/china-responds-to-japans-constitutional-reinterpretation/|title=China's response to Japan's constitutional reinterpretation|date=27 July 2014|work=East Asia Forum|accessdate=28 December 2015}}</ref> Abe argued that the move would not lead to Japan becoming involved in \"foreign wars\" such as the [[Gulf War|Gulf]] or [[Iraq War]], but instead would secure peace through deterrence.<ref>{{cite speech |title=Press Conference by Prime Minister Abe |author=Abe, Shinzo |date=1 July 2014 |location=Kantei, Tokyo |url=http://japan.kantei.go.jp/96_abe/statement/201407/0701kaiken.html |access-date=28 December 2015 }}</ref> This led to the introduction of the 2015 security legislation to give legal effect to the cabinet's decision (see below).\n\n===2014 cabinet reshuffle===\nThe cabinet inaugurated in December 2012 was the longest serving and most stable in post-war Japanese history, lasting 617 days without a change in personnel until Abe conducted a reshuffle in September 2014, with the stated aim of promoting more women into ministerial posts. The reshuffled cabinet tied the record of 5 women ministers set by the first Koizumi cabinet. Most key figures, such as Deputy Prime Minister Aso and Chief Cabinet Secretary Suga, were kept in post although Abe moved Justice Minister Sadakazu Tanigaki out of cabinet to become Secretary General of the LDP.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.japantimes.co.jp/news/2014/09/03/national/politics-diplomacy/abe-boosts-number-of-women-in-cabinet-but-retains-key-figures-in-reshuffle-2/|title=Abe keeps core intact in Cabinet shake-up|date=3 September 2014|work=Japan Times|accessdate=25 December 2015}}</ref> However, on 20 October two of the women promoted in the reshuffe, Justice Minister [[Midori Matsushima]] and Trade Minister [[Y\u016bko Obuchi]], were forced to resign in separate election finance scandals. Abe told the press, \"As prime minister, I bear full responsibility for having appointed them, and I apologize deeply to the people of Japan.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nippon.com/en/genre/politics/l00071/|title=Abe Cabinet Rocked by Double Resignation|date=20 October 2014|work=Nippon.com|accessdate=26 December 2015}}</ref>\n\n===2014 general election===\n[[File:Japanese Prime Minister Abe Shinzo - Akihabara - Dec 13 2014.ogv|thumb|thumbtime=2|(video) Prime Minister Abe giving a speech in front of the Gundam Cafe in [[Akihabara]], 2014]]\nIn November 2014, while Abe was attending the APEC forum meeting in China and the G20 Summit in Australia, rumours began appearing in the press that he was planning to call a snap election in the event that he decided to delay the second stage of the consumption tax increase.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-japan-politics-election-idUSKBN0IT03R20141109|title=Japan PM Abe considers sales tax hike delay, snap election -media|date=9 November 2014|work=Reuters|accessdate=26 December 2015}}</ref> It was speculated that Abe planned to do this to \"reset\" Diet business after it had become gridlocked due to the fallout from ministerial resignations in October, or because the political situation would be less favorable to re-election in 2015 and 2016.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mainichi.jp/english/english/perspectives/news/20141112p2a00m0na013000c.html |title=Abe looks to 'reset' parliamentary gridlock |date=12 November 2014 |work=Mainichi |accessdate=26 December 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141116065502/http://mainichi.jp/english/english/perspectives/news/20141112p2a00m0na013000c.html |archivedate=16 November 2014 }}</ref>\n\nOn 17 November GDP figures were released that showed Japan had fallen into recession, the two-quarters of negative growth following the first stage in the consumption tax rise in April.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/business-30077122|title=Japan's economy makes surprise fall into recession|date=17 November 2014|work=BBC News|accessdate=26 December 2015}}</ref> Abe held a press conference on 21 November and announced that he was delaying the rise in the consumption tax by 18 months, from October 2015 to April 2017, and calling a snap general election for 14 December. Abe described the election as the \"Abenomics Dissolution\" and asked the voters to pass judgement on his economic policies.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://japan.kantei.go.jp/96_abe/statement/201411/1121kaiken.html |title=Press Conference by Prime Minister Abe |publisher=Kantei |date=2014-11-21 |accessdate=2017-04-06}}</ref> Abe's popularity fell slightly with the announcement and he declared that he would resign if his coalition did not win a simple majority, though analysts agreed this was highly unlikely due to the weak state of the opposition.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://uk.reuters.com/article/uk-japan-election-dissolution-idUKKCN0J509F20141121|title=Japan PM seeks verdict on 'Abenomics' in snap election|date=21 November 2014|work=Reuters|accessdate=26 December 2015}}</ref> The opposition parties attempted to field a united front in opposition to Abe's policies, but found themselves divided on them.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://ajw.asahi.com/article/behind_news/politics/AJ201411220031 |title=Opposition parties seek unity, find disarray, ahead of election campaign |date=22 November 2014 |website=ajw.asahi.com |publisher=THE ASAHI SHIMBUN |accessdate=22 November 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141230190907/http://ajw.asahi.com/article/behind_news/politics/AJ201411220031 |archivedate=30 December 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn the elections, the LDP won 291 seats, a loss of 3, but the Komeito gained 4 to win 35. Therefore, the governing coalition maintained its two-thirds majority in a slightly-reduced lower house of 475.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.japantimes.co.jp/news/2014/12/15/national/politics-diplomacy/abes-snap-election-pays-big-win/#.Vn4aaU-REWg|title=Abe tightens grip on power as ruling coalition wins 325 seats in Lower House election|date=15 December 2014|work=Japan Times|accessdate=26 December 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Third term as prime minister (2014\u20132017)==\n[[File:2nd and 3rd Abe Cabinet Approval Disapproval Ratings.png|350px|thumb|right|Abe Cabinet Approval Ratings since December 2012]]\nOn 24 December 2014 Abe was re-elected to the position of Prime Minister by the House of Representatives. The only change he made when introducing his third cabinet was replacing defense minister [[Akinori Eto]], who was also involved in a political funding controversy, with [[Gen Nakatani]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-asia-30595376|title=Shinzo Abe re-elected as Japan's prime minister|date=24 December 2014|work=BBC News|accessdate=26 December 2015}}</ref> In his February policy speech, as the Cabinet weathered a [[Moritomo Gakuen]] school scandal, Abe called upon the new Diet to enact \"most drastic reforms since the end of World War II\" in the areas of the economy, agriculture, healthcare and other sectors.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://thediplomat.com/2015/02/japanese-pm-abe-urges-most-drastic-reforms-since-ww2/|title=Japanese PM Abe Urges Most Drastic Reforms Since WW2|date=18 February 2015|work=The Diplomat|accessdate=28 December 2015}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.japantimes.co.jp/news/2017/03/13/reference/abe-stands-ground-moritomo-gakuen-scandal-drags/|title=Abe stands his ground as Moritomo Gakuen scandal drags on|date=2017-03-13|website=The Japan Times|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170317171255/http://www.japantimes.co.jp/news/2017/03/13/reference/abe-stands-ground-moritomo-gakuen-scandal-drags/|archive-date=2017-03-17|url-status=|access-date=2017-03-27}}</ref>\n\n===Foreign policy===\n[[File:Obama & Abe Review Troops 2015.jpg|thumb|Abe and U.S. President [[Barack Obama]] review troops during the former's visit to [[Washington, D.C.]], in April 2015]]\nOn a tour of the Middle East in January 2015, Abe announced that Japan would provide 200 million dollars in non-military assistance to countries fighting against the [[Islamic State of Iraq and the Levant]] as part of a 2.5 billion dollar aid package.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://in.reuters.com/article/mideast-crisis-japan-idINKBN0KQ07520150117|title=Japan's Abe pledges support for Mideast countries battling Islamic State|date=17 January 2015|publisher=Reuters|accessdate=29 December 2015}}</ref> Shortly after this, ISIL released a video in which a masked figure (identified as Mohammed Emwazi or \"[[Jihadi John]]\") threatened to kill two Japanese hostages, [[Kenji Goto]] and Haruna Yukawa, in retaliation for the move unless Abe's government paid 200 million dollars of ransom money. Abe cut short his trip to deal with the crisis, declared that such acts of terrorism were \"unforgivable\" and promised to save the hostages, while refusing to pay the ransom.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-middle-east-30893735|title=Japan PM Shinzo Abe in Islamic State 'hostages' vow|date=20 January 2015|publisher=BBC News|accessdate=29 December 2015}}</ref> The Abe cabinet worked with the Jordanian government to attempt to secure the release of both hostages, after further videos were released by ISIL linking their fate to that of pilot [[Muath Al-Kasasbeh]], with deputy foreign minister [[Yasuhide Nakayama]] conducting negotiations in [[Amman]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.sky.com/story/1418955/japan-will-never-forgive-is-hostage-murder|title=Japan Will 'Never Forgive' IS Hostage Murder|date=1 February 2015|publisher=Sky News|accessdate=29 December 2015}}</ref> Both hostages were killed, ISIL releasing news of Yukawa's death on 24 January and Goto's on 31 January. Abe condemned the killings as a \"heinous act\", declared that Japan would \"not give in to terrorism\" and pledged to work with the international community to bring the killers to justice.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-middle-east-31075769|title=Japan outraged at IS 'beheading' of hostage Kenji Goto|date=1 February 2015|publisher=BBC News|accessdate=29 December 2015}}</ref> There was some criticism of Abe for his move to pledge aid against ISIL while they were holding Japanese citizens hostage, but polls showed support for his administration increasing in the aftermath of the crisis.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-japan-politics-abe-idUSKBN0LC05N20150208|title=PM Abe's approval ratings rise in Japan after hostage crisis|date=1 February 2015|publisher=Reuters|accessdate=29 December 2015}}</ref> He later used the example of the hostage crisis to argue the case for the collective self-defense legislation that his government introduced in the summer of 2015 (see below).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.eastasiaforum.org/2015/04/07/how-abe-used-the-is-hostage-crisis-to-push-security-reform/|title=How Abe used the IS hostage crisis to push security reform|date=7 April 2015|publisher=East Asia Forum|accessdate=29 December 2015}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Japan-China Summit Meeting at Jakarta on April 22, 2015.jpg|left|thumb|Abe and Chinese President [[Xi Jinping]], April 2015]]\nIn April 2015, he addressed a joint sitting of the U.S. Congress, the first Japanese prime minister to do so. In his speech he referred to the Japan-US Alliance as the \"Alliance of Hope\", promised that Japan would play a more active security and defense role in the alliance and argued that the TPP would bring both economic and security benefits to the Asia-Pacific region.<ref name=\"mofa.go.jp\">[http://www.mofa.go.jp/na/na1/us/page4e_000241.html Ministry of Foreign Affairs : Address by Prime Minister Shinzo Abe to a Joint Meeting of the U.S. Congress \"Toward an Alliance of Hope\" (April 29, 2015)] Retrieved 4 May 2015</ref><ref>[https://www.nytimes.com/2015/04/30/us/politics/shinzo-abe-japan-trade-accord-speech-to-congress.html?_r=0 Shinzo Abe of Japan Avoids Specifics in Speech on Trade Accord April 29, 2015] ''[[New York Times]]'' Retrieved 4 May 2015</ref> The address served as part of a state visit to the United States, the eighth of the Obama Presidency, which the president referred to as a \"celebration of the ties of friendship\" between America and Japan. During the visit, Abe attended a state dinner at the White House.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.pbs.org/newshour/rundown/obama-welcomes-abe-white-house-high-ceremony/|title=Obama welcomes Abe to White House with high ceremony|date=28 April 2015|agency=Associated Press|accessdate=29 December 2015}}</ref>\n\nLike his predecessors [[Tomiichi Murayama]] and Junichiro Koizumi, Abe issued a statement commemorating the 70th anniversary of the end of the [[World War II]] on 14 August 2015. This statement had been widely anticipated, with some commentators expecting Abe to amend or even refuse to repeat the previous leaders' apologies for Japan's role in the war.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.eastasiaforum.org/2015/08/17/relief-surprise-and-ambiguity-in-abes-war-apology/|title=Relief, surprise and ambiguity in Abe's war apology |date=17 August 2015|publisher=East Asia Forum|accessdate=29 December 2015}}</ref> In the statement, Abe committed to uphold the previous apologies and expressed \"profound grief and eternal, sincere condolences\" for the \"immeasurable damage and suffering\" Japan had caused for \"innocent people\" during the conflict. He also argued that Japan should not be \"predestined to apologize\" forever, noting that more than eighty percent of Japanese people alive today were born after the conflict and played no part in it.<ref>{{cite speech |title=Statement by Prime Minister Shinzo Abe |author=Abe, Shinzo |date=14 August 2015 |location=Kantei, Tokyo |url=http://japan.kantei.go.jp/97_abe/statement/201508/0814statement.html|access-date=29 December 2015 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-asia-33924159|title=Japan WW2: PM Shinzo Abe expresses 'profound grief'|date=14 August 2015|publisher=BBC News|accessdate=29 December 2015}}</ref> The governments of both China and South Korea responded with criticism of the statement, but analysts noted that it was muted and restrained in tone, in comparison to the harsher rhetoric that has been used previously.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.eastasiaforum.org/2015/08/19/abes-wwii-balancing-act/|title=Abe's WWII balancing act|date=19 August 2015|publisher=East Asia Forum|accessdate=29 December 2015}}</ref> A representative of the US National Security Council welcomed the statement, and referred to Japan as having been a \"model for nations everywhere\" in its record on \"peace, democracy, and the rule of law\" since the war's end.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://uk.reuters.com/article/us-ww2-anniversary-usa-idUKKCN0QJ1OP20150814|title=U.S. welcomes Abe's statement on war anniversary|date=14 August 2015|publisher=Reuters|accessdate=29 December 2015}}</ref> Professor Gerald Curtis of Columbia University argued that the statement \"probably satisfies no constituency\" either in Japan or abroad, but that by repeating the words \"aggression\", \"colonialism\", \"apology\" and \"remorse\" used in the [[Murayama Statement]] of 1995, it was likely to be enough to improve relations with China and Korea.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.eastasiaforum.org/2015/08/20/abe-treads-a-fine-line-on-wwii/|title=Abe treads a fine line on WWII|date=20 August 2015|publisher=East Asia Forum|accessdate=29 December 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn December 2015, Abe and Indian Prime Minister Narendra Modi signed deals in which India agreed to buy ''[[Shinkansen]]'' technology from Japan (financed in part by a loan from the Japanese government), and for Japan to be raised to full partner status in the [[Exercise Malabar|Malabar naval exercises]]. Also agreed at the talks was a proposal for Japan to sell non-military nuclear technology to India, to be formally signed once technical details were finalised.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-asia-india-35068531|title=Shinzo Abe: Japan PM in India, bullet train deal on cards|date=11 December 2015|publisher=BBC News|accessdate=29 December 2015}}</ref> Demonstrating their close relationship, Abe described Modi's policies as \"like ''Shinkansen''\u2014high speed, safe and reliable while carrying many people along\". In return, Modi complimented Abe as a \"phenomenal leader\", noted how India-Japan relations had a \"wonderful human touch\" and invited him to attend the ''Ganga aarti'' ceremony at [[Dashashwamedh Ghat]] in his [[Varanasi (Lok Sabha constituency)|Varanasi]] constituency.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://news.yahoo.com/japan-build-indias-first-bullet-train-india-pm-071104329.html|title=Japan and India agree bullet train, nuclear deals|date=12 December 2015|publisher=AFP|accessdate=29 December 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.firstpost.com/world/pm-modi-calls-japan-pm-shinzo-abe-a-phenomenal-leader-2542242.html|title=Narendra Modi calls Japan PM Shinzo Abe a 'phenomenal leader'|date=11 December 2015|work=First Post|accessdate=29 December 2015}}</ref> Analysts described the nuclear deal as part of Japan and India's efforts to respond to growing Chinese power in the Asia-Pacific region.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.eastasiaforum.org/2015/12/25/the-significance-of-the-japan-india-nuclear-deal/|title=The significance of the Japan\u2013India nuclear deal|date=25 December 2015|work=First Post|accessdate=29 December 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn Seoul in November 2015, Abe attended the first [[China\u2013Japan\u2013South Korea trilateral summit]] held for three years with Korean President Park Geun-hye and Chinese Premier [[Li Keqiang]]. The summits had been suspended in 2012 due to tensions over historical and territorial issues. The leaders agreed to restore the summits as annual events, negotiate a trilateral free trade agreement and work to check [[North Korea and weapons of mass destruction|North Korea's nuclear weapons programme]], and announced that trilateral co-operation had been \"completely restored\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-china-japan-southkorea-idUSKCN0SK0L620151026|title=China, Japan, South Korea to hold first summit in three years|date=26 October 2015|publisher=Reuters|accessdate=29 December 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/11/02/world/asia/china-japan-and-south-korea-conduct-first-trilateral-meeting-in-3-years.html?_r=0|title=China, Japan and South Korea Pledge to Expand Trade at Joint Meetingl|date=1 November 2015|work=The New York Times|accessdate=29 December 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://edition.cnn.com/2015/11/01/asia/china-korea-japan-talks/|title=China, Japan and South Korea relations 'completely restored' after summit|date=3 November 2015|publisher=CNN|accessdate=29 December 2015}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Shinz\u014d Abe and Donald Trump in Washington, D. C. (1).jpeg|thumb|Abe and U.S. President [[Donald Trump]] in February 2017]]\nJapan's relations with [[South Korea]] have improved somewhat during Abe's third term, in the aftermath of Abe's war anniversary statement.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.brookings.edu/research/opinions/2015/08/18-japan-korea-relations-abe-statement-revere|title=Japan-Korea relations after Abe's war anniversary statement: Opportunity for a reset?|date=18 August 2015|publisher=Heritage Foundation|accessdate=29 December 2015}}</ref> Abe and Korea's President [[Park Geun-hye]] held their first bilateral meeting in November 2015, where they both agreed to resolve the issue of so-called \"[[Comfort women]]\" which Park described as the biggest obstacle to closer ties.<ref name=\"The Guardian\"/> In late December 2015, foreign ministers Fumio Kishida and [[Yun Byung-se]] announced in Seoul that a deal had been reached to resolve the \"comfort women\" issue, in which Japan agreed to pay 1 billion yen into a fund to support the 46 surviving victims, and issued a statement that contained Abe's \"most sincere apologies and remorse\". Abe later telephoned Park to issue the apology. In return, the South Korean government agreed to consider the matter \"finally and irreversibly resolved\" and work to remove a statue from in front of the Japanese embassy in Seoul. Both sides agreed to refrain from criticising each other over the issue in the future. President Park stated that the agreement would be a \"new starting point\" for relations between the two countries, although both leaders received some domestic criticism: Abe for issuing the apology, Park for accepting the deal.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-asia-35188135|title=Japan and South Korea agree WW2 'comfort women' deal|date=28 December 2015|publisher=BBC News|accessdate=29 December 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2015-12-28/abe-offers-apology-compensation-to-south-korean-comfort-women-|title=Abe Offers Apology, Compensation to South Korean 'Comfort Women's|date=28 December 2015|publisher=Bloomberg|accessdate=29 December 2015}}</ref>\n\nShortly after Donald Trump had won the US [[2016 United States presidential election|presidential election]], Abe cut his presence at an Asia-Pacific Economic Cooperation summit in Lima short, in order to have an informal, impromptu meeting with the then President-elect, at the [[Trump Tower]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/politics/donald-trump-election-latest-japanese-prime-minister-shinzo-abe-meeting-a7424106.html|title=Donald Trump meets with Japanese PM Shinzo Abe for first foreign meeting|date=18 November 2016|work=The Independent|accessdate=20 May 2017}}</ref> After Trump's inauguration, they had a formal meeting at Mar-a-Lago, discussed security, in light of a North Korean threat,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2017/feb/12/north-korea-shoots-missile-500km-in-show-of-force-to-trump-says-south|title=North Korea shoots missile 500&nbsp;km in 'show of force' to Trump, says South|date=12 February 2017|work=The Guardian|accessdate=20 May 2017}}</ref> with Abe stating that Japan will be more committed to [[Japan\u2013United States relations]]. They also golfed alongside South African professional golfer [[Ernie Els]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/politics/2017/02/10/donald-trump-shinzo-abe-japan/97736828/|title=Trump commits to security of Japan|date=10 February 2017|work=USA Today|accessdate=20 May 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-usa-trump-japan-idUSKBN15Q0JN|title=Trump and Japan's Abe take a swing at golf diplomacy|date=11 February 2017|publisher=Reuters|accessdate=20 May 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Security and defense issues===\nIn his April speech to Congress, Abe announced that his government would \"enact all necessary bills by this coming summer\" to expand the [[Japan Self-Defense Forces|Self-Defense Forces]]' capacity for operations and to give effect to the cabinet's July 2014 decision to re-interpret the constitution in favor of collective self-defense.<ref name=\"mofa.go.jp\"/> Therefore, the Abe cabinet introduced 11 bills making up the [[2015 Japanese military legislation|\"Peace and Security Preservation Legislation\"]] into the Diet in May 2015, which pushed for a limited expansion of military powers to fight in foreign conflict. The principal aims of the bills were to allow Japan's Self-Defense Forces to come to the aid of allied nations under attack (even if Japan itself was not), to expand their scope to support international peacekeeping operations, and to allow for Japan to take on a greater share of security responsibilities as part of the [[Japan\u2013United States relations|US-Japan Alliance]].<ref name=\"reference to NY times\">[https://www.nytimes.com/2015/07/17/world/asia/japans-lower-house-passes-bills-giving-military-freer-hand-to-fight.html?_r=0 NYT, 2015]</ref><ref name=\"The Diplomat\">{{cite web|url=http://thediplomat.com/2015/09/japans-controversial-security-bills-pass-in-the-upper-house-now-what/|title=Japan's Controversial Security Bills Pass in the Upper House. Now What?|date=19 September 2015|work=The Diplomat|accessdate=28 December 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tokyofoundation.org/en/articles/2015/abe-security-bills|title=The Abe Government's Security Bills|date=7 May 2015|work=Tokyo Foundation|accessdate=28 December 2015}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Shinz\u014d Abe and Vladimir Putin (2016-11-20) 01.jpg|thumb|Abe and Russian President [[Vladimir Putin]] in November 2016. Japan have not yet signed a peace treaty with Russia to end [[World War II]] because of a [[Kuril Islands dispute]]]]\nIn order to allow for enough time to pass the bills in the face of lengthy opposition scrutiny, the Abe cabinet extended the Diet session by 95 days from June into September, making it the longest in the post-war era.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.japantimes.co.jp/news/2015/06/22/national/politics-diplomacy/diet-session-to-be-extended-through-september-as-abe-aims-to-pass-contentious-security-bills/#.VoF0eU-REWh|title=Diet session extended through September as Abe aims to pass contentious security bills|date=22 June 2015|work=Japan Times|accessdate=28 December 2015}}</ref> The bills passed the [[House of Representatives (Japan)|House of Representatives]] on 16 July with the support of the majority LDP-Komeito coalition. Diet members from opposition Democratic, [[Japan Innovation Party|Innovation]], [[Japanese Communist Party|Communist]] and [[Social Democratic Party (Japan)|Social Democratic]] parties walked out of the vote in protest at what they said was the government's move to force the bills through without sufficient debate and ignore \"responsible opposition parties\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2015-07-15/abe-stares-down-tears-protests-as-security-bills-erode-support|title=Abe Security Bills Pass Japan's Lower House as Protests Flare|date=16 July 2015|work=Bloomberg|accessdate=28 December 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-asia-33546465|title=Japan's lower house approves change to self-defence law|date=16 July 2015|work=BBC News|accessdate=28 December 2015}}</ref> Abe countered by arguing that the bills had been debated for \"as many as 113 hours\" before the vote.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.japantimes.co.jp/news/2015/07/15/national/politics-diplomacy/amid-angry-scenes-ruling-parties-force-security-bills-lower-house-committee/#.VoF3VU-REWg|title=Amid angry scenes, ruling parties force security bills through Lower House committee|date=15 July 2015|work=Japan Times|accessdate=28 December 2015}}</ref> While common practice in many other [[Parliamentary system|parliamentary democracies]], a government using its majority to \"railroad\" controversial bills though the Diet in the face of political and public opposition is a subject of criticism in Japan.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nippon.com/en/in-depth/a05001/|title=The Difficult Role of the Top Opposition Party|date=18 December 2015|work=Nippon.com|accessdate=28 December 2015}}</ref>\n\nAs a result of these moves, Abe faced a public backlash, and opinion polls showed that his approval ratings fell into negative figures for the first time since he returned to power in 2012, with 50 percent disapproving and 38 percent approving of the cabinet according to one Nikkei survey at the beginning of August.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://asia.nikkei.com/Politics-Economy/Policy-Politics/Abe-s-future-uncertain-as-public-support-dives?page=1|title=Abe's future uncertain as public support dives|date=3 August 2015|work=Nikkei|accessdate=28 December 2015}}</ref> Many protested the legislation outside the Diet buildings, denouncing what were referred to as \"war bills\" by opponents. Organizers of the protests estimated that up to 100,000 protesters marched against the bills' passage of the lower house in July.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/07/17/world/asia/japans-lower-house-passes-bills-giving-military-freer-hand-to-fight.html?_r=0|title=Japan Moves to Allow Military Combat for First Time in 70 Years|date=16 July 2015|work=The New York Times|accessdate=28 December 2015}}</ref> During Diet committee hearings on the bills, constitutional scholars (some of whom had been invited by the ruling parties) and a former supreme court justice argued that the legislation was unconstitutional.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mainichi.jp/english/articles/20150606/p2a/00m/0na/012000c |title=Experts' 'unconstitutional' verdict on security bills highlights contradictions |date=6 June 2015 |work=Mainichi Shimbun |accessdate=28 December 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151228185914/http://mainichi.jp/english/articles/20150606/p2a/00m/0na/012000c |archivedate=28 December 2015 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.japantimes.co.jp/news/2015/09/16/national/politics-diplomacy/ex-justice-brands-security-bills-unconstitutional-upper-house-hits-abe-duping-public/#.VoGDqE-REWh|title=Former justice brands security bills as unconstitutional, slams Abe for sophistry|date=16 September 2015|work=Japan Times|accessdate=28 December 2015}}</ref> Abe was publicly criticised by atomic bomb survivor [[Sumiteru Taniguchi]] in his speech at the [[Nagasaki Peace Park#Peace Memorial Ceremony|Nagasaki memorial ceremony]] on 9 August, when he stated that the defense reforms would take Japan \"back to the wartime period\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/asia/japan/11792659/Nagasaki-survivor-warns-Abe-reforms-will-lead-to-war.html|title=Nagasaki survivor warns Abe reforms 'will lead to war' |date=9 August 2015|work=Telegraph|accessdate=28 December 2015}}</ref> Members of the Abe cabinet said that they would make a greater effort to explain the contents of and the reasons for the security legislation to the public, with the LDP releasing an animated cartoon commercial, and Abe appearing live on television and internet chat streams to make the case for the legislation and take questions from members of the public.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-japan-security-abe-idUSKCN0PX2PC20150723|title=Cartoon capers: Japan PM uses offbeat PR blitz to rescue ratings|date=23 July 2015|work=Reuters|accessdate=28 December 2015}}</ref>\n\n[[File:James Mattis and Shinzo Abe 20170203 1.jpg|thumb|Abe with U.S. Secretary of Defense [[James Mattis]], February 2017]]\nThe security bills were finally approved 148 votes to 90 by the House of Councillors and became law on 19 September, following opposition attempts at [[Dilatory motions and tactics|delaying tactics]] and physical altercations in which some Diet members attempted to stop the relevant chairman calling the vote to move the bill out of committee and to a general vote.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-asia-34287362|title=Japan to allow military role overseas in historic move|date=18 September 2015|work=BBC News|accessdate=28 December 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/09/19/world/asia/japan-parliament-passes-legislation-combat-role-for-military.html|title=Japan's Parliament Approves Overseas Combat Role for Military |date=18 September 2015|work=The New York Times|accessdate=28 December 2015}}</ref> After the vote, Abe issued a statement saying that the new laws \"will fortify our pledge to never again wage war\", and that the legislation, rather than being \"war bills\", was instead \"aimed at deterring war and contributing to peace and security\". He also pledged to continue to explain the legislation to try to gain \"greater understanding\" from the public on the issue.<ref name=\"ReferenceA\">{{cite speech |title=Press Conference by Prime Minister Shinzo Abe |author=Abe, Shinzo |date=25 September 2015 |location=Kantei, Tokyo |url=http://japan.kantei.go.jp/97_abe/statement/201509/1213465_9928.html|access-date=28 December 2015 }}</ref> Following the bills' passage, Abe was expected to once again return his focus to economic issues.<ref name=\"The Diplomat\"/>\n\nOn 18 October 2015 Abe presided over the triennial fleet review of the [[Japan Maritime Self-Defense Force]] in his role as Commander-in-Chief of the Self-Defense Forces. In his speech to personnel on board the destroyer ''Kurama'' he announced that \"by highly hoisting the flag of 'proactive pacifism,' I'm determined to contribute more than ever to world peace and prosperity\". Later that day he went aboard the {{USS|Ronald Reagan}}, becoming the first Japanese prime minister to set foot on an American warship.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://thediplomat.com/2015/10/japans-fleet-review-abe-boards-us-warship-for-first-time-ever/|title=Japan's Fleet Review: Abe Boards US Warship for First Time Ever|date=20 October 2015|work=The Diplomat|accessdate=28 December 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn December 2015, the Abe government announced the creation of a new intelligence unit, the [[International Counterterrorism Intelligence Collection Unit]], to aid counter-terrorism operations, to be based in the Foreign Ministry but led by the Prime Minister's Office. This was reported as being part of efforts to step up security measures in preparation for the [[42nd G7 summit|2016 G7 Summit]] in [[Shima, Mie]], and [[2020 Summer Olympics|2020 Olympics in Tokyo]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://asia.nikkei.com/Japan-Update/Japan-to-launch-antiterrorism-intelligence-unit|title=Japan to launch antiterrorism intelligence unit|date=4 December 2015|work=Nikkei|accessdate=28 December 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151227210636/http://asia.nikkei.com/Japan-Update/Japan-to-launch-antiterrorism-intelligence-unit|archive-date=27 December 2015|url-status=dead}}</ref> In the same month the cabinet approved Japan's largest ever defense budget, at 5.1 trillion yen, for the fiscal year beginning in April 2016. The package included funding intended for the purchase of three [[Northrop Grumman RQ-4 Global Hawk|\"Global Hawk\" drones]], six [[Lockheed Martin F-35 Lightning II|F-35 fighter jets]] and a [[Boeing KC-46 Pegasus|Boeing KC-46A midair refueling aircraft]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://abcnews.go.com/International/wireStory/japan-cabinet-oks-record-defense-budget-amid-china-35937970|title=Japan Cabinet OKs Record Defense Budget Amid China Concern|date=24 December 2015|agency=Associated Press|accessdate=28 December 2015}}</ref>\n\n===Re-election as LDP president and \"Abenomics 2.0\"===\n[[File:Shinz\u014d Abe at Hudson Institute 2016.jpg|thumb|Abe speaking at the [[Hudson Institute]] in Washington, DC, in March 2016]]\nIn September 2015 Abe was re-elected as president of the LDP in an uncontested election after LDP Diet member [[Seiko Noda]] failed to garner enough support to stand as a candidate.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/09/09/world/asia/shinzo-abe-of-japan-re-elected-as-leader-of-ruling-party.html?_r=0|title=Shinzo Abe of Japan Re-elected as Leader of Ruling Party|date=8 September 2015|work=The New York Times|accessdate=26 December 2015}}</ref> Following this Abe carried out a cabinet reshuffle, once again keeping the key ministers of [[Minister of Finance (Japan)|Finance]], Economy, [[Minister for Foreign Affairs (Japan)|Foreign Affairs]] and the Chief Cabinet Secretary in post. He also created a new ministerial position for the co-ordination of policies related to the economy, population decline, and social security reform, which was filled by [[Katsunobu Kat\u014d]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://news.yahoo.com/abe-reshuffles-cabinet-adding-minister-focus-economy-114038353.html|title=Abe reshuffles Cabinet, adding minister to focus on economy|date=7 October 2015|agency=Associated Press|accessdate=28 December 2015}}</ref>\n\nAt a press conference after his official re-election as LDP President, Abe announced that the next stage of his administration would focus on what he called \"Abenomics 2.0\", the aim of which was to tackle issues of [[Demography of Japan|low fertility and an aging population]] and create a society \"in which each and every one of Japan's 100 million citizens can take on active roles\".<ref name=\"ReferenceA\"/> This new policy consisted of targets which Abe referred to as \"three new arrows\"; to boost Japan's GDP to 600 trillion yen by 2021, to raise the national fertility rate from an average of 1.4 to 1.8 children per woman and stabilise the population at 100 million, and to create a situation where people would not have to leave employment in order to care for elderly relatives by the mid 2020s. Abe explained that the government would take measures to increase wages, boost consumption, and expand childcare, social security and care services for the elderly to meet these goals.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.japantimes.co.jp/news/2015/09/24/national/politics-diplomacy/abe-outlines-new-goals-abenomics-20-rise-gdp/#.VoCp1E-REWj|title=Abe aims arrows at new targets with three fresh goals for 'Abenomics,' 20% rise in GDP|date=24 September 2015|work=Nippon.com|accessdate=28 December 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/business/2015/sep/24/abenomics-20-pm-updates-plan-to-refresh-japanese-economy|title=Abenomics 2.0 \u2013 PM updates plan to refresh Japanese economy|date=24 September 2015|agency=Associated Press|accessdate=28 December 2015}}</ref>\n\nThis new iteration of Abenomics was met with some criticism by commentators, who argued that it was not yet clear if the first three arrows had succeeded in lifting Japan out of deflation (inflation was some way below the 2 percent target), that the new arrows were merely presented as targets without the necessary policies to meet them, and that the targets themselves were unrealistic.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nippon.com/en/currents/d00207/|title=Reading Between the Lines of Abenomics 2.0|date=16 December 2015|work=Nippon.com|accessdate=28 December 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.economist.com/news/asia/21668283-japans-new-three-little-arrows-shinzo-abe-tweaks-his-economic-programme-japan|title=Less of the same|date=1 October 2015|work=The Economist|accessdate=28 December 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://thediplomat.com/2015/09/abenomics-2-0-a-reform-reboot-for-japan/|title=Abenomics 2.0: A Reform Reboot For Japan?|date=30 September 2015|work=The Diplomat|accessdate=28 December 2015}}</ref> However, opinion polls during the final months of 2015 showed the Abe cabinet's approval ratings once again climbing into positive figures after the change in emphasis back to economic issues.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://asia.nikkei.com/Politics-Economy/Policy-Politics/Abe-regains-support-on-pivot-to-economy|title=Abe regains support on pivot to economy|date=30 November 2015|work=Nikkei|accessdate=28 December 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.japantimes.co.jp/news/2015/12/12/national/politics-diplomacy/public-support-abe-cabinet-rises-third-month/#.VoCfAE-REWg|title=Public support for Abe Cabinet rises for third month|date=12 December 2015|work=The Japan Times|accessdate=28 December 2015}}</ref>\n\nAt the conclusion of the [[Trans-Pacific Partnership]] talks in early October 2015, Abe hailed the agreement for creating an \"unprecedented economic zone\" and opening up possibilities for an even wider Asia-Pacific free trade deal and Japanese trade with Europe. He also promised to mitigate any negative effects on the Japanese agricultural sector.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.japantimes.co.jp/news/2015/10/06/business/economy-business/abe-hails-tpp-success-calls-just-start/|title=Abe hails TPP success but calls it 'just a start'|date=6 October 2015|work=The Japan Times|accessdate=28 December 2015}}</ref> GDP figures released in November 2015 initially appeared to show that Japan had entered a second recession since the implementation of Abenomics,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/business-34829408|title=Japan's economy falls back into recession again|date=16 November 2015|work=BBC News|accessdate=28 December 2015}}</ref> however these figures were subsequently revised to show that the economy had grown by 1 percent in the third quarter, thus avoiding recession.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.businessinsider.com/ap-japan-avoids-recession-revised-growth-at-1-percent-2015-12?IR=T|title=Japan avoids recession, revised growth at 1 percent|date=8 December 2015|agency=Associated Press|accessdate=28 December 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn December 2015, the two parties making up Abe's governing coalition agreed to introduce a reduced rate of consumption tax for food when the anticipated tax increase from 8 to 10 percent takes place in April 2017. This deal was reached after Abe was seen to come down strongly in favor of the position held by his junior coalition partner the Komeito, that the tax rate should be reduced, which prompted some disagreement from members of his own party, who favored a policy of greater fiscal consolidation through taxes.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://the-japan-news.com/news/article/0002624907 |title=Abe prioritized coalition with Komeito |date=14 December 2015 |work=The Yomiuri Shimbun |accessdate=28 December 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151228040506/http://the-japan-news.com/news/article/0002624907 |archivedate=28 December 2015 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://the-japan-news.com/news/article/0002629557 |title=Tax agreement irks some in LDP |date=16 December 2015 |work=The Yomiuri Shimbun |accessdate=28 December 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151228040806/http://the-japan-news.com/news/article/0002629557 |archivedate=28 December 2015 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://mainichi.jp/english/articles/20151224/p2a/00m/0na/025000c |title=3 years on, Abe leads prime minister's office to dominate politics |date=24 December 2015 |work=The Mainichi Shimbun |accessdate=28 December 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151225093436/http://mainichi.jp/english/articles/20151224/p2a/00m/0na/025000c |archivedate=25 December 2015 }}</ref> Abe dismissed the chairman of the LDP's tax panel [[Takeshi Noda]] (who opposed the reduction), and appointed [[Yoichi Miyazawa]], who was more favorable to the policy, as his replacement.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.japantimes.co.jp/news/2015/10/14/business/economy-business/abe-orders-work-on-a-concessionary-tax-rate-to-cushion-blow-from-consumption-tax-hike/#.VoCyRU-REWh|title=Abe orders reduced rates to cushion blow from 2017 tax hike|date=14 October 2015|work=The Japan Times|accessdate=28 December 2015}}</ref> Abe declared the tax deal to be \"the best possible result\" of the negotiations.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://the-japan-news.com/news/article/0002625156 |title=Abe: Reduced tax rate for food 'best possible result' |date=14 December 2015 |work=The Yomiuri Shimbun |accessdate=28 December 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151228040236/http://the-japan-news.com/news/article/0002625156 |archivedate=28 December 2015 }}</ref>\n\n===Constitutional revision===\n{{Main|Article 9 of the Japanese Constitution Referendum}}\nAt the 2016 election to the House of Councillors, the first that allowed Japanese citizens 18 and over to vote, Abe led the LDP\u2013Komeito pact to victory, with the coalition being the largest in the House of Councillors, since it was set at 242 seats. The election's results opened the debate on constitutional reform, particularly in amending [[Article 9 of the Japanese Constitution|Article 9]] of Japan's pacifist constitution, with pro-revisionist parties gaining the two-thirds majority being necessary for reform, alongside a two-thirds majority in the House of Representatives, which would ultimately lead to a nationwide referendum.<ref>{{cite news|title=Abe camp gains supermajority needed to alter constitution|url=http://asia.nikkei.com/Politics-Economy/Policy-Politics/Abe-camp-gains-supermajority-needed-to-alter-constitution|accessdate=20 May 2017|work=Nikkei Asian Review|date=11 July 2016}}</ref>\nAbe remained relatively quiet on the issue for the remainder of the year, but in May 2017, announced that the constitutional reform would be in effect by 2020.<ref>{{cite news|title=Japan's Abe hopes for reform of pacifist charter by 2020|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-japan-government-constitution-idUSKBN17Z0BH|accessdate=20 May 2017|work=Reuters|date=3 May 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Fourth term as prime minister (2017\u2013present)==\n[[File:Shinzo Abe and Donald Trump playing golf.jpg|thumb|Abe has developed close ties with U.S. President [[Donald Trump]]]]\n[[File:Shinz\u014d Abe and Xi Jinping (November 2017).jpg|thumb|Abe and Chinese President [[Xi Jinping]] in November 2017]]\n[[File:Shinz\u014d Abe visits Russia (2018-05-26) 07.jpg|thumb|Abe with Russian President [[Vladimir Putin]] at the [[St. Petersburg International Economic Forum]] on 26 May 2018]]\nThe [[2017 Japanese general election|2017 general election]] was held on 22 October. Prime Minister Abe called the [[snap election]] on 25 September, while the [[2017 North Korea crisis|North Korea crisis]] was prominent in the news media.<ref name=\"veconomist\">{{cite news|title=Why the LDP keeps winning elections in Japan: pragmatism|url=https://www.economist.com/news/asia/21730204-scandals-and-economic-stagnation-seem-do-it-no-harm-why-ldp-keeps-winning-elections-japan|work=[[The Economist]]|date=12 October 2017}}</ref> Political opponents of Abe say the snap election was designed to evade questioning in parliament over alleged scandals.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://apjjf.org/2017/20/Repeta.html|title=Backstory to Abe's Snap Election \u2013 the Secrets of Moritomo, Kake and the \"Missing\" Japan SDF Activity Logs|last=Repeta|first=Lawrence|date=2017-10-15|website=The Asia-Pacific Journal: Japan Focus|access-date=2017-10-17}}</ref> Abe was expected to retain a majority of seats in the Diet.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/japan-election-exitpolls/japan-pm-abes-ruling-bloc-on-track-for-big-election-win-exit-polls-idUST9N1DU02X|title=Japan PM Abe's ruling bloc on track for big election win \u2013 exit polls|date=22 October 2017|via=Reuters}}</ref> Abe's ruling coalition took almost a majority of the vote and two-thirds of the seats. The last minute campaigning and voting took place as [[Typhoon Lan]], the biggest typhoon of 2017, was wreaking havoc on Japan.\n\n===Favoritism scandals===\nIn March 2018, it was revealed that the finance ministry (with finance minister [[Tar\u014d As\u014d]] at its head) had falsified documents presented to the parliament in relation to the [[Moritomo Gakuen]] scandal, to remove 14 passages implicating Abe.<ref name=\"financialtimes\">https://www.ft.com/content/44bc98c0-25be-11e8-b27e-cc62a39d57a0</ref> It was suggested that the scandal could cost Abe his seat as Liberal Democratic party's leader.<ref name=\"financialtimes\"/> Further accusations arose the same year that Abe had given preferential treatment to his friend Kotar\u014d Kake to open a veterinary department at his school, Kake Gakuen.  Abe denied the charges, but support for his administration fell below 30% in the polls, the lowest since taking power in 2012.  Those who called for him to step down included former prime minister [[Junichir\u014d Koizumi]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Japan PM Abe's rating falls in media poll amid scandal woes|work=Reuters|author=Reuters staff|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-japan-politics/japan-pm-abes-rating-falls-in-media-poll-amid-scandal-woes-idUSKBN1HM0D8=|date=2018-04-15|accessdate=2018-04-16}}{{Dead link|date=July 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> The scandal has been referred to as \"Abegate\".<ref>https://www.businesstimes.com.sg/opinion/abegate-may-be-just-the-tip-of-the-iceberg</ref>\n\nThe scandals, while not damaging his political standing permanently, did little good to his image. In July 2018, Abe's public standing was further hit after he held a drinking party with LDP lawmakers during the peak of the [[2018 Japan floods|disastrous floodings in western Japan]].<ref>{{cite web|title=LDP under fire for partying as disaster loomed in western Japan|work=[[Asahi Shimbun]]|author=Asahi Shimbun staff|url=http://www.asahi.com/ajw/articles/AJ201807110019.html|date=2018-07-11|accessdate=2018-07-12}}</ref> In a poll conducted by Reuters in 2019, a majority of Japanese companies want Prime Minister Shinzo Abe to finish his term to September 2021 but fewer than one in five say he should stay beyond then based on allegations that he broke campaign laws erode public support.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-japan-companies-abe-idUSKBN1Y92T4|title=As scandal simmers, majority of Japan firms want PM Abe to finish term: Reuters poll|date=2019-12-06|work=Reuters|access-date=2019-12-09|language=en}}</ref>\n\n===Foreign policy===\nAbe welcomed the [[2018 North Korea\u2013United States summit]]. Shortly after the summit was announced, Abe told reporters he appreciated \"North Korea's change\" and attributed the diplomatic change in tone to the coordinated sanctions campaign by the United States, Japan, and South Korea.<ref>{{cite news|title=Word of Trump-Kim Summit Meeting Stirs Concern in Asia|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/03/08/world/asia/trump-kim-meeting-asia-reaction.html|work=[[The New York Times]]|date=8 March 2018|access-date=11 June 2018}}</ref> Abe, however, cautioned President Trump not to strike a compromise on North Korea's missile program that would leave Japan exposed to [[Short-range ballistic missile|short-range missiles]] that do not reach the U.S. mainland or relieve pressure on North Korea too soon before complete denuclearization.<ref>{{cite web|title=North Korea's neighbors may have conflicting goals for Kim-Trump summit|url=http://www.chicagotribune.com/news/nationworld/politics/ct-north-korea-summit-japan-china-20180608-story.html|work=[[Chicago Tribune]]|access-date=11 June 2018|date=9 June 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Trump-Kim summit: Why Japan's defence strategy hangs in the balance|url=https://www.straitstimes.com/opinion/trump-kim-summit-why-japans-defence-strategy-hangs-in-the-balance|work=[[The Straits Times]]|date=11 June 2018|access-date=11 June 2018}}</ref> Abe also expressed a desire to hold a bilateral meeting with North Korea on the issue of [[North Korean abductions of Japanese citizens|abductions of Japanese citizens]], pressing President Trump to raise the matter at the summit.<ref>{{cite web|title=Abe repeats desire to hold summit with North Korea on abduction issue|url=https://www.japantimes.co.jp/news/2018/06/11/national/politics-diplomacy/abe-eager-hold-summit-north-korea-resolve-decades-old-abduction-issue/|work=[[Japan Times]]|date=11 June 2018|access-date=11 June 2018}}</ref>\nIn 2018, he paid a 2-day formal visit to China, in order to improve the communication with it. He had several meetings with [[Xi Jinping]], the paramount leader of China. Therefore, Abe promised that Chinese people will get visas of Japan much more easily in 2019, especially among teenagers. Abe also hopes President Xi will visit Japan, thus they can rise the level of the nexus between two countries.<ref>{{cite web|title=\u5b89\u500d\u664b\u4e09\u62b5\u5317\u4eac \u65e5\u672c\u9996\u76f8\u65f6\u96947\u5e74\u6b63\u5f0f\u8bbf\u534e|url=https://m.guancha.cn/politics/2018_10_25_476886.shtml|work=\u89c2\u5bdf\u8005\u7f51|date=25 October 2018|access-date=13 April 2019}}</ref> Abe cautioned President Xi over [[2019 Hong Kong anti-extradition bill protests|protests in Hong Kong]] at the [[2019 G20 Osaka summit|G20 Summit]]. Abe told Xi it is important for \"a free and open Hong Kong to prosper under \"one country, two systems' policy\".<ref>{{cite news|title=Japan says Abe raised Hong Kong with China's Xi|date=28 June 2019|url=https://www.taiwannews.com.tw/en/news/3734120|work=The Public's Radio}}</ref>\n\n===Re-election as LDP President===\nOn 20 September 2018, Abe was re-elected as leader of the main ruling Liberal Democratic Party.<ref>Newsroom Tokyo, 20:00 Japan Standard Time (JST), Thursday, 20 September 2018, NHK World Japan TV.</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.economist.com/leaders/2018/09/22/japans-prime-minister-is-more-of-a-survivor-than-a-reformer|title=Japan's prime minister is more of a survivor than a reformer|work=The Economist|access-date=2018-09-26|language=en}}</ref>\n\n===Longest serving Prime Minister of Japan===\nOn 19 November 2019, Abe became Japan's longest-serving Prime Minister, surpassing the 2,883-day record of [[Katsura Tar\u014d]].<ref name=\"ft\">{{cite news |last1=Harding |first1=Robin |title=Shinzo Abe becomes Japan\u2019s longest serving prime minister |url=https://www.ft.com/content/f4323946-0a9f-11ea-bb52-34c8d9dc6d84 |accessdate=20 November 2019 |work=Financial Times |date=20 November 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Political positions and philosophy==\nAffiliated to the openly revisionist organization [[Nippon Kaigi]] (Japan Conference),<ref name=\"Tea Party Politics in Japan\"/> Shinzo Abe consistently defends its agenda.\n\n===Views on history===\n[[File:Shinzo Abe with KSG Students.jpg|thumb|right|Abe, as the Japanese Chief Cabinet Secretary, with a group of students from [[Harvard University]] in March 2006. His future Chief Cabinet Secretary [[Yasuhisa Shiozaki]] (himself a graduate of Harvard University) is standing to his left]]\n\nAbe is widely viewed as a right-wing nationalist.<ref name=\"Lucy Alexander\"/><ref name=\"The New York Times\">{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2013/01/03/opinion/another-attempt-to-deny-japans-history.html?smid=fb-share&_r=0|title=Another Attempt to Deny Japan's History|work=The New York Times|date=2 January 2013}}</ref><ref name=\"Justin McCurry\"/> The British journalist [[Rupert Wingfield-Hayes]] of [[BBC]] described him as \"far more right wing than most of his predecessors\".<ref name=\"Rupert Wingfield-Hayes\">{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-asia-20728387|title=Japan loses faith in traditional politics|author=Rupert Wingfield-Hayes|publisher=BBC|date=15 December 2012}}</ref> Since 1997, as the bureau chief of the \"Institute of Junior Assembly Members Who Think About the Outlook of Japan and History Education\", Abe led the [[Japanese Society for History Textbook Reform]]. In 2007, he denied to reporters that Japan forced women into sexual slavery during World War II.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Onishi |first1=Norimitsu |title=Abe Rejects Japan's Files on War Sex |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2007/03/02/world/asia/02japan.html |accessdate=22 July 2018 |work=[[The New York Times]]|language=en}}</ref> On his official homepage,<ref>[http://www.s-abe.or.jp/poritics/textbook/textbook.htm] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20041011121213/http://www.s-abe.or.jp/poritics/textbook/textbook.htm|date=11 October 2004}}</ref> he questions the extent to which coercion was applied toward the [[comfort women]], dismissing South Korean positions on the issue as foreign interference in Japanese domestic affairs. In a Diet session on 6 October 2006, Abe revised his statement regarding comfort women, and said that he accepted the report issued in 1993 by the sitting cabinet secretary, [[Y\u014dhei K\u014dno]], where the Japanese government officially acknowledged the issue. Later in the session, Abe stated his belief that Class A war criminals are not criminals under Japan's domestic law.<ref>[http://www.yomiuri.co.jp/dy/national/20061007TDY03005.htm Abe clarifies views on 'history issue,' reaffirms apologies], ''Daily Yomiuri'', 7 October 2006.  {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130511225707/http://www.yomiuri.co.jp/dy/national/20061007TDY03005.htm |date=11 May 2013 }}</ref>\n\nIn a meeting of the Lower House Budget Committee in February 2006, Shinzo Abe said, \"There is a problem as to how to define aggressive wars; we cannot say it is decided academically\",<ref name=\"20060216minutes\">{{cite web|url=http://kokkai.ndl.go.jp/SENTAKU/syugiin/164/0018/16402160018013c.html|title=Official minutes of the Budget Committee|date=18 February 2006}}</ref> and \"It is not the business of the government to decide how to define the last world war. I think we have to wait for the estimation of historians\".<ref name=\"20060216minutes\" /> However, on a TV program in July 2006<ref>[http://www.jcp.or.jp/akahata/aik4/2005-08-01/2005080104_01_0.html \u30b5\u30f3\u30c7\u30fc\u30d7\u30ed\u30b8\u30a7\u30af\u30c8/\u5fd7\u4f4d\u59d4\u54e1\u9577\u306e\u767a\u8a00/\uff08\u5927\u8981] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090905230154/http://www.jcp.or.jp/akahata/aik4/2005-08-01/2005080104_01_0.html |date=5 September 2009 }}</ref> he denied that [[Manchukuo]] was a [[puppet state]].\n\nAbe published a book called {{nihongo|''Toward a Beautiful Nation''|\u7f8e\u3057\u3044\u56fd\u3078|Utsukushii kuni e}} in July 2006, which became a bestseller in Japan. The Korean and Chinese governments, as well as noted academics and commentators, have voiced concern about Abe's historical views.<ref>[http://www.zmag.org/content/showarticle.cfm?SectionID=17&ItemID=11120 Abe's \"normal\" Japan], ZNet, 5 October 2006. {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20061027223004/http://www.zmag.org/content/showarticle.cfm?SectionID=17&ItemID=11120 |date=27 October 2006 }}</ref><ref>[http://www.jpri.org/publications/workingpapers/wp107.html History Redux: Japan's Textbook Battle Reignites], Japan Policy Research Institute Working Paper No. 107 (June 2005).</ref><ref>[http://english.hani.co.kr/arti/english_edition/e_editorial/153791.html Japan's difficult drive to be a 'beautiful country'], The Hankyoreh, 2 September 2006.</ref>\n\nIn March 2007, in response to a [[United States Congress]] resolution by [[Mike Honda]], Abe denied any government coercion in the recruitment of comfort women during [[World War II]],<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20070901180504/http://search.japantimes.co.jp/cgi-bin/nn20070302a9.html ''The Japan Times'' 2 March 2007]</ref> in line with a statement made almost ten years before on the same issue, in which Abe voiced his opposition to the inclusion of the subject of military prostitution in several school textbooks and then denied any coercion in the \"narrow\" sense of the word, environmental factors notwithstanding.<ref name=\"japan-press.co.jp\">[http://www.japan-press.co.jp/pdf/special-2006-november.pdf Japan Press Weekly Special Issue \u2013 November 2006] ([[PDF]]).</ref>\nThis statement provoked negative reactions in Asian and [[Western Hemisphere|western]] countries; a ''[[New York Times]]'' editorial on 6 March 2007 commented for instance:\n<blockquote>What part of 'Japanese Army sex slaves' does Japan's prime minister, Shinzo Abe, have so much trouble understanding and apologizing for?&nbsp;... These were not commercial brothels. Force, explicit and implicit, was used in recruiting these women. What went on in them was serial rape, not prostitution. The Japanese Army's involvement is documented in the government's own defense files. A senior Tokyo official more or less apologized for this horrific crime in 1993&nbsp;... Yesterday, [Abe] grudgingly acknowledged the 1993 quasi-apology, but only as part of a pre-emptive declaration that his government would reject the call, now pending in the United States Congress, for an official apology. America isn't the only country interested in seeing Japan belatedly accept full responsibility. [South] Korea and China are also infuriated by years of Japanese equivocations over the issue.<ref>{{cite news|work=The New York Times|title=No comfort|date=6 March 2007|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2007/03/06/opinion/06tues3.html|accessdate=8 March 2007}}</ref></blockquote>\n\n[[File:President Trump and First Lady Melania Attend a Sumo Tournament (47958681958).jpg|thumb|Abe attends a traditional [[Sumo|Japanese wrestling]]]]\nA 2007 ''[[Washington Post]]'' editorial, \"Shinzo Abe's Double Talk\", also criticized him: \"he's passionate about Japanese victims of North Korea\u2014and blind to Japan's own war crimes\".<ref>[https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2007/03/23/AR2007032301640.html?sub=new Shinzo Abe's Double Talk], ''The Washington Post'', 24 March 2007.</ref> In ''[[The New York Times]]'' in 2014, an editorial called Abe a \"nationalist\" who is a profound threat to American\u2013Japanese relations,<ref>{{cite news|newspaper=The New York Times|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2014/03/03/opinion/mr-abes-dangerous-revisionism.html?_r=0|title=Mr. Abe's Dangerous Revisionism|accessdate=4 March 2014|date=2 March 2014}}</ref> and an opinion piece labeled Abe's position on the subject of comfort women a \"war on truth\".<ref>{{cite news|newspaper=The New York Times|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2014/11/15/opinion/comfort-women-and-japans-war-on-truth.html|title=The Comfort Women and Japan's War on Truth|accessdate=19 February 2014|date=14 November 2014}}</ref> The same editorial presented him as a [[Historical negationism|revisionist]], a view largely accepted by the international and part of the Japanese press.<ref>{{cite web|last=Kingston |first=Jeff |url=http://www.japantimes.co.jp/opinion/2015/08/22/commentary/abes-revisionism-japans-divided-war-memories/#.WC-W1yNREy4 |title=Abe's revisionism and Japan's divided war memories |work=The Japan Times|date=2015-08-22 |accessdate=2017-04-06}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.chinadaily.com.cn/opinion/2015-08/14/content_21595221.htm |title=Washington's dubious silence on Abe revisionism |publisher=Chinadaily.com.cn |date=2015-08-14 |accessdate=2017-04-06}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://koreatimes.co.kr/www/news/nation/2015/08/113_184884.html |title=Abe refuses to make direct apology |publisher=Koreatimes.co.kr |date=2015-08-14 |accessdate=2017-04-06}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author=Kosuke Takahashi |url=http://thediplomat.com/2014/02/shinzo-abes-nationalist-strategy/ |title=Shinzo Abe's Nationalist Strategy |publisher=The Diplomat |date=2014-02-13 |accessdate=2017-04-06}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/view/articles/2015-04-29/diplomat-george-kennan-is-behind-shinzo-abe-s-history-problems |title=Blame George Kennan for Abe's Bad History |publisher=Bloomberg.com |date=2015-04-29 |accessdate=2017-04-06}}</ref> Writing in the ''[[London Review of Books]]'', political scientist [[Edward Luttwak]] called Abe a \"pragmatic Japanese Tory driving through reforms at home, while weaving an alliance aimed at containing China.\"<ref>{{cite news|newspaper=The London Review of Books|url=https://www.lrb.co.uk/v41/n07/edward-luttwak/friendly-relations|title=Friendly Relations|accessdate=21 November 2019|date=4 April 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn a speech to LDP lawmakers in Tokyo on 8 March 2019, [[Steve Bannon]] said that \"Prime Minister Abe is a great hero to the grassroots, the populist, and the nationalist movement throughout the world\". According to Bannon, Abe was the first nationalist leader to win an election in an industrialized democracy and successfully govern as a nationalist.\" \"Prime Minister Abe was Trump before Trump\", Bannon declared, eliciting laughter from some LDP lawmakers.<ref>[https://www.japantimes.co.jp/news/2019/03/08/national/politics-diplomacy/ex-adviser-steve-bannon-confident-donald-trump-win-2020-despite-probes/#.XILevy2ZPOR], Ex-adviser Steve Bannon says Abe was 'Trump before Trump,' urges him to play hardball with China, Japan Times, 8 March 2019.</ref>\n\n===Response to mass media===\n[[File:Shinzo Abe.jpg|thumb|Abe campaigning in June 2010]]\nThe ''[[Asahi Shimbun]]'' also accused Abe and [[Sh\u014dichi Nakagawa]] of censoring a 2001 [[NHK]] program concerning \"The Women's International War Crimes Tribunal\".<ref>[http://www.asahi.com/english/politics/TKY200501120160.html LDP pressure led to cuts in NHK show], Asahi Shimbun, 12 January 2005.</ref> The \"tribunal\" was a private committee to adjudicate comfort women; about 5,000 people, including 64 victims from Japan and abroad, attended. The committee members, who claimed to be specialists of [[international law]], claimed that Emperor [[Hirohito]] and the Japanese government were responsible for the use of comfort women. The TV program, however, did not mention the full name of the tribunal and key words such as \"Japanese troops\" or \"sexual slavery\", and it also cut the sight of the tribunal, the host grouping, statements of the organizer, and the judgement itself. Instead, it presented criticism against the tribunal by a right-wing academic and his statement that \"there was no abduction of sex slaves and they were prostitutes\".<ref>[http://www1.jca.apc.org/vaww-net-japan/english/womenstribunal2000/whatstribunal.html \"What is the Women's Tribunal?\"] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20061005154836/http://www1.jca.apc.org/vaww-net-japan/english/womenstribunal2000/whatstribunal.html |date=5 October 2006 }}. Retrieved 29 September 2007.</ref>\n\nOn the day following the ''[[Asahi Shimbun]]'' report, Akira Nagai, the chief producer and primary person responsible for the program, held a press conference and ensured the report of the ''Asahi Shimbun''. Abe stated that the content \"had to be broadcast from a neutral point of view\" and \"what I did is not to give political pressure\". Abe said, \"It was a political terrorism by ''Asahi Shimbun'' and it was tremendously clear that they had intention to inhume me and Mr. Nakagawa politically, and it is also clear that it was complete fabrication.\" He also characterized the tribunal as a \"mock trial\" and raised objection to the presence of [[North Korea]]n [[prosecutor]]s, singling them out as agents of North Korean government.<ref>[http://www1.jca.apc.org/vaww-net-japan/nhk/appeal050117.html \u5b89\u500d\u664b\u4e09\u6c0f\u306e\u4e8b\u5b9f\u6b6a\u66f2\u767a\u8a00\u306b\u3064\u3044\u3066] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20061005155752/http://www1.jca.apc.org/vaww-net-japan/nhk/appeal050117.html |date=5 October 2006 }}, Violence Against Women in War Network Japan, 17 January 2005.</ref> Abe's actions in the NHK incident have been criticized {{who|date=January 2015}} as being both illegal (violating the [[Broadcast Law]]) and unconstitutional (violating the [[Constitution of Japan|Japanese Constitution]]).<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20050422074846/http://www.zmag.org/content/showarticle.cfm?ItemID=7140 War and Japan's Memory Wars], ZNet, 29 January 2005.</ref>\n\nA news program aired on [[Tokyo Broadcasting System|Tokyo Broadcasting System (TBS)]] on 21 July 2006 about a secret biological weapons troop of Imperial Japanese Army called [[Unit 731]], along with a picture panel of Shinzo Abe, who has no relation to the report. Abe said in a press conference, \"It is a truly big problem if they want to injure my political life\". The [[Ministry of Internal Affairs and Communications]] inquired into fact relevance and stated that there had been an omission in editing the TV program fairly, making an administrative direction of exceptional stringent warning based upon [[Broadcast Law]].\n\nOn 24 October 2006, a report emerged that Abe's new administration had called on the NHK to \"pay attention\" to the [[North Korean abductions of Japanese citizens|North Korean abductees issue]].<ref>[http://www.iht.com/articles/ap/2006/10/24/asia/AS_GEN_Japan_NKorea_Media.php Japan to order more public media coverage of North Korea abductees], International Herald Tribune, 24 October 2006.</ref> Critics, some even within Abe's own LDP party, charged that the government was violating freedom of expression by meddling in the affairs of the public broadcaster.\n\nIn December 2006, it was revealed that former Prime-Minister Junichiro Koizumi's government, in which Abe was Chief Cabinet Secretary, had influenced town hall style meetings, during which paid performers would ask government officials favorable questions.<ref>[https://www.nytimes.com/2006/12/14/world/asia/14japan.html?_r=2&oref=slogin&oref=slogin Japan's Leaders Rigged Voter Forums, a Government Report Says], New York Times, 14 December 2006.</ref>\n\nOn 22 November 2012, it was reported that TBS early morning TV show \"Asazuba\" accidentally displayed Abe's photo alongside a news report about an NHK announcer's arrest for a sex offense. Abe's face filled viewers' screens along with the name of NHK announcer Takeshige Morimoto, who anchors NHK's \"Ohayo Nippon\" program on Saturday and Sunday. Morimoto was arrested for allegedly groping a woman on the train. Abe posted on his public Facebook page \"This morning on the TBS show 'Asazuba,' when a newscaster reported on a story regarding the apprehension of a molester, a photo of me was shown. Images of this blunder can now be seen clearly across the Internet, Have the slander campaigns already begun!? If this were merely an accident, it would be proper for the TV station to give me a personal apology, but as yet I haven't heard a single word.\" The newscaster acknowledged that the incorrect image had been displayed, but merely stated that the photo was \"unrelated\" and did not refer to the politician by name. Neither Abe nor his office have received any form of apology.<ref>[http://www.japantoday.com/category/politics/view/tv-blunder-labels-abe-a-train-groper TV blunder labels Abe a train groper], RocketNews24, 22 November 2012.</ref>\n\n===Yasukuni Shrine===\nAbe has visited [[Yasukuni Shrine]] on several occasions. While serving as Chief Cabinet Secretary in the government of Junichiro Koizumi, he visited in April 2006, prompting South Korea to describe the trip as \"regrettable\".<ref>[http://www.japantimes.co.jp/text/nn20060805a6.html Abe's April Yasukuni visit regrettable, Seoul says] ''The Japan Times'', 5 August 2006</ref> He visited again on 15 August 2012, the anniversary of the end of World War&nbsp;II,<ref>[http://www.japantimes.co.jp/text/nn20120922f1.html Fears mount over LDP's nationalistic turn Saber-rattling over island disputes likely to grow louder] ''The Japan Times'', 22 September 2012</ref> and after winning the presidency of the Liberal Democratic Party, he visited on 17 October 2012 in an official capacity as party president.<ref>[http://www.japantimes.co.jp/text/nn20121017x3.html Abe pays Yasukuni visit amid isle rows] ''The Japan Times'', 17 October 2012</ref>\n\nHe initially refrained from visiting the shrine as a sitting Prime Minister. He did not visit at all during his first term from September 2006 to September 2007, unlike his predecessor Koizumi, who had visited yearly while in office. Abe's not visiting the shrine prompted a Japanese nationalist named Yoshihiro Tanjo to cut off his own little finger in protest and mail it to the LDP.<ref>[http://www.japantimes.co.jp/text/nn20070824a7.html Severed pinkie sent to LDP to protest Abe's Yasukuni no-show] ''The Japan Times'', 24 August 2007</ref> While campaigning for the presidency of the LDP in 2012, Abe said that he regretted not visiting the shrine while Prime Minister. He again refrained from visiting the shrine during the first year of his second stint as prime minister in consideration for improving relations with China and Korea, whose leaders refused to meet with Abe during this time. He said on 9 December 2013 that \"it is natural that we should express our feelings of respect to the war dead who sacrificed their lives for the nation&nbsp;... but it is my thinking that we should avoid making [Yasukuni visits] political and diplomatic issues\". In lieu of visiting, Abe sent ritual offerings to the shrine for festivals in April and October 2013, as well as the anniversary of the end of World War II in August 2013.<ref>{{cite news|title=Abe unlikely to visit Yasukuni by year-end in consideration for ties with neighbors |url=http://mainichi.jp/english/english/newsselect/news/20131225p2a00m0na009000c.html |accessdate=26 December 2013 |newspaper=Mainichi Shimbun |date=25 December 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131227003151/http://mainichi.jp/english/english/newsselect/news/20131225p2a00m0na009000c.html |archivedate=27 December 2013}}</ref>\n\nHis first visit to the shrine as prime minister took place on 26 December 2013, the first anniversary of his second term in office. It was the first visit to the shrine by a sitting prime minister since Junichiro Koizumi visited in August 2006. Abe said that he \"prayed to pay respect for the war dead who sacrificed their precious lives and hoped that they rest in peace\". The Chinese government published a protest that day, calling government visits to the shrine \"an effort to glorify the Japanese militaristic history of external invasion and colonial rule and to challenge the outcome of World War II\".<ref>{{cite news|title=Japanese prime minister visits Yasukuni war shrine |url=http://mainichi.jp/english/english/newsselect/news/20131226p2g00m0dm032000c.html |accessdate=26 December 2013 |newspaper=Associated Press |date=26 December 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131227012900/http://mainichi.jp/english/english/newsselect/news/20131226p2g00m0dm032000c.html |archivedate=27 December 2013}}</ref> Qin Gang of the Chinese [[Ministry of Foreign Affairs of the People's Republic of China|Ministry of Foreign Affairs]] said Abe is \"unwelcome by Chinese people&nbsp;... Chinese leaders won't meet him any more\".<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.sina.com.cn/c/2013-12-31/023529123438.shtml|title=Chinese Make it Clear Blocking Abe|language=Chinese|accessdate=31 December 2013|date=27 December 2013|location=Beijing|newspaper=Sina News}}</ref> The ''[[Mainichi Shimbun]]'' argued in an editorial that the visit could also \"cast a dark shadow\" on relations with the United States,<ref>{{cite news|title=Abe's Yasukuni visit could cast dark shadow on Japanese foreign diplomacy |url=http://mainichi.jp/english/english/newsselect/news/20131226p2a00m0na004000c.html |accessdate=26 December 2013 |newspaper=Mainichi Shimbun |date=26 December 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131227013006/http://mainichi.jp/english/english/newsselect/news/20131226p2a00m0na004000c.html |archivedate=27 December 2013}}</ref> and the US embassy in Tokyo released a statement that \"the United States is disappointed that Japan's leadership has taken an action that will exacerbate tensions with Japan's neighbors\".<ref>{{cite web|title=Statement on Prime Minister Abe's December 26 Visit to Yasukuni Shrine|url=http://japan.usembassy.gov/e/p/tp-20131226-01.html|publisher=U.S. Department of State|accessdate=26 December 2013|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131226225952/http://japan.usembassy.gov/e/p/tp-20131226-01.html|archivedate=26 December 2013}}</ref> ''[[The Wall Street Journal]]'' reported that U.S. officials urge Abe not to visit the shrine and pay homage to war criminals anymore.<ref>{{cite news|title=U.S. Seeks Abe Assurance He Won't Visit War Shrine|url=https://online.wsj.com/news/articles/SB10001424052702304757004579331951101919562?mg=reno64-wsj&url=http%3A%2F%2Fonline.wsj.com%2Farticle%2FSB10001424052702304757004579331951101919562.html|accessdate=24 January 2014|date=23 January 2014|newspaper=The Wall Street Journal}}</ref> Public intellectual [[Amitai Etzioni]] of the Institute for Communitarian Policy Studies, who was a child in Germany when the Nazis rose to power, has stated in response to Abe's visits, \"Unlike Japan, [Germany] faced their past, came to terms with it and learned from it. Japan should do the same.\"<ref>Chen Weihua, \"Japan should learn from Germany: US expert\", ''China Daily'', 29 January 2014, [http://usa.chinadaily.com.cn/2014-01/29/content_17263869.htm].</ref> Etzioni criticized Prime Minister Abe's visit to the shrine as well as what he refers to as Japan's recent \"nationalist wave\" in an op-ed for ''[[The Diplomat]]''.<ref>Etzioni, Amitai, \"Japan Should Follow--Germany\", ''The Diplomat'', 6 February 2014, [http://thediplomat.com/2014/02/japan-should-follow-germany/].</ref> On 15 August 2014, the 69th anniversary of the surrender of Japan in World War II, Abe chose to not visit the shrine, in what was perceived as a diplomatic gesture to South Korea, China and Taiwan. Despite Abe's absence, China and South Korea both voiced their disapproval at Japan's leadership as a large number of politicians, and three cabinet members, did attend the shrine to mark the anniversary.<ref name=\"AbeAbsence\">{{cite news|title=Abe avoids war shrine to placate neighbours on WWII surrender anniversary|url=http://www.thejapannews.net/index.php/sid/224785741|date=15 August 2014|accessdate=15 August 2014|publisher=The Japan News.Net}}</ref>\n\n===Restoration of Sovereignty Day===\nOn 28 April 2013, a new public event, the [[Restoration of Sovereignty Day]], was held in Tokyo to mark the 61st anniversary of the end of the US [[occupation of Japan]]. It had been proposed by Abe in 2012. The event, which was attended by [[Emperor Akihito]], was denounced by many Okinawans who saw it as celebrating a betrayal, and there were demonstrations in both [[Okinawa]] and Tokyo.<ref name=\"bbc rsd\">{{cite web|title=Japan marks 'return of sovereignty' day|date=28 April 2013|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-asia-22330635|publisher=BBC News|accessdate=28 April 2013}}</ref>\n\n===Migration===\nIn 2015, Abe's government refused to admit [[refugee]]s affected by conflicts in the Middle East and Africa. Abe stated that Japan must solve its own problems before accepting any immigrants.<ref>\"[https://www.theguardian.com/world/2015/sep/30/japan-says-it-must-look-after-its-own-before-allowing-syrian-refugees-in Japan says it must look after its own before allowing in Syrian refugees]\". ''The Guardian''. 30 September 2015.</ref> Abe has favored short-term working visas for migrant workers to \"work and raise incomes for a limited period of time, and then return home\".<ref>\"[http://thediplomat.com/2015/03/japan-abe-misses-chance-on-immigration-debate/ Japan: Abe Misses Chance on Immigration Debate]\". ''[[The Diplomat]]'' 6 March 2015.</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\n[[File:Foreign Leader Visits (34617655472).jpg|thumb|Abe and his wife Akie Abe with Donald and Melania Trump]]\nAbe's father Shintaro Abe served in the House of Representatives from 1958 to 1991 and was foreign minister from 1982 to 1986; he is the son of Kan Abe, who served in the House from 1937 to 1946. Abe's mother, Yoko Abe, is the daughter of [[Nobusuke Kishi]], a wartime cabinet minister imprisoned as a \"Class A\" [[Japanese war crimes|war crimes]] suspect following the war, who by 1957 had become Japanese prime minister.<ref name=\"akie\">{{cite news|title=Akie Abe not afraid to speak her mind|url=http://www.japantoday.com/category/kuchikomi/view/akie-abe-not-afraid-to-speak-her-mind|accessdate=15 January 2014|newspaper=Japan Today|date=4 January 2014}}</ref> His older brother, Hironobu Abe, became president and CEO of Mitsubishi Sh\u014dji Packaging Corporation, while his younger brother, [[Nobuo Kishi]], became Senior Vice-Minister for Foreign Affairs.\n\nAbe married [[Akie Abe|Akie Matsuzaki]], a socialite and former radio disc jockey, in 1987. She is the daughter of the president of [[Morinaga]], a chocolate manufacturer. She is popularly known as the \"domestic opposition party\" due to her outspoken views, which often contradict her husband's. Following her husband's first stint as prime minister, she opened an organic [[izakaya]] in the [[Kanda, Tokyo|Kanda]] district of Tokyo, but is not active in management due to the urging of her mother-in-law.<ref name=\"akie\" /> The couple have no children, having undergone unsuccessful fertility treatments earlier in their marriage.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/asia-pacific/6044608.stm|title=BBC NEWS \u2013 Asia-Pacific \u2013 Japan PM's wife in rare interview|accessdate=14 December 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn addition to his native Japanese, Abe speaks English.<ref>{{cite web |title=Shinzo Abe Addresses Australian Parliament (July 8, 2014) |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=YjQfgEsMMBA |website=YouTube |publisher=Malcolm Farnsworth |accessdate=15 December 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Prime Minister Shinzo Abe of Japan's Address to a Joint Meeting of Congress |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=pzy4exj0YPg |website=YouTube |publisher=John Boehner |accessdate=15 December 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Davos 2014 \u2013 The Reshaping of the World Vision from Japan |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ApRaK516PZU |website=YouTube |publisher=World Economic Forum |accessdate=15 December 2018}}</ref>\n\n== Honors, awards and international recognition ==\n{{More citations needed section|date=December 2019}}\n[[File:Gurtnyyaz Nurlyyewic Hanmyradow and Shinzo Abe 20151023.jpg|thumb|Gurtnyyaz Nurlyyewic Hanmyradow and Shinzo Abe in Turkmenistan]]\n\n=== Honors ===\n* [[File:Spange des K\u00f6nig-Abdulaziz-Ordens.png|30px]] Member Special Class of the [[Order of Abdulaziz Al Saud]], April 2007.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.47news.jp/CN/200704/CN2007042901000062.html|title=\u77f3\u6cb9\u5099\u84c4\u3067\u57fa\u5730\u63d0\u4f9b\u63d0\u6848 \u5b89\u500d\u9996\u76f8\u3001\u30b5\u30a6\u30b8\u56fd\u738b\u306b|work=47news|date=29 April 2007|accessdate=18 July 2013|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130922174128/http://www.47news.jp/CN/200704/CN2007042901000062.html|archivedate=22 September 2013}}</ref> ({{Flag|Saudi Arabia}})\n* [[File:GRE Order of Honour Grand Cross BAR.png|30px]] Grand Cross of the [[Order of Honour (Greece)|Order of Honour]]. ({{Flag|Greece}})\n* Member First Class of the [[Shaikh Isa bin Salman Al Khalifa Order]], August 2013. ({{Flag|Bahrain}})\n* [[File:Cote d'Ivoire Ordre du merite ivoirien GC ribbon.svg|30px]] Grand Cross of the [[Order of Ivory Merit]], January 2014. ({{Flag|Ivory Coast}})\n* [[File:NLD Order of Orange-Nassau - Knight Grand Cross BAR.png|30px]] Knight Grand Cross of the [[Order of Orange-Nassau]], October 2014.<ref>[http://www.koninklijkhuis.nl/nieuws/nieuwsberichten/2014/oktober/decoraties-staatsbezoeken-japan-en-republiek-korea/ Decoraties Staatsbezoeken Japan en Republiek Korea] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141104190003/https://www.koninklijkhuis.nl/nieuws/nieuwsberichten/2014/oktober/decoraties-staatsbezoeken-japan-en-republiek-korea/ |date= 4 November 2014}} \u2013 website of the Dutch Royal House</ref> ({{flag|Netherlands}})\n* [[File:PHL Order of Sikatuna - Grand Cross BAR.png|30px]] Grand Collar of the [[Order of Sikatuna]], Rank of Raja 3 June 2015.<ref>[http://globalnation.inquirer.net/123845/aquino-flies-to-japan-for-four-day-state-visit-exchange-of-top-honors] - website of Inquirer.net</ref> ({{Flag|Philippines}})\n* [[File:ESP Isabella Catholic Order GC.svg|30px]] Grand Cross of the [[Order of Isabella the Catholic]], 2017.<ref>[https://www.boe.es/buscar/doc.php?id=BOE-A-2017-4552] - website of Inquirer.net, Spanish Official Journal (In Spanish)</ref> ({{Flag|Spain}})\n* [[File:LUX Order of the Oak Crown - Grand Cross BAR.png|30px]] Grand Cross of the [[Order of the Oak Crown]], 2017. ({{Flag|Luxembourg}})\n\n=== Awards ===\n* [[FP Top 100 Global Thinkers|2013 ''Foreign Policy'' Top 100 Global Thinkers]], 2013. ({{flag|US}})\n* [[Hudson Institute|Herman Kahn Award]], September 2013. ({{flag|US}})\n* [[The Straits Times|Asian of the Year award]], December 2013. ({{flag|Singapore}})\n* [[Time 100|Time 100 in 2014]], April 2014. ({{flag|US}})\n* [[Time 100|Time 100 in 2018]], 2018. ({{flag|US}})\n* Boston Global Forum's World Leader in Cybersecurity Award, December 2015.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://bostonglobalforum.org/category/global-cybersecurity-day/world-leaders-awards/world-leaders-awards-2015/ |title=Archived copy |access-date=15 October 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190604063404/https://bostonglobalforum.org/category/global-cybersecurity-day/world-leaders-awards/world-leaders-awards-2015/ |archive-date=4 June 2019 |url-status=dead }}</ref> ({{flag|US}})\n\n=== Honorary doctorates ===\n* [[Rangsit University]], March 2013. ({{Flag|Thailand}})\n* [[Jawaharlal Nehru University]], December 2015. ({{Flag|India}})\n* [[Turkmen State University]], October 2015.<ref>[https://turkmenportal.com/blog/6730]</ref> ({{Flag|Turkmenistan}})\n\n==Cabinets==\n\n===First stint (2006&ndash;2007)===\nAbe's first cabinet was announced on 26 September 2006. The only minister retained in his position from the previous Koizumi cabinet was Foreign Minister Taro Aso, who had been one of Abe's competitors for the LDP presidency. In addition to the cabinet positions existing under Koizumi, Abe created five new \"advisor\" positions.\nHe reshuffled his cabinet on 27 August 2007.<ref>[http://www.japannewsreview.com/politics/politics/20070827page_id=1814 Abe attempts to save his LDP with Cabinet reshuffle] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071006084325/http://www.japannewsreview.com/politics/politics/20070827page_id=1814 |date=6 October 2007 }}, ''Japan News Review'', 27 August 2007.</ref>\n\n{|class=\"wikitable\" style=\"font-size: 80%;\"\n|-\n! !! First<br />(26 September 2006) !! First, Realigned<br />(27 August 2007) \n|-\n! [[Chief Cabinet Secretary|Secretary]]\n|[[Yasuhisa Shiozaki]] ||[[Kaoru Yosano]]\n|-\n! [[Minister of Internal Affairs and Communications (Japan)|Internal Affairs]]\n|[[Yoshihide Suga]] ||[[Hiroya Masuda]]\n|-\n! [[Minister of Justice|Justice]]\n|[[Jinen Nagase]] ||[[Kunio Hatoyama]]\n|-\n! [[Minister of Foreign Affairs|Foreign Affairs]]\n|[[Tar\u014d As\u014d]] ||[[Nobutaka Machimura]]\n|-\n! [[Minister of Finance|Finance]]\n|[[K\u014dji Omi]] ||[[Fukushiro Nukaga]]\n|-\n! [[Minister of Education, Culture, Sports, Science and Technology (Japan)|Education]]\n|colspan=\"2\" |[[Bunmei Ibuki]]\n|-\n! [[Minister of Health, Labour and Welfare (Japan)|Health]]\n|[[Hakuo Yanagisawa]] ||[[Y\u014dichi Masuzoe]]\n|-\n! [[Minister of Agriculture, Forestry and Fisheries (Japan)|Agriculture]]\n|[[Toshikatsu Matsuoka]] <sup>1</sup><br />[[Norihiko Akagi]]<sup>1</sup> ||[[Masatoshi Wakabayashi]]<sup>2</sup>\n|-\n! [[Minister of Economy, Trade and Industry (Japan)|Economy]]\n|colspan=\"2\" |[[Akira Amari]]\n|-\n! [[Minister of Land, Infrastructure and Transport|Land]]\n|colspan=\"2\" |[[Tetsuzo Fuyushiba]]\n|-\n! [[Minister of the Environment|Environment]]\n|[[Masatoshi Wakabayashi|Masatoshi&nbsp;Wakabayashi]]&nbsp;<sup>1</sup> ||[[Ichir\u014d Kamoshita]]\n|-\n! [[Minister of Defense (Japan)|Defense]]<sup>3</sup>\n|[[Fumio Ky\u016bma]] <sup>4</sup>||[[Masahiko K\u014dmura]]\n|-\n! [[National Public Safety Commission (Japan)|Public Safety]],<br />Disaster Prevention\n|[[Kensei Mizote]] ||[[Shinya Izumi]]\n|-\n! Economic and Fiscal Policy\n|colspan=\"2\" |[[Hiroko \u014cta]]\n|-\n! Financial Policy\n|[[Yuji Yamamoto]] ||rowspan=\"2\" |[[Yoshimi Watanabe]]\n|-\n! Administrative Reform\n|rowspan=\"2\" |[[Yoshimi Watanabe]] <sup>5</sup>\n|-\n! Regulatory Reform\n|rowspan=\"2\" |[[Fumio Kishida]]\n|-\n! Okinawa/Northern Territories, Technology\n|rowspan=\"2\" |[[Sanae Takaichi]]\n|-\n! Birth Rate, Youth and Gender Equality\n||[[Y\u014dko Kamikawa]]\n|-\n! National Security Advisor\n|colspan=\"2\" |[[Yuriko Koike]]\n|-\n! Economic Policy Advisor\n|colspan=\"2\" |[[Takumi Nemoto]]\n|-\n! [[Minister for the Abduction Issue|North Korean Abductions Advisor]]\n|colspan=\"2\" |[[Kyoko Nakayama]]\n|-\n! Education Advisor\n|colspan=\"2\" |[[Eriko Yamatani]]\n|-\n! Public Relations Advisor\n|colspan=\"2\" |[[Hiroshige Sek\u014d]]\n|}\n\nNotes:\n# [[Toshikatsu Matsuoka]] committed suicide on 28 May 2007, hours before being due for questioning in connection to allegations of misappropriation of government funds. He was replaced by Norihiko Akagi, who himself resigned on 1 August 2007 due to suspicions of similar conduct. [[Masatoshi Wakabayashi]] was appointed Agriculture Minister, which he served concurrently with his post as Environment Minister.\n# Masatoshi Wakabayashi was appointed Agriculture Minister on 3 September 2007, following [[Takehiko Endo]]'s resignation due to a financial scandal.\n# Prior to Abe's administration, this post was known as \"Director General of the Defense Agency\". In December 2006, its status was elevated to ministry level.\n# [[Fumio Ky\u016bma]] resigned on 3 July 2007 for controversial remarks made about the atomic bombing of Hiroshima. He was replaced by [[Yuriko Koike]], then National Security Advisor.\n# [[Yoshimi Watanabe]] was appointed Minister of State for Administrative Reform upon 28 December 2007 resignation of [[Genichiro Sata]]. He served in this capacity concurrently with his role as Minister of State for Regulatory Reform.\n\n===Second stint (2012&ndash;present)===\n{|class=\"wikitable\" style=\"font-size: 80%;\"\n|-\n! !! Second<br />(26 December 2012) !! Second, Realigned<br />(3 September 2014) !! Third<br />(24 December 2014) !! Third, Realigned<br />(7 October 2015) !! Third, Realigned<br />(3 August 2016) !! Third, Realigned<br />(3 August 2017) !! Fourth<br />(1 November 2017) !! Fourth, Realigned<br />(2 October 2018) !! Fourth, Realigned<br />(11 September 2019)\n|-\n! [[Chief Cabinet Secretary|Secretary]]\n| style=\"text-align: center;\" colspan=\"9\" |[[Yoshihide Suga]]\n|-\n! [[Minister of Internal Affairs and Communications (Japan)|Internal Affairs]]\n|[[Yoshitaka Shind\u014d]] ||colspan=\"4\" |[[Sanae Takaichi]] || colspan=\"2\" |[[Seiko Noda]] || [[Masatoshi Ishida (politician)|Masatoshi Ishida]] || [[Sanae Takaichi]]\n|-\n! [[Minister of Justice (Japan)|Justice]]\n|[[Sadakazu Tanigaki]] ||[[Midori Matsushima]] replaced by [[Y\u014dko Kamikawa]] (2014/10/20) ||[[Y\u014dko Kamikawa]] || [[Mitsuhide Iwaki]] || [[Katsutoshi Kaneda]] || colspan=\"2\" |[[Y\u014dko Kamikawa]] || [[Takashi Yamashita]] || [[Katsuyuki Kawai]] replaced by [[Masako Mori (politician)|Masako Mori]] (2019/10/31)\n|-\n! [[Minister of Foreign Affairs (Japan)|Foreign Affairs]]\n|colspan=\"5\" style=\"text-align: center;\"|[[Fumio Kishida]] || colspan=\"3\" |[[Tar\u014d K\u014dno]] || [[Toshimitsu Motegi]]\n|-\n! [[Deputy Prime Minister of Japan|Deputy Prime Minister]], Financial Services, [[Minister of Finance|Finance]]\n|colspan=\"9\" style=\"text-align: center;\"|[[Tar\u014d As\u014d]]\n|-\n! [[Minister of Education, Culture, Sports, Science and Technology (Japan)|Education]], Educational Reform\n|colspan=\"3\" |[[Hakubun Shimomura]] || [[Hiroshi Hase]] || [[Hirokazu Matsuno]] || colspan=\"2\" |[[Yoshimasa Hayashi]] || [[Masahiko Shibayama]] || [[K\u014dichi Hagiuda]]\n|-\n! [[Minister of Health, Labour and Welfare (Japan)|Health]]\n|[[Norihisa Tamura]] ||colspan=\"4\" |[[Yasuhisa Shiozaki]] || colspan=\"2\" |[[Katsunobu Kat\u014d]] || [[Takumi Nemoto]] || [[Katsunobu Kat\u014d]] \n|-\n! [[Minister of Agriculture, Forestry and Fisheries (Japan)|Agriculture]]\n|[[Yoshimasa Hayashi]] ||colspan=\"2\" |[[Koya Nishikawa]] replaced by [[Yoshimasa Hayashi]] (2015/2/23) ||[[Hiroshi Moriyama]] ||[[Yuji Yamamoto]] || colspan=\"2\" |[[Ken Sait\u014d]] || [[Takamori Yoshikawa]] || [[Taku Et\u014d]]\n|-\n! [[Minister of Economy, Trade and Industry (Japan)|Economy]]\n||[[Toshimitsu Motegi]] ||[[Y\u016bko Obuchi]] replaced by [[Yoichi Miyazawa]] (2014/10/20) || [[Yoichi Miyazawa]] ||[[Motoo Hayashi]] || colspan=\"4\" |[[Hiroshige Sek\u014d]] || [[Isshu Sugawara]] replaced by [[Hiroshi Kajiyama (politician)|Hiroshi Kajiyama]] (2019/10/25)\n|-\n! [[Minister of Land, Infrastructure, Transport and Tourism|Land]]\n|colspan=\"3\" |[[Akihiro Ota]] ||colspan=\"5\" | [[Keiichi Ishii]] || [[Kazuyoshi Akaba]]\n|-\n! [[Minister of the Environment (Japan)|Environment]], Nuclear Crisis Management\n|[[Nobuteru Ishihara]] ||colspan=\"2\" |[[Yoshio Mochizuki]] ||[[Tamayo Marukawa]] ||[[Koichi Yamamoto]] || colspan=\"2\" |[[Masaharu Nakagawa (House of Councillors)|Masaharu Nakagawa]] || [[Yoshiaki Harada]] || [[Shinjir\u014d Koizumi]]\n|-\n! [[Minister of Defense (Japan)|Defense]]<sup>3</sup>\n|[[Itsunori Onodera]] ||[[Akinori Eto]]||colspan=\"2\"|[[Gen Nakatani]]  || [[Tomomi Inada]] || colspan=\"2\" |[[Itsunori Onodera]] || [[Takeshi Iwaya]] || [[Tar\u014d K\u014dno]]\n|-\n! [[National Public Safety Commission (Japan)|Public Safety]],<br /> Measures for National Land Strengthening and Disaster Management\n|[[Keiji Furuya]] ||colspan=\"2\" |[[Eriko Yamatani]] || [[Tar\u014d K\u014dno]] ||[[Jun Matsumoto (politician)|Jun Matsumoto]] || colspan=\"2\" |[[Hachiro Okonogi]] || [[Junzo Yamamoto]] || [[Ryota Takeda]] \n|-\n! Economic and Fiscal Policy and Economic Revitalisation\n|colspan=\"4\" |[[Akira Amari]] replaced by [[Nobuteru Ishihara]] (2016/1/28) || [[Nobuteru Ishihara]] || colspan=\"3\" |[[Toshimitsu Motegi]] || [[Yasutoshi Nishimura]]\n|-\n! Disaster Reconstruction\n|[[Takumi Nemoto]] ||colspan=\"2\" |[[Wataru Takeshita]] || [[Tsuyoshi Takagi]] || [[Masahiro Imamura]] replaced by [[Yoichi Miyazawa]] (2017/4/26) || colspan=\"2\"|[[Masayoshi Yoshino]] || [[Hiromichi Watanabe]] || [[Kazunori Tanaka]]\n|-\n! Administrative Reform and Public Servant System Reforms\n|[[Tomomi Inada]] ||colspan=\"2\" |[[Haruko Arimura]] ||  [[Tar\u014d K\u014dno]] || [[Kozo Yamamoto]] || colspan=\"2\" |[[Hiroshi Kajiyama (politician)|Hiroshi Kajiyama]] || [[Mitsuhiro Miyakoshi]] || [[Ryota Takeda]]\n|-\n! Okinawa/Northern Territories\n|[[Ichita Yamamoto]] ||colspan=\"2\" |[[Shunichi Yamaguchi]] || [[Aiko Shimajiri]] || [[Y\u014dsuke Tsuruho]] || colspan=\"2\" |[[Tetsuma Esaki]] replaced by [[Teru Fukui]] (2018/2/27) || [[Mitsuhiro Miyakoshi]] || [[Seiichi Eto]]\n|-\n! Birth Rate\n||[[Masako Mori (politician)|Masako Mori]] ||colspan=\"2\" |[[Haruko Arimura]] ||colspan=\"5\" |[[Katsunobu Kat\u014d]] || [[Seiichi Eto]]\n|-\n! National Security Advisor\n|colspan=\"9\" style=\"text-align: center;\"|[[Shotaro Yachi]] \n|-\n! Economic Policy Advisor\n|| - || - || - || - || - || - || - || - || -\n|-\n! [[Minister for the Abduction Issue|North Korean Abductions Advisor]]\n|[[Keiji Furuya]] ||colspan=\"2\" |[[Eriko Yamatani]] ||colspan=\"5\" |[[Katsunobu Kat\u014d]] || [[Yoshihide Suga]]\n|-\n! Education Advisor\n| - || - || - || - || - || - || - || - || -\n|-\n! Public Relations Advisor\n| - || - || - || - || - || - || - || - || -\n|-\n! Regional Economy\n| - ||colspan=\"3\" |[[Shigeru Ishiba]] || [[Kozo Yamamoto]] || colspan=\"2\" |[[Hiroshi Kajiyama (politician)|Hiroshi Kajiyama]] || [[Satsuki Katayama]] || [[Seigo Kitamura]]\n|-\n! Olympics and Paralympics\n| - ||- ||colspan=\"2\" |[[Toshiaki Endo]] (from 2015/06/25) || [[Tamayo Marukawa]] || colspan=\"2\" |[[Shun'ichi Suzuki (politician)|Shunichi Suzuki]] || [[Yoshitaka Sakurada]] replaced by [[Shun'ichi Suzuki (politician)|Shunichi Suzuki]] (2019/4/11) || [[Seiko Hashimoto]]\n|-\n! Minister for Promoting Dynamic Engagement of All Citizens, and other\n|| - || - || - || colspan=\"2\" |[[Katsunobu Kat\u014d]] || colspan=\"2\" |[[Masaji Matsuyama]] || [[Mitsuhiro Miyakoshi]] || [[Seiichi Eto]]\n|}\n\n<ref>{{cite web|last1=Kantei|title=List of Ministers|url=http://japan.kantei.go.jp/97_abe/meibo/daijin/index_e.html|website=Prime Minister of Japan and His Cabinet|accessdate=4 August 2016}}</ref><ref>[http://arquivo.pt/wayback/20090627095325/http://www.yomiuri.co.jp/dy/national/0001/ ''Yomiuri Shimbun'', \"Cabinet Lineup\", 28 Dec. 2012]</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Kameda|first1=Masaaki|last2=Kyodo News Agency|title=Farm minister Nishikawa resigns over donation scandal|url=http://www.japantimes.co.jp/news/2015/02/23/national/politics-diplomacy/farm-minister-nishikawa-resigns-in-funding-scandal/#.VOuyJvmsWSo|accessdate=24 February 2015|work=The Japan Times|date=23 February 2015}}</ref><ref>[http://japan.kantei.go.jp/97_abe/cabinetlist1/daijin/index_e.html/ Kantei; \"List of Ministers (The Cabinet)\" (25 June 2015). Retrieved 25 December 2015.] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160914064705/http://japan.kantei.go.jp/97_abe/cabinetlist1/daijin/index_e.html/ |date=14 September 2016 }}</ref><ref>[http://japan.kantei.go.jp/97_abe/meibo/daijin/index_e.html/ Kantei; \"List of Ministers (The Cabinet)\" (7 Oct 2015). Retrieved 25 December 2015.] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151104111345/http://japan.kantei.go.jp/97_abe/meibo/daijin/index_e.html/ |date=4 November 2015 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://ajw.asahi.com/article/behind_news/politics/AJ201401080046|title=New national security bureau faces rocky start|author=Katsuhisa Kuramae|date=8 January 2014|work=The Asahi Shimbun|accessdate=25 December 2015|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140125104958/http://ajw.asahi.com/article/behind_news/politics/AJ201401080046|archivedate=25 January 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://uk.reuters.com/article/uk-olympics-japan-minister-idUKKBN0P509T20150625|title=Veteran politician Endo named Japan Olympics minister|author1=Elaine Lies  |author2=Kiyoshi Takenaka |lastauthoramp=yes |date=25 June 2015|work=Reuters UK|accessdate=25 December 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-asia-35427563|title=Japanese economy minister Akira Amari quits over bribery claims|date=28 January 2016|work=BBC|accessdate=4 June 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Ancestry==\n{{ahnentafel\n|collapsed=yes |align=center\n|boxstyle_1=background-color: #fcc;\n|boxstyle_2=background-color: #fb9;\n|boxstyle_3=background-color: #ffc;\n|boxstyle_4=background-color: #bfc;\n|boxstyle_5=background-color: #9fe;\n|1= 1. '''Shinz\u014d Abe'''\n|2= 2. [[Shintaro Abe]]\n|3