jin/index_e.html/ |date=14 September 2016 }}</ref><ref>[http://japan.kantei.go.jp/97_abe/meibo/daijin/index_e.html/ Kantei; \"List of Ministers (The Cabinet)\" (7 Oct 2015). Retrieved 25 December 2015.] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151104111345/http://japan.kantei.go.jp/97_abe/meibo/daijin/index_e.html/ |date=4 November 2015 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://ajw.asahi.com/article/behind_news/politics/AJ201401080046|title=New national security bureau faces rocky start|author=Katsuhisa Kuramae|date=8 January 2014|work=The Asahi Shimbun|accessdate=25 December 2015|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140125104958/http://ajw.asahi.com/article/behind_news/politics/AJ201401080046|archivedate=25 January 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://uk.reuters.com/article/uk-olympics-japan-minister-idUKKBN0P509T20150625|title=Veteran politician Endo named Japan Olympics minister|author1=Elaine Lies  |author2=Kiyoshi Takenaka |lastauthoramp=yes |date=25 June 2015|work=Reuters UK|accessdate=25 December 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-asia-35427563|title=Japanese economy minister Akira Amari quits over bribery claims|date=28 January 2016|work=BBC|accessdate=4 June 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Ancestry==\n{{ahnentafel\n|collapsed=yes |align=center\n|boxstyle_1=background-color: #fcc;\n|boxstyle_2=background-color: #fb9;\n|boxstyle_3=background-color: #ffc;\n|boxstyle_4=background-color: #bfc;\n|boxstyle_5=background-color: #9fe;\n|1= 1. '''Shinz\u014d Abe'''\n|2= 2. [[Shintaro Abe]]\n|3= 3. Yoko Kishi\n|4= 4. [[Kan Abe]]\n|5= 5. Shizuko Hond\u014d\n|6= 6. [[Nobusuke Kishi]]\n|7= 7. Yoshiko Kishi\n|8= 8. Abe Ayasuke\n|9= 9. Abe Tame\n|10= 10. Hond\u014d Tsunejir\u014d\n|11= 11. Hideko \u014cshima\n|12= 12. Sat\u014d Hidesuke\n|13= 13. Sat\u014d Moyo\n|14= 14. Kishi Nobumasa\n|22= 22. [[\u014cshima Yoshimasa]]\n|26= 26. Sat\u014d Nobuhiko\n|27= 27. Kunihiro Mine\n}}\n\n==See also==\n{{portal|Conservatism|Japan|Politics}}\n* 