{"title_page": "Russian interference in the 2020 United States elections", "text_new": "Is a left wing conspiracy theory!!\n{{Short description|national security concern}}\n\n{{Use mdy dates|date=July 2019}}\n'''Russian interference in the 2020 United States elections''' has become a question of concern at the highest level of [[National security of the United States|national security]] as well as in the [[computer industry|computer]] and [[social media]] industries.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/politics/politics-features/trump-election-hacking-russia-iran-ransomware-interference-938109/ |title=Hackers Are Coming for the 2020 Election \u2014 And We're Not Ready |first=Andy |last=Kroll |work=[[Rolling Stone]] |date=2020-01-17 |accessdate=2020-01-17 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200117192107/https://www.rollingstone.com/politics/politics-features/trump-election-hacking-russia-iran-ransomware-interference-938109/ |archive-date=January 17, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> In February 2020, the American intelligence community advised members of Congress that Russia was attempting to interfere in the 2020 election.\n\n==Reports of attempted interference==\n\nIn response to [[Russian interference in the 2016 United States elections]], special counsel [[Robert Mueller]] conducted a two-year-long [[Special Counsel investigation (2017\u20132019)|investigation]]. The resulting [[Mueller Report|report]] concluded that Russia interfered in \u201csweeping and systematic fashion\u201d.<ref>''[https://www.justice.gov/storage/report.pdf Mueller Report] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190422095933/https://www.justice.gov/storage/report.pdf |date=April 22, 2019 }}'', vol. I, p. 1: \"The Russian government interfered in the 2016 presidential election in sweeping and systematic fashion\"</ref> In his July 2019 Congressional testimony, Mueller stated that the Russians continue to interfere in U.S. elections \"as we sit here\u201d, and that \"many more countries\" have developed disinformation campaigns targeting U.S. elections, based partly on the Russian model.<ref>{{cite news |title=Mueller rejects Trump's claims of exoneration, 'witch hunt' |work=[[The Washington Post]] |date=2019-07-25 |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/mueller-no-russia-exoneration-for-trump-despite-his-claims/2019/07/24/428d5a0c-ae85-11e9-9411-a608f9d0c2d3_story.html |last1=Tucker |first1=Eric |last2=Jalonick |first2=Mary Clare |last3=Balsamo |first3=Michael |quote=And [Mueller] said of the interference by Russians and others: \"They are doing it as we sit here. And they expect to do it during the next campaign.\" |access-date=July 27, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190727155844/https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/mueller-no-russia-exoneration-for-trump-despite-his-claims/2019/07/24/428d5a0c-ae85-11e9-9411-a608f9d0c2d3_story.html |archive-date=July 27, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |author= |date=July 25, 2019 |url=https://www.cnn.com/2019/07/24/politics/russia-trump-election-interference/index.html |title=Robert Mueller's testimony: The biggest takeaway is Russia's interference in US elections |work=CNN |accessdate=2019-07-26 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190726211452/https://www.cnn.com/2019/07/24/politics/russia-trump-election-interference/index.html |archive-date=July 26, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nAlso in July 2019, the [[Senate Intelligence Committee]] released the first volume of a bipartisan report on Russian interference in the 2016 United States elections, a report that included recommendations for securing the 2020 elections.<ref>{{cite news |title=Russia Targeted Election Systems in All 50 States, Report Finds |work=[[The New York Times]] |date=2019-07-25 |last1=Sanger |first1=David E. |authorlink1=David E. Sanger |last2=Edmondson |first2=Catie |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/07/25/us/politics/russian-hacking-elections.html |quote=But while the bipartisan report's warning that the United States remains vulnerable in the next election is clear, its findings were so heavily redacted at the insistence of American intelligence agencies that even some key recommendations for 2020 were blacked out. |access-date=July 27, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190727201549/https://www.nytimes.com/2019/07/25/us/politics/russian-hacking-elections.html |archive-date=July 27, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.intelligence.senate.gov/sites/default/files/documents/Report_Volume1.pdf |title=Report of the Select Committee on Intelligence, United States Senate, on Russian Active Measures, Campaigns, and Interference in the 2016 U.S. Election |access-date=2019-07-27 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190727210348/https://www.intelligence.senate.gov/sites/default/files/documents/Report_Volume1.pdf |archive-date=July 27, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> The second volume of that report noted, based on social-media data from October 2018, that \"Russian disinformation efforts may be focused on gathering information and data points in support of an active measures campaign targeted at the 2020 U.S. presidential election.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.intelligence.senate.gov/sites/default/files/documents/Report_Volume2.pdf |title=Report of the Select Committee on Intelligence, United States Senate, on Russian Active Measures, Campaigns, and Interference in the 2016 U.S. Election, Volume 2 |access-date=2019-10-08 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191008172455/https://www.intelligence.senate.gov/sites/default/files/documents/Report_Volume2.pdf |archive-date=October 8, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nU.S. officials have accused [[Russia]], [[China]] and [[Iran]] of trying to influence the 2020 elections.<ref>{{cite news |title=US warns of 'ongoing' election interference by Russia, China, Iran |url=https://thehill.com/policy/national-security/412292-us-warns-of-ongoing-election-interference-by-russia-china-iran |work=The Hill |date=October 19, 2018 |access-date=October 4, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191006082404/https://thehill.com/policy/national-security/412292-us-warns-of-ongoing-election-interference-by-russia-china-iran |archive-date=October 6, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=U.S. Sees Russia, China, Iran Trying to Influence 2020 Elections |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2019-06-24/u-s-sees-russia-china-iran-trying-to-influence-2020-elections |work=Bloomberg |date=June 24, 2019 |access-date=October 4, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191006082404/https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2019-06-24/u-s-sees-russia-china-iran-trying-to-influence-2020-elections |archive-date=October 6, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=US says Russia, China and Iran are trying to influence 2020 elections |url=https://www.thenational.ae/world/the-americas/us-says-russia-china-and-iran-are-trying-to-influence-2020-elections-1.878647 |work=The National |date=June 25, 2019 |access-date=October 4, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191006082401/https://www.thenational.ae/world/the-americas/us-says-russia-china-and-iran-are-trying-to-influence-2020-elections-1.878647 |archive-date=October 6, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=2020 Election Meddling by China, Iran, N. Korea Likely, Administration Officials Warn |url=https://news.yahoo.com/2020-election-meddling-china-iran-090500666.html |work=Yahoo News |date=June 28, 2019 |access-date=October 4, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191006082400/https://news.yahoo.com/2020-election-meddling-china-iran-090500666.html |archive-date=October 6, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> Between January and late July 2017, [[Twitter]] identified and shut down over 7,000 phony accounts created by [[Iran]]ian influence operations.<ref name=\"auto\">{{cite news |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/technology/2019/07/25/its-not-just-russians-anymore-iranians-others-turn-up-disinformation-efforts-ahead-vote/ |title=It's not just the Russians anymore as Iranians and others turn up disinformation efforts ahead of 2020 vote |date=2019-07-25 |website=[[The Washington Post]] |accessdate=2019-07-27 |last1=Timberg |first1=Craig |last2=Romm |first2=Tony |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190728001957/https://www.washingtonpost.com/technology/2019/07/25/its-not-just-russians-anymore-iranians-others-turn-up-disinformation-efforts-ahead-vote/ |archive-date=July 28, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> According to [[Christopher A. Wray]], the [[Director of the Federal Bureau of Investigation]], Russia is attempting to interfere with the [[2020 United States elections]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-usa-election-security-idUSKCN1UI1XW|title=FBI Director Wray: Russia intent on interfering with U.S. elections|date=July 23, 2019|work=Reuters|accessdate=July 24, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190723221517/https://www.reuters.com/article/us-usa-election-security-idUSKCN1UI1XW|archive-date=July 23, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"goldman-nyt\">{{cite news |first=Adam |last=Goldman |authorlink=Adam Goldman |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/04/26/us/politics/fbi-russian-election-interference.html |title=F.B.I. Warns of Russian Interference in 2020 Race and Boosts Counterintelligence Operations |work=The New York Times |date=April 26, 2019 |accessdate=2019-07-24 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190724161858/https://www.nytimes.com/2019/04/26/us/politics/fbi-russian-election-interference.html |archive-date=July 24, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Russian Internet Trolls Are Apparently Switching Strategies for 2020 U.S. Elections |url=https://time.com/5548544/russian-internet-trolls-strategies-2020-elections/ |website=[[Time (magazine)|Time]] |date=2019-03-09 |accessdate=2019-07-27 |last=Sebenius |first=Alyza |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190618030544/https://time.com/5548544/russian-internet-trolls-strategies-2020-elections/ |archive-date=June 18, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> Speaking to the [[Council on Foreign Relations]] in July 2019, Wray stated, \"We are very much viewing 2018 as just kind of a dress rehearsal for the big show in 2020.\"<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/2019/07/25/brief-history-administration-officials-warning-that-our-elections-are-risk-russia/ |title=A brief history of administration officials warning that our elections are at risk from Russia |last=Bump |first=Philip |work=[[The Washington Post]] |date=2019-07-25 |accessdate=2019-07-29 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190729132406/https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/2019/07/25/brief-history-administration-officials-warning-that-our-elections-are-risk-russia/ |archive-date=July 29, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> [[Dan Coats]], the former [[Director of National Intelligence]], believes that Russia and China will both attempt to influence the elections.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.nbcnews.com/politics/national-security/u-s-intel-agencies-russia-china-plotting-interfere-2020-election-n963896 |title=U.S. intel agencies: Russia and China plotting to interfere in 2020 election |website=[[NBC News]] |date=2019-01-29 |accessdate=2019-07-24 |last=Dilanian |first=Ken |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190724194211/https://www.nbcnews.com/politics/national-security/u-s-intel-agencies-russia-china-plotting-interfere-2020-election-n963896 |archive-date=July 24, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.intelligence.senate.gov/sites/default/files/documents/os-dcoats-012919.pdf |title=Worldwide Threat Assessment of the US Intelligence Community |first=Daniel R. |last=Coats |authorlink=Dan Coats |accessdate=2019-07-27 |date=2019-01-29 |website=[[United States Senate Select Committee on Intelligence]] |quote=Russia's social media efforts will continue to focus on aggravating social and racial tensions, undermining trust in authorities, and criticizing perceived anti-Russia politicians.  Moscow may employ additional influence toolkits\u2014such as spreading disinformation, conducting hack-and-leak operations, or manipulating data\u2014in a more targeted fashion to influence US policy, actions, and elections. |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190810023229/https://www.intelligence.senate.gov/sites/default/files/documents/os-dcoats-012919.pdf |archive-date=August 10, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nVarious disinformation campaigns on social media have targeted the [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic Party]] candidates running in the [[2020 Democratic Party presidential primaries]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.politico.com/story/2019/02/20/2020-candidates-social-media-attack-1176018 |title='Sustained and ongoing' disinformation assault targets Dem presidential candidates; A coordinated barrage of social media attacks suggests the involvement of foreign state actors. |first=Natasha |last=Korecki |authorlink=Natasha Korecki |date=February 20, 2019 |website=[[Politico.com]] |publisher= |access-date=July 24, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190724011259/https://www.politico.com/story/2019/02/20/2020-candidates-social-media-attack-1176018 |archive-date=July 24, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> This has prompted considerable concern regarding the ability of [[social media]] companies to cope with disinformation and manipulation.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/powerpost/paloma/the-technology-202/2019/06/26/the-technology-202-06262019-tech202/5d129076a7a0a47d87c56e85/ |title=The Technology 202: Social media companies readying to combat disinformation in Democratic debates |website=[[The Washington Post]] |last=Zakrzewski |first=Cat |date=2019-06-26 |accessdate=2019-07-27 |quote=Facebook and Twitter say they're taking additional precautions this week after analysis found debates were a key target for Russian actors seeking to sow discord on social media ahead of the 2016 election. The companies are under immense public pressure to avoid a repeat in 2020 after they say they were caught off guard by the foreign influence operations in 2016. |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190629042008/https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/powerpost/paloma/the-technology-202/2019/06/26/the-technology-202-06262019-tech202/5d129076a7a0a47d87c56e85/ |archive-date=June 29, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.cbsnews.com/news/anti-vax-movement-russian-trolls-fueled-anti-vaccination-debate-in-us-by-spreading-misinformation-twitter-study/ |work=[[CBS News]] |title=Russian trolls fueled anti-vaccination debate in U.S. by spreading misinformation on Twitter, study finds |last=O'Kane |first=Caitlin |date=2019-05-31 |accessdate=2019-07-28 |quote=Facebook also said it would crack down on the spread of vaccine misinformation by de-prioritizing medical myths across the platform ...  however, misinformation about vaccines is not the only threat, as Russia is focusing on spreading misinformation around health care issues ahead of the 2020 election. |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190723003409/https://www.cbsnews.com/news/anti-vax-movement-russian-trolls-fueled-anti-vaccination-debate-in-us-by-spreading-misinformation-twitter-study/ |archive-date=July 23, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> By August 2019, [[Facebook]] and [[Twitter]] had banned advertisements that use misinformation to attempt the suppression of voter turnout.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/technology/2019/08/28/maryland-was-never-play-russians-targeted-it-anyway/ |title=Maryland was never in play in 2016. The Russians targeted it anyway |work=[[The Washington Post]] |date=2019-08-28 |accessdate=2019-08-28 |last1=Priest |first1=Dana |last2=Aljas |first2=Riin |last3=Gelman |first3=Scott |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190828211553/https://www.washingtonpost.com/technology/2019/08/28/maryland-was-never-play-russians-targeted-it-anyway/ |archive-date=August 28, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n[[Microsoft]] developed an open source software called ElectionGuard to help safeguard the 2020 elections.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.npr.org/2019/05/06/720071488/ahead-of-2020-microsoft-unveils-tool-to-allow-voters-to-track-their-ballots |title=Ahead Of 2020, Microsoft Unveils Tool To Allow Voters To Track Their Ballots |work=[[NPR]] |date=2019-05-06 |last=Parks |first=Miles |access-date=July 27, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190727112620/https://www.npr.org/2019/05/06/720071488/ahead-of-2020-microsoft-unveils-tool-to-allow-voters-to-track-their-ballots |archive-date=July 27, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> In mid-July 2019, Microsoft announced that it had, over the prior year, \"notified nearly 10,000 customers they've been targeted or compromised by nation-state attacks\". Based on attacks that had targeted political organizations, and on experience from 2016 and 2018, Microsoft anticipated \"attacks targeting U.S. election systems, political campaigns or NGOs that work closely with campaigns\".<ref>{{cite web |url=https://blogs.microsoft.com/on-the-issues/2019/07/17/new-cyberthreats-require-new-ways-to-protect-democracy/ |title=New cyberthreats require new ways to protect democracy |last=Burt |first=Tom |website=[[Microsoft]] |date=2019-07-17 |accessdate=2019-07-27 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190727025240/https://blogs.microsoft.com/on-the-issues/2019/07/17/new-cyberthreats-require-new-ways-to-protect-democracy/ |archive-date=July 27, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> Of the \"nation-state attacks\" that had originated from Russia, Microsoft claimed that they followed the \"same pattern of engagement\" as Russian operations in 2016 and 2018.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.cbsnews.com/news/iranian-cyber-activity-spiked-after-u-s-withdrawal-from-nuclear-deal-says-microsoft-official/ |title=Iranian cyber activity \"spiked\" after U.S. withdrawal from nuclear deal, says Microsoft official |last=Gazis |first=Olivia |date=2019-07-19 |accessdate=2019-07-27 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190720130910/https://www.cbsnews.com/news/iranian-cyber-activity-spiked-after-u-s-withdrawal-from-nuclear-deal-says-microsoft-official/ |archive-date=July 20, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> On September 20, 2019, Microsoft announced that it would provide free security updates for [[Windows 7]], which reached its [[End-of-life (product)|end-of-life]] on January 14, 2020, on federally-certified voting machines through the 2020 United States elections.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://blogs.microsoft.com/on-the-issues/2019/09/20/extending-free-windows-7-security-updates-to-voting-systems/|title=Extending free Windows 7 security updates to voting systems|last=Burt|first=Tom|date=September 20, 2019|website=Microsoft On The Issues|url-status=live|access-date=December 11, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191218214735/https://blogs.microsoft.com/on-the-issues/2019/09/20/extending-free-windows-7-security-updates-to-voting-systems/|archive-date=December 18, 2019}}</ref> On October 4, 2019, Microsoft announced that \"Phosphorus\", a group of hackers linked to the [[Government of the Islamic Republic of Iran|Iranian government]], had attempted to compromise e-mail accounts belonging to journalists, prominent Iranian expatriates, U.S. government officials and the campaign of a U.S. presidential candidate.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/technology/2019/10/04/iran-tried-hack-us-presidential-candidates-journalists-effort-that-targeted-hundreds-microsoft-finds/ |title=Iranians tried to hack U.S. presidential candidate in effort that targeted hundreds, Microsoft says |date=October 4, 2019 |accessdate=October 4, 2019 |work=[[The Washington Post]] |first1=Jay |last1=Greene |last2=Romm |first2=Tony |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191004175108/https://www.washingtonpost.com/technology/2019/10/04/iran-tried-hack-us-presidential-candidates-journalists-effort-that-targeted-hundreds-microsoft-finds/ |archive-date=October 4, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://blogs.microsoft.com/on-the-issues/2019/10/04/recent-cyberattacks-require-us-all-to-be-vigilant/ |title=Recent cyberattacks require us all to be vigilant |last=Burt |first=Tom |date=October 4, 2019 |accessdate=October 4, 2019 |website=[[Microsoft]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191004174845/https://blogs.microsoft.com/on-the-issues/2019/10/04/recent-cyberattacks-require-us-all-to-be-vigilant/ |archive-date=October 4, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> While Microsoft did not disclose which campaign had been the target of the cyber attack, unnamed sources informed [[Reuters]] that it had been [[Donald Trump 2020 presidential campaign|that of Donald Trump]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Trump campaign targeted by Iran-linked hackers |url=https://www.jpost.com/Breaking-News/Trump-campaign-targeted-by-Iran-linked-hackers-603732 |work=The Jerusalem Post |date=October 4, 2019 |access-date=October 6, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191006084141/https://www.jpost.com/Breaking-News/Trump-campaign-targeted-by-Iran-linked-hackers-603732 |archive-date=October 6, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nOn October 21, 2019, Facebook CEO [[Mark Zuckerberg]] announced that his company has detected a \"highly sophisticated\" set of campaigns to interfere with the 2020 elections. These campaigns originated from Russia and from Iran.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.nbcnews.com/tech/tech-news/mark-zuckerberg-facebook-caught-russia-iran-trying-interfere-2020-n1069366 |title=Mark Zuckerberg: Facebook caught Russia and Iran trying to interfere in 2020 |work=[[NBC News]] |date=October 21, 2019 |accessdate=October 21, 2019 |first=Jason |last=Abbruzzese |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191021194958/https://www.nbcnews.com/tech/tech-news/mark-zuckerberg-facebook-caught-russia-iran-trying-interfere-2020-n1069366 |archive-date=October 21, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> Fake accounts based in Russia posed as Americans of varied political backgrounds and worked to undermine the campaign of [[Joe Biden]], aiming to sow discontent with Biden from [[Left\u2013right political spectrum|both the left and the right]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.cnn.com/2019/10/21/tech/russia-instagram-accounts-2020-election/index.html |title=Facebook: Russian trolls are back. And they're here to meddle with 2020 |work=[[CNN]] |date=October 21, 2019 |accessdate=October 21, 2019 |first=Donie |last=O'Sullivan |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191021170904/https://www.cnn.com/2019/10/21/tech/russia-instagram-accounts-2020-election/index.html |archive-date=October 21, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nA September 2019 report from ''[[The Washington Post]]'' demonstrated that due to bad default passwords and weak encryption, hackers with physical access can easily get into voting machines designed for use in the [[2020 United States elections]], and remote hacking was possible if the machines were accidentally misconfigured.<ref>{{cite web|website=Yahoo! Finance|title=Researchers easily breached voting machines for the 2020 election|author=Christine Fisher|date=Sep 27, 2019|url=https://finance.yahoo.com/news/2019-09-27-us-voting-machines-hackers-2020-election.html?soc_src=social-sh&soc_trk=tw|access-date=January 26, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191219201412/https://finance.yahoo.com/news/2019-09-27-us-voting-machines-hackers-2020-election.html?soc_src=social-sh&soc_trk=tw|archive-date=December 19, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn February 13, 2020, American intelligence officials advised members of the [[House Intelligence Committee]] that Russia was interfering in the 2020 election in an effort to get Trump re-elected.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://apnews.com/a55930e0a02d2e21d8ed2be7bc496a6f |title=FBI official: Russia wants to see US 'tear ourselves apart' |work=[[Associated Press]] |date=2020-02-24 |accessdate=2020-02-26 |last=Tucker |first=Eric |quote=One intelligence official said lawmakers were not told that Russia was working directly to aid Trump. But other people familiar with the meeting said they were told the Kremlin was looking to help Trump's candidacy. The people spoke on condition of anonymity to discussed the classified briefing. |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200226204303/https://apnews.com/a55930e0a02d2e21d8ed2be7bc496a6f |archive-date=February 26, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> The briefing was delivered by [[Shelby Pierson]], the intelligence community's top election security official and an aide to acting [[Director of National Intelligence]] [[Joseph Maguire]]. Trump allies on the committee challenged the findings, and Trump was angered to learn of the briefing as he believed Democrats might \"weaponize\" the information against him. He chastised Maguire for allowing the briefing to occur, and days later he appointed [[Richard Grenell]] to replace Maguire.<ref name=\"Goldman_Barnes_Haberman_Fandos_2/20/2020\">{{cite web | last1=Goldman | first1=Adam | last2=Barnes | first2=Julian E. | last3=Haberman | first3=Maggie | last4=Fandos | first4=Nicholas | title=Lawmakers Are Warned That Russia Is Meddling to Re-elect Trump | website=[[The New York Times]] | date=February 20, 2020 | url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/02/20/us/politics/russian-interference-trump-democrats.html | access-date=February 26, 2020 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200225234247/https://www.nytimes.com/2020/02/20/us/politics/russian-interference-trump-democrats.html | archive-date=February 25, 2020 | url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=\"Acosta_Cohen_Bash_Herb_2/20/2020\">{{cite web | last=Acosta | first=Jim | last2=Cohen | first2=Zachary | last3=Bash | first3=Dana | last4=Herb | first4=Jeremy | title=Russia is looking to help Trump win in 2020, election security official told lawmakers | publisher=[[CNN]] | date=February 20, 2020 | url=https://www.cnn.com/2020/02/20/politics/trump-russia-intelligence-2020/index.html | access-date=February 26, 2020 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200226001124/https://www.cnn.com/2020/02/20/politics/trump-russia-intelligence-2020/index.html | archive-date=February 26, 2020 | url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=\"Nakashima_Harris_Dawsey_Gearan_2/20/2020\">{{cite web | last=Nakashima | first=Ellen | last2=Harris | first2=Shane | last3=Dawsey | first3=Josh | last4=Gearan | first4=Anne | title=Senior intelligence official told lawmakers that Russia wants to see Trump reelected | website=[[The Washington Post]] | date=February 20, 2020 | url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/national-security/after-a-congressional-briefing-on-election-threats-trump-soured-on-acting-spy-chief/2020/02/20/1ed2b4ec-53f1-11ea-b119-4faabac6674f_story.html | access-date=February 26, 2020 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200225222025/https://www.washingtonpost.com/national-security/after-a-congressional-briefing-on-election-threats-trump-soured-on-acting-spy-chief/2020/02/20/1ed2b4ec-53f1-11ea-b119-4faabac6674f_story.html | archive-date=February 25, 2020 | url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nOn February 21, 2020, ''[[The Washington Post]]'' reported that, according to unnamed US officials, Russia was interfering in the Democratic primary in an effort to support the nomination of Senator [[Bernie Sanders]]. Sanders issued a statement after the news report, saying in part, \"I don't care, frankly, who Putin wants to be president. My message to Putin is clear: stay out of American elections, and as president I will make sure that you do.\"<ref name=\"wapo-2020-02-21\">{{cite news |title=Bernie Sanders briefed by U.S. officials that Russia is trying to help his presidential campaign |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/national-security/bernie-sanders-briefed-by-us-officials-that-russia-is-trying-to-help-his-presidential-campaign/2020/02/21/5ad396a6-54bd-11ea-929a-64efa7482a77_story.html |work=The Washington Post |date=February 21, 2020 |access-date=February 22, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200222124440/https://www.washingtonpost.com/national-security/bernie-sanders-briefed-by-us-officials-that-russia-is-trying-to-help-his-presidential-campaign/2020/02/21/5ad396a6-54bd-11ea-929a-64efa7482a77_story.html |archive-date=February 22, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> Sanders acknowledged that his campaign was briefed about Russia's alleged efforts about a month prior.<ref>{{cite news |title=Russia Is Said to Be Interfering to Aid Sanders in Democratic Primaries |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/02/21/us/politics/bernie-sanders-russia.html |work=The New York Times |date=February 21, 2020 |access-date=February 22, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200222132741/https://www.nytimes.com/2020/02/21/us/politics/bernie-sanders-russia.html |archive-date=February 22, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> Sanders suggested that Russians were impersonating people claiming to be his supporters online in order to create an atmosphere of toxicity and give \"[[Bernie Bro]]s\" a bad reputation, a suggestion that [[Twitter]] rejected.<ref>{{cite news |title=Experts Say There's 'No Evidence' for Bernie's Russian Bot Claim |url=https://www.thedailybeast.com/experts-call-bs-on-bernies-russian-bot-theory |work=The Daily Beast |date=February 21, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Twitter knocks down Bernie Sanders' suggestion that Russian trolls are behind online attacks from his supporters |url=https://www.cnbc.com/2020/02/20/twitter-knocks-down-sanders-suggestion-russian-trolls-behind-supporters.html |work=CNBC |date=February 20, 2020 |access-date=February 22, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200222115000/https://www.cnbc.com/2020/02/20/twitter-knocks-down-sanders-suggestion-russian-trolls-behind-supporters.html |archive-date=February 22, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> According to election-security expert Laura Rosenberger, \"Russian attempts to sow discord in the Democratic primary would be consistent with its strategy of undermining Americans' faith in democratic institutions and processes.\"<ref name=\"wapo-2020-02-21\"/>\n\nIn March 2020, the [[University of Wisconsin\u2013Madison]] and the [[Brennan Center for Justice]] published a report indicating that Russia-linked social media accounts have been spreading [[Instagram]] posts calculated to sow division among American voters.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://apnews.com/0db953743c56cd6fd6e4ef73e02f120c|title=Report: Russian social accounts sow election discord - again|last=Seitz|first=Amanda|last2=Ortutay|first2=Barbara|date=2020-03-05|website=[[Associated Press]]|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200309180450/https://apnews.com/0db953743c56cd6fd6e4ef73e02f120c|archive-date=March 9, 2020|access-date=2020-03-09}}</ref><ref name=\"brennan\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.brennancenter.org/our-work/analysis-opinion/new-evidence-shows-how-russias-election-interference-has-gotten-more|title=New Evidence Shows How Russia's Election Interference Has Gotten More Brazen|last=Kim|first=Young Mie|date=2020-05-05|website=[[Brennan Center for Justice]]|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200311173959/https://www.brennancenter.org/our-work/analysis-opinion/new-evidence-shows-how-russias-election-interference-has-gotten-more|archive-date=March 11, 2020|access-date=2020-03-09}}</ref> According to the report, Russian operatives were increasingly impersonating real political candidates and groups rather than creating fictional groups.<ref name=\"brennan\" /> According to Twitter's head of site integrity, Russian agents also attempted in 2018 to create the impression of more election interference than is actually happening to undermine confidence in the process.<ref>[https://www.npr.org/2020/03/05/812497423/report-russian-election-trolling-becoming-subtler-tougher-to-detect Report: Russian Election Trolling Becoming Subtler, Tougher To Detect]</ref> Shortly thereafter, the ''New York Times'' reported that according to American intelligence officials Russian operatives have been promoting and pressuring [[hate group]]s, including [[neo-Nazis]], in order to create strife within American society.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Barnes|first=Julian E.|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/10/us/politics/russian-interference-race.html|title=Russia Trying to Stoke U.S. Racial Tensions Before Election, Officials Say|date=2020-03-10|work=[[The New York Times]]|access-date=2020-03-10|url-status=live|last2=Goldman|first2=Adam|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200310192420/https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/10/us/politics/russian-interference-race.html|archive-date=March 10, 2020}}</ref> A [[CNN]] investigation found that Russian efforts had partly been outsourced to [[troll farm]]s in [[Ghana]] and [[Nigeria]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.cnn.com/2020/03/12/world/russia-ghana-troll-farms-2020-ward/index.html |title=Russian election meddling is back \u2014 via Ghana and Nigeria \u2014 and in your feeds |date=2020-03-12 |accessdate=2020-03-12 |work=[[CNN]] |first1=Clarissa |last1=Ward |first2=Katie |last2=Polglase |first3=Sebastian |last3=Shukla |first4=Gianluca |last4=Mezzofiore |first5=Tim |last5=Lister |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200312232339/https://www.cnn.com/2020/03/12/world/russia-ghana-troll-farms-2020-ward/index.html |archive-date=March 12, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n==Government reaction==\n\n[[Dan Coats]] appointed [[Shelby Pierson]] as the U.S. election security [[Czar (political term)|czar]] in July 2019, creating a new position in a move seen as an acknowledgment that foreign influence operations against U.S. elections will be ongoing indefinitely.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Barnes |first1=Julian E. |title=Intelligence Chief Names New Election Security Oversight Official |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/07/19/us/politics/intelligence-election-security.html |work=[[The New York Times]] |date=July 19, 2019 |accessdate=July 26, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190723140612/https://www.nytimes.com/2019/07/19/us/politics/intelligence-election-security.html |archive-date=July 23, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.npr.org/2019/07/28/696376152/dan-coats-who-challenged-president-trump-to-depart-top-intelligence-job |title=Dan Coats, Who Challenged President Trump, Is Ousted From Top Intelligence Job |last=Myre |first=Greg |work=[[NPR]] |date=2019-07-28 |accessdate=2019-07-28 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190728220444/https://www.npr.org/2019/07/28/696376152/dan-coats-who-challenged-president-trump-to-depart-top-intelligence-job |archive-date=July 28, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> Election-security task forces established before the [[2018 United States elections|2018 midterm elections]] at the FBI, the [[Department of Homeland Security]], the [[National Security Agency]] and the [[United States Cyber Command]] have been expanded and \"made permanent\".<ref name=\"goldman-nyt\"/> The Department of Homeland Security indicated that the threat of [[ransomware]] attacks upon [[voter registration]] databases was a particular concern.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-usa-cyber-election-exclusive/exclusive-u-s-officials-fear-ransomware-attack-against-2020-election-idUSKCN1VG222 |title=U.S. officials fear ransomware attack against 2020 election |work=[[Reuters]] |date=2019-08-26 |accessdate=2019-08-27 |last=Bing |first=Christopher |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190827174333/https://www.reuters.com/article/us-usa-cyber-election-exclusive/exclusive-u-s-officials-fear-ransomware-attack-against-2020-election-idUSKCN1VG222 |archive-date=August 27, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nPrior to resigning as [[U.S. Secretary of Homeland Security]], [[Kirstjen Nielsen]] attempted to organize a meeting of the [[U.S. Cabinet]] to discuss how to address potential foreign interference in the 2020 elections. [[Mick Mulvaney]], the [[White House Chief of Staff]], reportedly warned her to keep the subject away from Trump, who views the discussion as questioning the legitimacy of his victory in 2016.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/04/24/us/politics/russia-2020-election-trump.html |work=[[The New York Times]] |date=2019-04-24 |title=In Push for 2020 Election Security, Top Official Was Warned: Don't Tell Trump |last1=Schmitt |first1=Eric |authorlink1=Eric P. Schmitt |last2=Sanger |first2=David E. |authorlink2=David E. Sanger |last3=Haberman |first3=Maggie |authorlink3=Maggie Haberman |access-date=July 27, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190727194235/https://www.nytimes.com/2019/04/24/us/politics/russia-2020-election-trump.html |archive-date=July 27, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> [[Mitch McConnell]], the [[Senate Majority Leader]], has blocked various bills intended to improve election security from being considered,<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.newsweek.com/2019/08/02/elections-2020-will-take-place-cyber-battleground-that-puts-us-disadvantage-says-expert-1450351.html |title=Russia Is Using Cold War Strategy to Undermine the Faith of Americans in the 2020 Election\u2014Will It Work? |website=[[Newsweek]] |date=2019-07-23 |last=Piore |first=Adam |accessdate=2019-07-27 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190727231644/https://www.newsweek.com/2019/08/02/elections-2020-will-take-place-cyber-battleground-that-puts-us-disadvantage-says-expert-1450351.html |archive-date=July 27, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last=Croucher |first=Shane |url=https://www.newsweek.com/moscow-mitch-trends-twitter-mcconnell-russia-election-interference-1451274 |title=#MoscowMitch Trends on Twitter as Mitch McConnell Blocks Election Security Bills Despite 'Unprecedented Level' of Russian Interference |publisher=Newsweek.com |date=July 26, 2019 |accessdate=2019-07-26 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190726192133/https://www.newsweek.com/moscow-mitch-trends-twitter-mcconnell-russia-election-interference-1451274 |archive-date=July 26, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.pbs.org/newshour/politics/how-the-u-s-is-trying-to-improve-election-security-ahead-of-2020 |title=How the U.S. is trying to improve election security ahead of 2020 |last=Martinez |first=Gabriela |date=2019-07-26 |accessdate=2019-07-27 |website=[[PBS Newshour]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190727232600/https://www.pbs.org/newshour/politics/how-the-u-s-is-trying-to-improve-election-security-ahead-of-2020 |archive-date=July 27, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> including some measures that have had bipartisan support.<ref>{{cite news |last=Dilanian |first=Ken |title=Hill push to battle foreign election interference is stuck at McConnell roadblock |url=https://www.nbcnews.com/politics/national-security/hill-push-battle-foreign-election-interference-stuck-mcconnell-roadblock-n1017361 |work=[[NBC News]] |date=2019-06-13 |accessdate=2019-07-30 |quote=In fact, some GOP senators have joined with Democrats to co-sponsor legislation designed to shore up voting machines and make it harder for foreign intelligence operatives to hack, leak and manipulate social media the way the Russians did in 2016. But those bills are going nowhere \u2014 because Senate Majority Leader Mitch McConnell, R-Ky., has not allowed a vote on any of them. |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190723050705/https://www.nbcnews.com/politics/national-security/hill-push-battle-foreign-election-interference-stuck-mcconnell-roadblock-n1017361 |archive-date=July 23, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |url=https://www.wired.com/story/russia-2020-election-security-mark-warner/ |title=Russia Is Going To Up Its Game For The 2020 Elections |journal=[[Wired (magazine)|Wired]] |last=Laslo |first=Matt |date=2019-07-31 |accessdate=2019-08-02 |quote=Both bills have bipartisan support\u2014Senator Susan Collins became the first Republican to cosponsor the Foreign Influence Reporting in Elections Act earlier this week. |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190801204804/https://www.wired.com/story/russia-2020-election-security-mark-warner/ |archive-date=August 1, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> Election-security legislation remains stalled in the Senate as of February 2020.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://thehill.com/homenews/house/482569-senate-gop-blocks-three-election-security-bills|title=Senate GOP blocks three election security bills|last=Balluck|first=Kyle|date=2020-02-11|website=[[The Hill (newspaper)|The Hill]]|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200211215724/https://thehill.com/homenews/house/482569-senate-gop-blocks-three-election-security-bills|archive-date=February 11, 2020|access-date=2020-02-11}}</ref> However, various states have implemented changes, such as [[paper ballot]]s.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/07/26/us/politics/states-voting-systems.html |work=[[The New York Times]] |title=States Rush to Make Voting Systems More Secure as New Threats Emerge |date=2019-07-26 |last1=Sanger |first1=David E. |authorlink1=David E. Sanger |last2=Epstein |first2=Reid J. |last3=Wines |first3=Michael |authorlink3=Michael Wines |access-date=July 27, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190727001938/https://www.nytimes.com/2019/07/26/us/politics/states-voting-systems.html |archive-date=July 27, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> [[Florida]] has expanded its paper-ballot backup system since 2016, but experts warn that its voting systems are still vulnerable to manipulation, a particular concern being the electronic poll books that store lists of registered voters.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2019/aug/27/florida-russian-hackers-target-2020-election |title=Russian hackers likely to target Florida again in 2020 election, experts warn |work=[[The Guardian]] |date=2019-08-27 |accessdate=2019-08-27 |last=Stone |first=Peter |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190827143332/https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2019/aug/27/florida-russian-hackers-target-2020-election |archive-date=August 27, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> All 67 election supervisors in Florida have been required to sign [[nondisclosure agreement]]s, and consequently, information such as the identity of which four counties had been hacked by Russian intelligence in 2016 remains unknown to the public.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.usatoday.com/in-depth/news/investigations/2020/02/25/voting-access-florida-sunshine-state-election-security/4866141002/ |title=Will your vote count? Veil of secrecy makes it impossible for Florida voters to know |first=Jeffrey |last=Schweers |date=2020-02-25 |accessdate=2020-02-26 |work=[[USA Today]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200226204743/https://www.usatoday.com/in-depth/news/investigations/2020/02/25/voting-access-florida-sunshine-state-election-security/4866141002/ |archive-date=February 26, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]] members of Congress cited the lack of effort to secure U.S. elections against foreign interference, particularly from Russia, as among grounds to begin an [[impeachment]] inquiry.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.cnn.com/2019/07/25/politics/jackie-speier-take-action-impeachment-shut-it-down-cnntv/index.html |title=Dem lawmaker to her party: 'Take action' on impeachment by September or 'shut it down' |last=Sullivan |first=Kate |work=[[CNN]] |date=2019-07-25 |accessdate=2019-07-29 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190727145555/https://www.cnn.com/2019/07/25/politics/jackie-speier-take-action-impeachment-shut-it-down-cnntv/index.html |archive-date=July 27, 2019 |url-status=live }}<br/>{{cite news |url=https://www.wbur.org/news/2019/07/25/ed-markey-trump-impeachment-probe |title=Rep. Clark Backs Impeachment Probe, Putting Pressure On Pelosi |work=[[WBUR]] |last1=Swasey |first1=Benjamin |last2=Atkins |first2=Kimberley |date=2019-07-25 |accessdate=2019-07-29 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190727170338/https://www.wbur.org/news/2019/07/25/ed-markey-trump-impeachment-probe |archive-date=July 27, 2019 |url-status=live }}<br/>{{cite news |url=https://www.seattletimes.com/seattle-news/all-washington-house-democrats-now-favor-impeachment-inquiry-of-trump/ |title=All Washington House Democrats now favor Trump impeachment inquiry |last=Romano |first=Benjamin |work=[[The Seattle Times]] |date=2019-07-29 |accessdate=2019-07-29 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190729131505/https://www.seattletimes.com/seattle-news/all-washington-house-democrats-now-favor-impeachment-inquiry-of-trump/ |archive-date=July 29, 2019 |url-status=live }}<br/>{{cite news |url=https://www.theolympian.com/news/local/article233239221.html |title=U.S. Reps Heck, Kilmer, Schreir, and Del Bene announce support of impeachment inquiry |work=[[The Olympian]] |last=Boone |first=Rolf |date=2019-07-28 |accessdate=2019-07-29 }}</ref>\n\nOn September 30, 2019, the United States issued economic sanctions against seven Russians affiliated with the [[Internet Research Agency]], an organization that manipulates social media for misinformation purposes. The sanctions were described as a warning against foreign interference in United States elections.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/09/30/us/politics/us-russia-sanctions-election-meddling.html |title=With Sanctions on Russians, U.S. Warns Against Foreign Election Meddling |work=[[The New York Times]] |date=September 30, 2019 |last=Jakes |first=Lara |access-date=October 1, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191001022221/https://www.nytimes.com/2019/09/30/us/politics/us-russia-sanctions-election-meddling.html |archive-date=October 1, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nOn December 9, 2019, FBI Director [[Christopher A. Wray]] told ABC News: \"as far as the [2020] election itself goes, we think Russia represents the most significant threat.\"<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://abcnews.go.com/Politics/fbi-director-chris-wray-reacts-doj-watchdog-report/story?id=67605418|title=FBI Director Chris Wray reacts to DOJ watchdog report on Russia investigation: Exclusive|website=ABC News|language=en|access-date=2019-12-10|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191219051108/https://abcnews.go.com/Politics/fbi-director-chris-wray-reacts-doj-watchdog-report/story?id=67605418|archive-date=December 19, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> According to [[William Evanina]], director of the [[National Counterintelligence and Security Center]], Russia is \"using social media and many other tools to inflame social divisions, promote conspiracy theories and sow distrust in our democracy and elections.\"<ref name=\"bloomberg-jan2020\">{{cite news |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2020-01-10/u-s-probes-if-russia-targeting-biden-in-2020-election-meddling |title=U.S. Probes If Russia Is Targeting Biden in 2020 Election Meddling |first=Chris |last=Strohm |date=January 10, 2020 |accessdate=January 10, 2020 |work=[[Bloomberg News]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200110210442/https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2020-01-10/u-s-probes-if-russia-targeting-biden-in-2020-election-meddling |archive-date=January 10, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n''Bloomberg News'' reported in January 2020 that American intelligence and law enforcement were examining whether Russia was involved in promoting disinformation to undermine Joe Biden as part of a campaign to disrupt the 2020 election.<ref name=\"bloomberg-jan2020\"/> The following month, the [[Estonian Foreign Intelligence Service]] warned that Russia would attempt to interfere in the [[Georgia (country)|Georgian]] [[2020 Georgian parliamentary election|parliamentary election]] in October 2020 as well as the US election in November.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.nbcnews.com/politics/national-security/russia-will-try-meddle-2020-u-s-election-intelligence-report-n1134446 |title=Russia will try to meddle in 2020 U.S. election, intelligence report says |work=[[NBC News]] |date=February 12, 2020 |accessdate=February 12, 2020 |last=Kube |first=Courtney |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200213153143/https://www.nbcnews.com/politics/national-security/russia-will-try-meddle-2020-u-s-election-intelligence-report-n1134446 |archive-date=February 13, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n=== Trump administration reaction ===\n\nThe Trump administration reacted to the briefing by American intelligence officials to the House Intelligence Committee that Russia was interfering in the 2020 election in an effort to get Trump re-elected<ref name=\"Goldman_Barnes_Haberman_Fandos_2/20/2020\"/><ref name=\"Acosta_Cohen_Bash_Herb_2/20/2020\"/><ref name=\"Nakashima_Harris_Dawsey_Gearan_2/20/2020\"/>  by rejecting the efforts were in favor of Trump<ref name=\"Diamond_Tapper_Cohen_2/23/2020\">{{cite web | last=Diamond | first=Jeremy | last2=Tapper | first2=Jake | last3=Cohen | first3=Zachary | title=US intelligence briefer appears to have overstated assessment of 2020 Russian interference | publisher=[[CNN]] | date=February 23, 2020 | url=https://www.cnn.com/2020/02/23/politics/intelligence-briefer-russian-interference-trump-sanders/index.html | access-date=February 26, 2020 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200226015505/https://www.cnn.com/2020/02/23/politics/intelligence-briefer-russian-interference-trump-sanders/index.html | archive-date=February 26, 2020 | url-status=live }}</ref> and by firing Joseph Maguire, who was involved in those reports.<ref name=\"Goldman_Barnes_Haberman_Fandos_2/20/2020\"/><ref name=\"Acosta_Cohen_Bash_Herb_2/20/2020\"/><ref name=\"Nakashima_Harris_Dawsey_Gearan_2/20/2020\"/>\n\nBy contrast, Trump and his national security adviser [[Robert C. O'Brien (attorney)|Robert O'Brien]]<ref name=\"Sanger_2/24/2020\">{{cite web | last=Sanger | first=David E. | title=Dueling Narratives Emerge From Muddied Account of Russia's 2020 Interference | website=[[The New York Times]] | date=February 24, 2020 | url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/02/23/us/politics/russia-2020-election-interference.html | access-date=February 26, 2020 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200225231616/https://www.nytimes.com/2020/02/23/us/politics/russia-2020-election-interference.html | archive-date=February 25, 2020 | url-status=live }}</ref> accepted reports the Russians were supporting the nomination of Bernie Sanders.<ref name=\"Pengelly_2/22/2020\">{{cite web | last=Pengelly | first=Martin | title=Donald Trump pounces on reports Russia is seeking to help Bernie Sanders | website=[[The Guardian]] | date=February 22, 2020 | url=http://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2020/feb/22/donald-trump-bernie-sanders-russia | access-date=February 26, 2020 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200225170801/https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2020/feb/22/donald-trump-bernie-sanders-russia | archive-date=February 25, 2020 | url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=\"wapo-2020-02-21\">{{cite news |title=Bernie Sanders briefed by U.S. officials that Russia is trying to help his presidential campaign |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/national-security/bernie-sanders-briefed-by-us-officials-that-russia-is-trying-to-help-his-presidential-campaign/2020/02/21/5ad396a6-54bd-11ea-929a-64efa7482a77_story.html |work=The Washington Post |date=February 21, 2020 |access-date=February 22, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200222124440/https://www.washingtonpost.com/national-security/bernie-sanders-briefed-by-us-officials-that-russia-is-trying-to-help-his-presidential-campaign/2020/02/21/5ad396a6-54bd-11ea-929a-64efa7482a77_story.html |archive-date=February 22, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nThree weeks after Trump loyalist [[Richard Grenell]] was appointed acting [[Director of National Intelligence]], intelligence officials briefed members of Congress behind closed doors that they had \"not concluded that the Kremlin is directly aiding any candidate\u2019s re-election or any other candidates\u2019 election,\" which differed from testimony they had provided the previous month indicating that Russia was working to aid Trump's candidacy. Two intelligence officials pushed back on suggestions the new testimony was politically motivated. One intelligence official asserted the earlier testimony had overreached and that Democrats had mischaracterized it. [[Trump\u2013Ukraine scandal#Kashyap Patel|Kash Patel]], a former aide to congressman [[Devin Nunes]] who joined Grenell at the ODNI, imposed limits on what intelligence officials could tell Congress about foreign influence operations. The briefers reportedly did not intend to contradict their previous testimony, though they avoided repeating it.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/10/us/politics/election-interference-briefing-trump.html |title=Archived copy |access-date=March 11, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200311165910/https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/10/us/politics/election-interference-briefing-trump.html |archive-date=March 11, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/02/20/us/politics/russian-interference-trump-democrats.html |title=Archived copy |access-date=February 21, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200221010559/https://www.nytimes.com/2020/02/20/us/politics/russian-interference-trump-democrats.html |archive-date=February 21, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n==Presidency of Donald Trump==\n\nIn a June 2019 interview with [[George Stephanopoulos]], [[President of the United States|President]] [[Donald Trump]] said that he would accept information from other nations about his opponents in the [[2020 United States presidential election]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Baker |first1=Peter |authorlink1=Peter Baker (journalist) |title=Trump Says 'I'd Take It' if Russia Again Offered Dirt on Opponent |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/06/12/us/politics/trump-russia-fbi.html |work=The New York Times |date=June 12, 2019 |accessdate=July 26, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190724184644/https://www.nytimes.com/2019/06/12/us/politics/trump-russia-fbi.html |archive-date=July 24, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://abcnews.go.com/Politics/transcript-abc-news-george-stephanopoulos-exclusive-interview-president/story?id=63749144 |title=Transcript: ABC News' George Stephanopoulos' exclusive interview with President Trump |author=<!--Not stated--> |date=June 16, 2019 |website=ABC News |access-date=31 July 2019 |quote=[[George Stephanopoulos|STEPHANOPOULOS]]: Your campaign this time around, if foreigners, if Russia, if China, if someone else offers you information on opponents, should they accept it or should they call the FBI?  TRUMP: I think maybe you do both. I think you might want to listen, I don't, there's nothing wrong with listening. If somebody called from a country, Norway, \"We have information on your opponent.\" Oh, I think I'd want to hear it.  STEPHANOPOULOS: You want that kind of interference in our elections?  TRUMP: It's not an interference, they have information. I think I'd take it. If I thought there was something wrong, I'd go maybe to the FBI. If I thought there was something wrong. But when somebody comes up with oppo research, right, that they come up with oppo research. Oh, let's call the FBI. The FBI doesn't have enough agents to take care of it, but you go and talk honestly to congressmen, they all do it, they always have. And that's the way it is. It's called oppo research.  STEPHANOPOULOS: Surprising. Thank you.  TRUMP: Thank you. Okay. Fine. |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190801032648/https://abcnews.go.com/Politics/transcript-abc-news-george-stephanopoulos-exclusive-interview-president/story?id=63749144 |archive-date=August 1, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nAccording to reporting by ''The Wall Street Journal'', ''The Washington Post'' and ''The New York Times'', Trump and his personal attorney [[Rudy Giuliani]] repeatedly pressed the [[Government of Ukraine|Ukrainian government]] to investigate [[Hunter Biden]], the son of [[Joe Biden]], leading to the {{As of|2020|1|9|df=US|alt=ongoing}} [[Trump\u2013Ukraine scandal]].<ref name=\"auto4\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/trump-defends-conversation-with-ukraine-leader-11568993176|title=WSJ News Exclusive &#124; Trump Repeatedly Pressed Ukraine President to Investigate Biden's Son|first=Alan Cullison, Rebecca Ballhaus and Dustin|last=Volz|website=WSJ|access-date=September 23, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190923092317/https://www.wsj.com/articles/trump-defends-conversation-with-ukraine-leader-11568993176|archive-date=September 23, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"auto5\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/national-security/trump-pressed-ukrainian-leader-to-investigate-bidens-son-according-to-people-familiar-with-the-matter/2019/09/20/7fa39b20-dbdc-11e9-bfb1-849887369476_story.html|title=Trump pressed Ukrainian leader to investigate Biden's son, according to people familiar with the matter|website=Washington Post|access-date=September 23, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190922233816/https://www.washingtonpost.com/national-security/trump-pressed-ukrainian-leader-to-investigate-bidens-son-according-to-people-familiar-with-the-matter/2019/09/20/7fa39b20-dbdc-11e9-bfb1-849887369476_story.html|archive-date=September 22, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/09/20/us/politics/trump-whistle-blower-ukraine.html|title=Trump Pressed Ukraine's Leader on Inquiry Into Biden's Son|first1=Julian E.|last1=Barnes|first2=Michael S.|last2=Schmidt|first3=Kenneth P.|last3=Vogel|first4=Adam|last4=Goldman|first5=Maggie|last5=Haberman|date=September 20, 2019|via=NYTimes.com|access-date=September 23, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190923114022/https://www.nytimes.com/2019/09/20/us/politics/trump-whistle-blower-ukraine.html|archive-date=September 23, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> Biden is a potentially strong Trump challenger in the 2020 presidential election.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/trump-defends-conversation-with-ukraine-leader-11568993176|title=WSJ News Exclusive {{!}} Trump Repeatedly Pressed Ukraine President to Investigate Biden's Son|last=Volz|first=Alan Cullison, Rebecca Ballhaus and Dustin|website=WSJ|language=en-US|access-date=September 20, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190923092317/https://www.wsj.com/articles/trump-defends-conversation-with-ukraine-leader-11568993176|archive-date=September 23, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/09/20/world/europe/ukraine-trump-zelensky.html|title=Ukraine Pressured on U.S. Political Investigations|last=Kramer|first=Andrew E.|date=September 20, 2019|work=The New York Times|access-date=September 20, 2019|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190920171010/https://www.nytimes.com/2019/09/20/world/europe/ukraine-trump-zelensky.html|archive-date=September 20, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> The purpose of the requested investigation was alleged to be to damage [[Joe Biden 2020 presidential campaign|Biden's election campaign]] for president.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.axios.com/trump-whistleblower-ukraine-e57df07d-137d-41db-9adc-5c17b74013ab.html|title=WSJ: Trump urged Ukrainian president \"about 8 times\" to investigate Biden's son|website=Axios|language=en|access-date=September 20, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190920210637/https://www.axios.com/trump-whistleblower-ukraine-e57df07d-137d-41db-9adc-5c17b74013ab.html|archive-date=September 20, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"auto1\">{{Cite web|url=https://foreignpolicy.com/2019/09/20/is-trump-trying-to-get-ukraine-to-take-out-biden-for-him/|title=Is Trump Trying to Get Ukraine to Take Out Biden for Him?|last=Mackinnon|first=Amy|website=Foreign Policy|language=en-US|access-date=September 20, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190920210034/https://foreignpolicy.com/2019/09/20/is-trump-trying-to-get-ukraine-to-take-out-biden-for-him/|archive-date=September 20, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> Reports suggested that Trump threatened to withhold [[military aid]] from [[Ukraine]] unless they investigate Biden.<ref name=\"auto1\" /><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.newyorker.com/news/our-columnists/did-trump-try-to-extort-the-president-of-ukraine-into-investigating-joe-biden|title=Did Trump Try to Extort the President of Ukraine Into Investigating Joe Biden?|last=Cassidy|first=John|date=September 20, 2019|access-date=September 20, 2019|language=en|issn=0028-792X|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190920205009/https://www.newyorker.com/news/our-columnists/did-trump-try-to-extort-the-president-of-ukraine-into-investigating-joe-biden|archive-date=September 20, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> The controversy triggered the commencement of the [[Impeachment inquiry against Donald Trump|formal process of impeachment inquiries against Trump]] on September 24, with House speaker [[Nancy Pelosi]] directing six House committee chairmen to proceed \"under that umbrella of impeachment inquiry\".<ref name = formal>{{cite web |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/powerpost/pelosi-top-democrats-privately-discuss-creation-of-select-committee-for-impeachment/2019/09/24/af6f735a-dedf-11e9-b199-f638bf2c340f_story.html |title=House Speaker Nancy Pelosi announces formal impeachment inquiry of Trump, says his actions were a 'betrayal of national security' |work=The Washington Post |date= |accessdate=2019-09-24 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190924201421/https://www.washingtonpost.com/powerpost/pelosi-top-democrats-privately-discuss-creation-of-select-committee-for-impeachment/2019/09/24/af6f735a-dedf-11e9-b199-f638bf2c340f_story.html |archive-date=September 24, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nOn October 3, 2019, Trump said that \"[[China]] should start an investigation\" into [[2020 Democratic Party presidential primaries|presidential candidate]] Joe Biden and his son Hunter Biden. Moments before, while discussing negotiations on a possible agreement in the ongoing [[China\u2013United States trade war]], he said that \"if they [China] don't do what we want, we have tremendous power.\" Chair of the [[Federal Election Commission]] [[Ellen Weintraub]] then retweeted a June statement explaining that \"it is illegal for any person to solicit, accept, or receive anything of value from a foreign national in connection with a U.S. election\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nbcnews.com/politics/2020-election/trump-publicly-urges-china-ukraine-investigate-bidens-amid-impeachment-inquiry-n1061956|title=Trump publicly urges China to investigate Bidens amid impeachment inquiry|publisher=NBC News|date=October 3, 2019|accessdate=October 3, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191003160859/https://www.nbcnews.com/politics/2020-election/trump-publicly-urges-china-ukraine-investigate-bidens-amid-impeachment-inquiry-n1061956|archive-date=October 3, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n{{As of|2019|10|alt=As of early October 2019}}, there is evidence President Trump, Vice President [[Mike Pence]], U.S. Attorney General [[William Barr]], as well as Trump's personal attorney Giuliani have solicited help from Ukraine, Australia, Italy, the United Kingdom, and China for assistance in discrediting Trump's political opponents.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/trump-impeachment-inquiry-live-updates/2019/10/03/5f81ec5a-e55c-11e9-a6e8-8759c5c7f608_story.html|title=Trump ordered removal of ambassador over Biden probe; president calls for China to investigate Bidens|first1=Colby|last1=Itkowitz|first2=John|last2=Wagner|first3=Felicia|last3=Sonmez|date=October 4, 2019|via=www.washingtonpost.com|access-date=October 4, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191004204355/https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/trump-impeachment-inquiry-live-updates/2019/10/03/5f81ec5a-e55c-11e9-a6e8-8759c5c7f608_story.html|archive-date=October 4, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/10/03/us/politics/trump-china-bidens.html|title=Trump Publicly Urges China to Investigate the Bidens|first1=Peter|last1=Baker|first2=Eileen|last2=Sullivan|date=October 3, 2019|via=NYTimes.com|access-date=October 4, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191004231604/https://www.nytimes.com/2019/10/03/us/politics/trump-china-bidens.html|archive-date=October 4, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/trump-urges-ukraine-china-to-investigate-the-bidens-11570114755|title=Trump Administration Used Potential Meeting to Pressure Ukraine on Biden, Texts Indicate|first=Rebecca Ballhaus, Siobhan Hughes and Dustin|last=Volz|website=WSJ|access-date=October 4, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191004172356/https://www.wsj.com/articles/trump-urges-ukraine-china-to-investigate-the-bidens-11570114755|archive-date=October 4, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnn.com/2019/10/03/politics/donald-trump-ukraine-china-investigate-2020/index.html|title=Trump now says both China and Ukraine should investigate Bidens|author=Kevin Liptak|website=CNN|access-date=October 4, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191004193006/https://www.cnn.com/2019/10/03/politics/donald-trump-ukraine-china-investigate-2020/index.html|archive-date=October 4, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://apnews.com/c4fc388b22f549e0a67925cab8cd7e93|title=Not just Ukraine: Trump now calls for China to probe Bidens|date=October 3, 2019|website=AP NEWS|access-date=October 4, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191004175445/https://www.apnews.com/c4fc388b22f549e0a67925cab8cd7e93|archive-date=October 4, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.axios.com/trump-china-investigate-joe-biden-f7d034bf-91ea-4ede-a879-6b86c36e719a.html|title=Trump says China should investigate Bidens|website=Axios|access-date=October 4, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191004081222/https://www.axios.com/trump-china-investigate-joe-biden-f7d034bf-91ea-4ede-a879-6b86c36e719a.html|archive-date=October 4, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nbcnews.com/politics/2020-election/trump-publicly-urges-china-ukraine-investigate-bidens-amid-impeachment-inquiry-n1061956|title=Trump publicly urges China to investigate Bidens amid impeachment inquiry|website=NBC News|access-date=October 3, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191003205659/https://www.nbcnews.com/politics/2020-election/trump-publicly-urges-china-ukraine-investigate-bidens-amid-impeachment-inquiry-n1061956|archive-date=October 3, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnbc.com/2019/10/03/trump-calls-for-ukraine-china-to-investigate-the-bidens.html|title=Trump says China should investigate the Bidens, doubles down on Ukraine probe|first=Kevin|last=Breuninger|date=October 3, 2019|website=CNBC|access-date=October 4, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191004193118/https://www.cnbc.com/2019/10/03/trump-calls-for-ukraine-china-to-investigate-the-bidens.html|archive-date=October 4, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2019/oct/03/trump-biden-china-investigation-demand|title=Trump calls on China to investigate Biden in extraordinary demand|first1=Julian|last1=Borger|first2=Lauren|last2=Gambino|date=October 3, 2019|via=www.theguardian.com|access-date=October 4, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191027153313/https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2019/oct/03/trump-biden-china-investigation-demand|archive-date=October 27, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n\n*[[Impeachment inquiry against Donald Trump]]\n*[[Second American Civil War#Culture war as Second American Civil War|Cold Civil war]]\n*[[Cold War II]]\n*[[Cyberwarfare and Iran]]\n*[[Cyberwarfare by Russia]]\n*[[Democratic National Committee cyber attacks]]\n*[[Foreign electoral intervention]]\n*[[Presidency of Donald Trump]]\n*[[Russian espionage in the United States]]\n*[[Russian interference in the 2018 United States elections]]\n*[[Social media in the 2016 United States presidential election]]\n*[[Social media in the 2020 United States presidential election]]\n*2016 interference timeline\n**[[Timeline of Russian interference in the 2016 United States elections]]\n**[[Timeline of Russian interference in the 2016 United States elections (July 2016\u2013election day)]]\n**[[Timeline of post-election transition following Russian interference in the 2016 United States elections]]\n**[[Timeline of investigations into Trump and Russia (January\u2013June 2017)]]\n**[[Timeline of investigations into Trump and Russia (July\u2013December 2017)]]\n**[[Timeline of investigations into Trump and Russia (January\u2013June 2018)]]\n**[[Timeline of investigations into Trump and Russia (July\u2013December 2018)]]\n**[[Timeline of investigations into Trump and Russia (2019\u20132020)]]\n*[[1996 United States campaign finance controversy]]\n\n==References==\n\n{{Reflist}}\n{{Russian interference in the 2016 United States elections}}\n{{2020 United States elections}}\n\n<!--[[Category:2020 controversies in the United States]]-->\n[[Category:2020 elections in the United States]]\n[[Category:Russia\u2013United States relations]]\n[[Category:Foreign electoral intervention]]\n[[Category:Internet manipulation and propaganda]]\n[[Category:Trump administration controversies]]\n[[Category:Information operations and warfare]]\n", "text_old": "{{Short description|national security concern}}\n\n{{Use mdy dates|date=July 2019}}\n'''Russian interference in the 2020 United States elections''' has become a question of concern at the highest level of [[National security of the United States|national security]] as well as in the [[computer industry|computer]] and [[social media]] industries.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/politics/politics-features/trump-election-hacking-russia-iran-ransomware-interference-938109/ |title=Hackers Are Coming for the 2020 Election \u2014 And We're Not Ready |first=Andy |last=Kroll |work=[[Rolling Stone]] |date=2020-01-17 |accessdate=2020-01-17 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200117192107/https://www.rollingstone.com/politics/politics-features/trump-election-hacking-russia-iran-ransomware-interference-938109/ |archive-date=January 17, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> In February 2020, the American intelligence community advised members of Congress that Russia was attempting to interfere in the 2020 election.\n\n==Reports of attempted interference==\n\nIn response to [[Russian interference in the 2016 United States elections]], special counsel [[Robert Mueller]] conducted a two-year-long [[Special Counsel investigation (2017\u20132019)|investigation]]. The resulting [[Mueller Report|report]] concluded that Russia interfered in \u201csweeping and systematic fashion\u201d.<ref>''[https://www.justice.gov/storage/report.pdf Mueller Report] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190422095933/https://www.justice.gov/storage/report.pdf |date=April 22, 2019 }}'', vol. I, p. 1: \"The Russian government interfered in the 2016 presidential election in sweeping and systematic fashion\"</ref> In his July 2019 Congressional testimony, Mueller stated that the Russians continue to interfere in U.S. elections \"as we sit here\u201d, and that \"many more countries\" have developed disinformation campaigns targeting U.S. elections, based partly on the Russian model.<ref>{{cite news |title=Mueller rejects Trump's claims of exoneration, 'witch hunt' |work=[[The Washington Post]] |date=2019-07-25 |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/mueller-no-russia-exoneration-for-trump-despite-his-claims/2019/07/24/428d5a0c-ae85-11e9-9411-a608f9d0c2d3_story.html |last1=Tucker |first1=Eric |last2=Jalonick |first2=Mary Clare |last3=Balsamo |first3=Michael |quote=And [Mueller] said of the interference by Russians and others: \"They are doing it as we sit here. And they expect to do it during the next campaign.\" |access-date=July 27, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190727155844/https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/mueller-no-russia-exoneration-for-trump-despite-his-claims/2019/07/24/428d5a0c-ae85-11e9-9411-a608f9d0c2d3_story.html |archive-date=July 27, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |author= |date=July 25, 2019 |url=https://www.cnn.com/2019/07/24/politics/russia-trump-election-interference/index.html |title=Robert Mueller's testimony: The biggest takeaway is Russia's interference in US elections |work=CNN |accessdate=2019-07-26 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190726211452/https://www.cnn.com/2019/07/24/politics/russia-trump-election-interference/index.html |archive-date=July 26, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nAlso in July 2019, the [[Senate Intelligence Committee]] released the first volume of a bipartisan report on Russian interference in the 2016 United States elections, a report that included recommendations for securing the 2020 elections.<ref>{{cite news |title=Russia Targeted Election Systems in All 50 States, Report Finds |work=[[The New York Times]] |date=2019-07-25 |last1=Sanger |first1=David E. |authorlink1=David E. Sanger |last2=Edmondson |first2=Catie |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/07/25/us/politics/russian-hacking-elections.html |quote=But while the bipartisan report's warning that the United States remains vulnerable in the next election is clear, its findings were so heavily redacted at the insistence of American intelligence agencies that even some key recommendations for 2020 were blacked out. |access-date=July 27, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190727201549/https://www.nytimes.com/2019/07/25/us/politics/russian-hacking-elections.html |archive-date=July 27, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.intelligence.senate.gov/sites/default/files/documents/Report_Volume1.pdf |title=Report of the Select Committee on Intelligence, United States Senate, on Russian Active Measures, Campaigns, and Interference in the 2016 U.S. Election |access-date=2019-07-27 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190727210348/https://www.intelligence.senate.gov/sites/default/files/documents/Report_Volume1.pdf |archive-date=July 27, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> The second volume of that report noted, based on social-media data from October 2018, that \"Russian disinformation efforts may be focused on gathering information and data points in support of an active measures campaign targeted at the 2020 U.S. presidential election.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.intelligence.senate.gov/sites/default/files/documents/Report_Volume2.pdf |title=Report of the Select Committee on Intelligence, United States Senate, on Russian Active Measures, Campaigns, and Interference in the 2016 U.S. Election, Volume 2 |access-date=2019-10-08 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191008172455/https://www.intelligence.senate.gov/sites/default/files/documents/Report_Volume2.pdf |archive-date=October 8, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nU.S. officials have accused [[Russia]], [[China]] and [[Iran]] of trying to influence the 2020 elections.<ref>{{cite news |title=US warns of 'ongoing' election interference by Russia, China, Iran |url=https://thehill.com/policy/national-security/412292-us-warns-of-ongoing-election-interference-by-russia-china-iran |work=The Hill |date=October 19, 2018 |access-date=October 4, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191006082404/https://thehill.com/policy/national-security/412292-us-warns-of-ongoing-election-interference-by-russia-china-iran |archive-date=October 6, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=U.S. Sees Russia, China, Iran Trying to Influence 2020 Elections |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2019-06-24/u-s-sees-russia-china-iran-trying-to-influence-2020-elections |work=Bloomberg |date=June 24, 2019 |access-date=October 4, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191006082404/https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2019-06-24/u-s-sees-russia-china-iran-trying-to-influence-2020-elections |archive-date=October 6, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=US says Russia, China and Iran are trying to influence 2020 elections |url=https://www.thenational.ae/world/the-americas/us-says-russia-china-and-iran-are-trying-to-influence-2020-elections-1.878647 |work=The National |date=June 25, 2019 |access-date=October 4, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191006082401/https://www.thenational.ae/world/the-americas/us-says-russia-china-and-iran-are-trying-to-influence-2020-elections-1.878647 |archive-date=October 6, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=2020 Election Meddling by China, Iran, N. Korea Likely, Administration Officials Warn |url=https://news.yahoo.com/2020-election-meddling-china-iran-090500666.html |work=Yahoo News |date=June 28, 2019 |access-date=October 4, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191006082400/https://news.yahoo.com/2020-election-meddling-china-iran-090500666.html |archive-date=October 6, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> Between January and late July 2017, [[Twitter]] identified and shut down over 7,000 phony accounts created by [[Iran]]ian influence operations.<ref name=\"auto\">{{cite news |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/technology/2019/07/25/its-not-just-russians-anymore-iranians-others-turn-up-disinformation-efforts-ahead-vote/ |title=It's not just the Russians anymore as Iranians and others turn up disinformation efforts ahead of 2020 vote |date=2019-07-25 |website=[[The Washington Post]] |accessdate=2019-07-27 |last1=Timberg |first1=Craig |last2=Romm |first2=Tony |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190728001957/https://www.washingtonpost.com/technology/2019/07/25/its-not-just-russians-anymore-iranians-others-turn-up-disinformation-efforts-ahead-vote/ |archive-date=July 28, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> According to [[Christopher A. Wray]], the [[Director of the Federal Bureau of Investigation]], Russia is attempting to interfere with the [[2020 United States elections]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-usa-election-security-idUSKCN1UI1XW|title=FBI Director Wray: Russia intent on interfering with U.S. elections|date=July 23, 2019|work=Reuters|accessdate=July 24, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190723221517/https://www.reuters.com/article/us-usa-election-security-idUSKCN1UI1XW|archive-date=July 23, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"goldman-nyt\">{{cite news |first=Adam |last=Goldman |authorlink=Adam Goldman |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/04/26/us/politics/fbi-russian-election-interference.html |title=F.B.I. Warns of Russian Interference in 2020 Race and Boosts Counterintelligence Operations |work=The New York Times |date=April 26, 2019 |accessdate=2019-07-24 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190724161858/https://www.nytimes.com/2019/04/26/us/politics/fbi-russian-election-interference.html |archive-date=July 24, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Russian Internet Trolls Are Apparently Switching Strategies for 2020 U.S. Elections |url=https://time.com/5548544/russian-internet-trolls-strategies-2020-elections/ |website=[[Time (magazine)|Time]] |date=2019-03-09 |accessdate=2019-07-27 |last=Sebenius |first=Alyza |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190618030544/https://time.com/5548544/russian-internet-trolls-strategies-2020-elections/ |archive-date=June 18, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> Speaking to the [[Council on Foreign Relations]] in July 2019, Wray stated, \"We are very much viewing 2018 as just kind of a dress rehearsal for the big show in 2020.\"<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/2019/07/25/brief-history-administration-officials-warning-that-our-elections-are-risk-russia/ |title=A brief history of administration officials warning that our elections are at risk from Russia |last=Bump |first=Philip |work=[[The Washington Post]] |date=2019-07-25 |accessdate=2019-07-29 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190729132406/https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/2019/07/25/brief-history-administration-officials-warning-that-our-elections-are-risk-russia/ |archive-date=July 29, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> [[Dan Coats]], the former [[Director of National Intelligence]], believes that Russia and China will both attempt to influence the elections.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.nbcnews.com/politics/national-security/u-s-intel-agencies-russia-china-plotting-interfere-2020-election-n963896 |title=U.S. intel agencies: Russia and China plotting to interfere in 2020 election |website=[[NBC News]] |date=2019-01-29 |accessdate=2019-07-24 |last=Dilanian |first=Ken |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190724194211/https://www.nbcnews.com/politics/national-security/u-s-intel-agencies-russia-china-plotting-interfere-2020-election-n963896 |archive-date=July 24, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.intelligence.senate.gov/sites/default/files/documents/os-dcoats-012919.pdf |title=Worldwide Threat Assessment of the US Intelligence Community |first=Daniel R. |last=Coats |authorlink=Dan Coats |accessdate=2019-07-27 |date=2019-01-29 |website=[[United States Senate Select Committee on Intelligence]] |quote=Russia's social media efforts will continue to focus on aggravating social and racial tensions, undermining trust in authorities, and criticizing perceived anti-Russia politicians.  Moscow may employ additional influence toolkits\u2014such as spreading disinformation, conducting hack-and-leak operations, or manipulating data\u2014in a more targeted fashion to influence US policy, actions, and elections. |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190810023229/https://www.intelligence.senate.gov/sites/default/files/documents/os-dcoats-012919.pdf |archive-date=August 10, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nVarious disinformation campaigns on social media have targeted the [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic Party]] candidates running in the [[2020 Democratic Party presidential primaries]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.politico.com/story/2019/02/20/2020-candidates-social-media-attack-1176018 |title='Sustained and ongoing' disinformation assault targets Dem presidential candidates; A coordinated barrage of social media attacks suggests the involvement of foreign state actors. |first=Natasha |last=Korecki |authorlink=Natasha Korecki |date=February 20, 2019 |website=[[Politico.com]] |publisher= |access-date=July 24, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190724011259/https://www.politico.com/story/2019/02/20/2020-candidates-social-media-attack-1176018 |archive-date=July 24, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> This has prompted considerable concern regarding the ability of [[social media]] companies to cope with disinformation and manipulation.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/powerpost/paloma/the-technology-202/2019/06/26/the-technology-202-06262019-tech202/5d129076a7a0a47d87c56e85/ |title=The Technology 202: Social media companies readying to combat disinformation in Democratic debates |website=[[The Washington Post]] |last=Zakrzewski |first=Cat |date=2019-06-26 |accessdate=2019-07-27 |quote=Facebook and Twitter say they're taking additional precautions this week after analysis found debates were a key target for Russian actors seeking to sow discord on social media ahead of the 2016 election. The companies are under immense public pressure to avoid a repeat in 2020 after they say they were caught off guard by the foreign influence operations in 2016. |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190629042008/https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/powerpost/paloma/the-technology-202/2019/06/26/the-technology-202-06262019-tech202/5d129076a7a0a47d87c56e85/ |archive-date=June 29, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.cbsnews.com/news/anti-vax-movement-russian-trolls-fueled-anti-vaccination-debate-in-us-by-spreading-misinformation-twitter-study/ |work=[[CBS News]] |title=Russian trolls fueled anti-vaccination debate in U.S. by spreading misinformation on Twitter, study finds |last=O'Kane |first=Caitlin |date=2019-05-31 |accessdate=2019-07-28 |quote=Facebook also said it would crack down on the spread of vaccine misinformation by de-prioritizing medical myths across the platform ...  however, misinformation about vaccines is not the only threat, as Russia is focusing on spreading misinformation around health care issues ahead of the 2020 election. |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190723003409/https://www.cbsnews.com/news/anti-vax-movement-russian-trolls-fueled-anti-vaccination-debate-in-us-by-spreading-misinformation-twitter-study/ |archive-date=July 23, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> By August 2019, [[Facebook]] and [[Twitter]] had banned advertisements that use misinformation to attempt the suppression of voter turnout.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/technology/2019/08/28/maryland-was-never-play-russians-targeted-it-anyway/ |title=Maryland was never in play in 2016. The Russians targeted it anyway |work=[[The Washington Post]] |date=2019-08-28 |accessdate=2019-08-28 |last1=Priest |first1=Dana |last2=Aljas |first2=Riin |last3=Gelman |first3=Scott |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190828211553/https://www.washingtonpost.com/technology/2019/08/28/maryland-was-never-play-russians-targeted-it-anyway/ |archive-date=August 28, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n[[Microsoft]] developed an open source software called ElectionGuard to help safeguard the 2020 elections.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.npr.org/2019/05/06/720071488/ahead-of-2020-microsoft-unveils-tool-to-allow-voters-to-track-their-ballots |title=Ahead Of 2020, Microsoft Unveils Tool To Allow Voters To Track Their Ballots |work=[[NPR]] |date=2019-05-06 |last=Parks |first=Miles |access-date=July 27, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190727112620/https://www.npr.org/2019/05/06/720071488/ahead-of-2020-microsoft-unveils-tool-to-allow-voters-to-track-their-ballots |archive-date=July 27, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> In mid-July 2019, Microsoft announced that it had, over the prior year, \"notified nearly 10,000 customers they've been targeted or compromised by nation-state attacks\". Based on attacks that had targeted political organizations, and on experience from 2016 and 2018, Microsoft anticipated \"attacks targeting U.S. election systems, political campaigns or NGOs that work closely with campaigns\".<ref>{{cite web |url=https://blogs.microsoft.com/on-the-issues/2019/07/17/new-cyberthreats-require-new-ways-to-protect-democracy/ |title=New cyberthreats require new ways to protect democracy |last=Burt |first=Tom |website=[[Microsoft]] |date=2019-07-17 |accessdate=2019-07-27 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190727025240/https://blogs.microsoft.com/on-the-issues/2019/07/17/new-cyberthreats-require-new-ways-to-protect-democracy/ |archive-date=July 27, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> Of the \"nation-state attacks\" that had originated from Russia, Microsoft claimed that they followed the \"same pattern of engagement\" as Russian operations in 2016 and 2018.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.cbsnews.com/news/iranian-cyber-activity-spiked-after-u-s-withdrawal-from-nuclear-deal-says-microsoft-official/ |title=Iranian cyber activity \"spiked\" after U.S. withdrawal from nuclear deal, says Microsoft official |last=Gazis |first=Olivia |date=2019-07-19 |accessdate=2019-07-27 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190720130910/https://www.cbsnews.com/news/iranian-cyber-activity-spiked-after-u-s-withdrawal-from-nuclear-deal-says-microsoft-official/ |archive-date=July 20, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> On September 20, 2019, Microsoft announced that it would provide free security updates for [[Windows 7]], which reached its [[End-of-life (product)|end-of-life]] on January 14, 2020, on federally-certified voting machines through the 2020 United States elections.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://blogs.microsoft.com/on-the-issues/2019/09/20/extending-free-windows-7-security-updates-to-voting-systems/|title=Extending free Windows 7 security updates to voting systems|last=Burt|first=Tom|date=September 20, 2019|website=Microsoft On The Issues|url-status=live|access-date=December 11, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191218214735/https://blogs.microsoft.com/on-the-issues/2019/09/20/extending-free-windows-7-security-updates-to-voting-systems/|archive-date=December 18, 2019}}</ref> On October 4, 2019, Microsoft announced that \"Phosphorus\", a group of hackers linked to the [[Government of the Islamic Republic of Iran|Iranian government]], had attempted to compromise e-mail accounts belonging to journalists, prominent Iranian expatriates, U.S. government officials and the campaign of a U.S. presidential candidate.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/technology/2019/10/04/iran-tried-hack-us-presidential-candidates-journalists-effort-that-targeted-hundreds-microsoft-finds/ |title=Iranians tried to hack U.S. presidential candidate in effort that targeted hundreds, Microsoft says |date=October 4, 2019 |accessdate=October 4, 2019 |work=[[The Washington Post]] |first1=Jay |last1=Greene |last2=Romm |first2=Tony |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191004175108/https://www.washingtonpost.com/technology/2019/10/04/iran-tried-hack-us-presidential-candidates-journalists-effort-that-targeted-hundreds-microsoft-finds/ |archive-date=October 4, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://blogs.microsoft.com/on-the-issues/2019/10/04/recent-cyberattacks-require-us-all-to-be-vigilant/ |title=Recent cyberattacks require us all to be vigilant |last=Burt |first=Tom |date=October 4, 2019 |accessdate=October 4, 2019 |website=[[Microsoft]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191004174845/https://blogs.microsoft.com/on-the-issues/2019/10/04/recent-cyberattacks-require-us-all-to-be-vigilant/ |archive-date=October 4, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> While Microsoft did not disclose which campaign had been the target of the cyber attack, unnamed sources informed [[Reuters]] that it had been [[Donald Trump 2020 presidential campaign|that of Donald Trump]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Trump campaign targeted by Iran-linked hackers |url=https://www.jpost.com/Breaking-News/Trump-campaign-targeted-by-Iran-linked-hackers-603732 |work=The Jerusalem Post |date=October 4, 2019 |access-date=October 6, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191006084141/https://www.jpost.com/Breaking-News/Trump-campaign-targeted-by-Iran-linked-hackers-603732 |archive-date=October 6, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nOn October 21, 2019, Facebook CEO [[Mark Zuckerberg]] announced that his company has detected a \"highly sophisticated\" set of campaigns to interfere with the 2020 elections. These campaigns originated from Russia and from Iran.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.nbcnews.com/tech/tech-news/mark-zuckerberg-facebook-caught-russia-iran-trying-interfere-2020-n1069366 |title=Mark Zuckerberg: Facebook caught Russia and Iran trying to interfere in 2020 |work=[[NBC News]] |date=October 21, 2019 |accessdate=October 21, 2019 |first=Jason |last=Abbruzzese |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191021194958/https://www.nbcnews.com/tech/tech-news/mark-zuckerberg-facebook-caught-russia-iran-trying-interfere-2020-n1069366 |archive-date=October 21, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> Fake accounts based in Russia posed as Americans of varied political backgrounds and worked to undermine the campaign of [[Joe Biden]], aiming to sow discontent with Biden from [[Left\u2013right political spectrum|both the left and the right]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.cnn.com/2019/10/21/tech/russia-instagram-accounts-2020-election/index.html |title=Facebook: Russian trolls are back. And they're here to meddle with 2020 |work=[[CNN]] |date=October 21, 2019 |accessdate=October 21, 2019 |first=Donie |last=O'Sullivan |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191021170904/https://www.cnn.com/2019/10/21/tech/russia-instagram-accounts-2020-election/index.html |archive-date=October 21, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nA September 2019 report from ''[[The Washington Post]]'' demonstrated that due to bad default passwords and weak encryption, hackers with physical access can easily get into voting machines designed for use in the [[2020 United States elections]], and remote hacking was possible if the machines were accidentally misconfigured.<ref>{{cite web|website=Yahoo! Finance|title=Researchers easily breached voting machines for the 2020 election|author=Christine Fisher|date=Sep 27, 2019|url=https://finance.yahoo.com/news/2019-09-27-us-voting-machines-hackers-2020-election.html?soc_src=social-sh&soc_trk=tw|access-date=January 26, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191219201412/https://finance.yahoo.com/news/2019-09-27-us-voting-machines-hackers-2020-election.html?soc_src=social-sh&soc_trk=tw|archive-date=December 19, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn February 13, 2020, American intelligence officials advised members of the [[House Intelligence Committee]] that Russia was interfering in the 2020 election in an effort to get Trump re-elected.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://apnews.com/a55930e0a02d2e21d8ed2be7bc496a6f |title=FBI official: Russia wants to see US 'tear ourselves apart' |work=[[Associated Press]] |date=2020-02-24 |accessdate=2020-02-26 |last=Tucker |first=Eric |quote=One intelligence official said lawmakers were not told that Russia was working directly to aid Trump. But other people familiar with the meeting said they were told the Kremlin was looking to help Trump's candidacy. The people spoke on condition of anonymity to discussed the classified briefing. |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200226204303/https://apnews.com/a55930e0a02d2e21d8ed2be7bc496a6f |archive-date=February 26, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> The briefing was delivered by [[Shelby Pierson]], the intelligence community's top election security official and an aide to acting [[Director of National Intelligence]] [[Joseph Maguire]]. Trump allies on the committee challenged the findings, and Trump was angered to learn of the briefing as he believed Democrats might \"weaponize\" the information against him. He chastised Maguire for allowing the briefing to occur, and days later he appointed [[Richard Grenell]] to replace Maguire.<ref name=\"Goldman_Barnes_Haberman_Fandos_2/20/2020\">{{cite web | last1=Goldman | first1=Adam | last2=Barnes | first2=Julian E. | last3=Haberman | first3=Maggie | last4=Fandos | first4=Nicholas | title=Lawmakers Are Warned That Russia Is Meddling to Re-elect Trump | website=[[The New York Times]] | date=February 20, 2020 | url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/02/20/us/politics/russian-interference-trump-democrats.html | access-date=February 26, 2020 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200225234247/https://www.nytimes.com/2020/02/20/us/politics/russian-interference-trump-democrats.html | archive-date=February 25, 2020 | url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=\"Acosta_Cohen_Bash_Herb_2/20/2020\">{{cite web | last=Acosta | first=Jim | last2=Cohen | first2=Zachary | last3=Bash | first3=Dana | last4=Herb | first4=Jeremy | title=Russia is looking to help Trump win in 2020, election security official told lawmakers | publisher=[[CNN]] | date=February 20, 2020 | url=https://www.cnn.com/2020/02/20/politics/trump-russia-intelligence-2020/index.html | access-date=February 26, 2020 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200226001124/https://www.cnn.com/2020/02/20/politics/trump-russia-intelligence-2020/index.html | archive-date=February 26, 2020 | url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=\"Nakashima_Harris_Dawsey_Gearan_2/20/2020\">{{cite web | last=Nakashima | first=Ellen | last2=Harris | first2=Shane | last3=Dawsey | first3=Josh | last4=Gearan | first4=Anne | title=Senior intelligence official told lawmakers that Russia wants to see Trump reelected | website=[[The Washington Post]] | date=February 20, 2020 | url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/national-security/after-a-congressional-briefing-on-election-threats-trump-soured-on-acting-spy-chief/2020/02/20/1ed2b4ec-53f1-11ea-b119-4faabac6674f_story.html | access-date=February 26, 2020 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200225222025/https://www.washingtonpost.com/national-security/after-a-congressional-briefing-on-election-threats-trump-soured-on-acting-spy-chief/2020/02/20/1ed2b4ec-53f1-11ea-b119-4faabac6674f_story.html | archive-date=February 25, 2020 | url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nOn February 21, 2020, ''[[The Washington Post]]'' reported that, according to unnamed US officials, Russia was interfering in the Democratic primary in an effort to support the nomination of Senator [[Bernie Sanders]]. Sanders issued a statement after the news report, saying in part, \"I don't care, frankly, who Putin wants to be president. My message to Putin is clear: stay out of American elections, and as president I will make sure that you do.\"<ref name=\"wapo-2020-02-21\">{{cite news |title=Bernie Sanders briefed by U.S. officials that Russia is trying to help his presidential campaign |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/national-security/bernie-sanders-briefed-by-us-officials-that-russia-is-trying-to-help-his-presidential-campaign/2020/02/21/5ad396a6-54bd-11ea-929a-64efa7482a77_story.html |work=The Washington Post |date=February 21, 2020 |access-date=February 22, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200222124440/https://www.washingtonpost.com/national-security/bernie-sanders-briefed-by-us-officials-that-russia-is-trying-to-help-his-presidential-campaign/2020/02/21/5ad396a6-54bd-11ea-929a-64efa7482a77_story.html |archive-date=February 22, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> Sanders acknowledged that his campaign was briefed about Russia's alleged efforts about a month prior.<ref>{{cite news |title=Russia Is Said to Be Interfering to Aid Sanders in Democratic Primaries |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/02/21/us/politics/bernie-sanders-russia.html |work=The New York Times |date=February 21, 2020 |access-date=February 22, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200222132741/https://www.nytimes.com/2020/02/21/us/politics/bernie-sanders-russia.html |archive-date=February 22, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> Sanders suggested that Russians were impersonating people claiming to be his supporters online in order to create an atmosphere of toxicity and give \"[[Bernie Bro]]s\" a bad reputation, a suggestion that [[Twitter]] rejected.<ref>{{cite news |title=Experts Say There's 'No Evidence' for Bernie's Russian Bot Claim |url=https://www.thedailybeast.com/experts-call-bs-on-bernies-russian-bot-theory |work=The Daily Beast |date=February 21, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Twitter knocks down Bernie Sanders' suggestion that Russian trolls are behind online attacks from his supporters |url=https://www.cnbc.com/2020/02/20/twitter-knocks-down-sanders-suggestion-russian-trolls-behind-supporters.html |work=CNBC |date=February 20, 2020 |access-date=February 22, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200222115000/https://www.cnbc.com/2020/02/20/twitter-knocks-down-sanders-suggestion-russian-trolls-behind-supporters.html |archive-date=February 22, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> According to election-security expert Laura Rosenberger, \"Russian attempts to sow discord in the Democratic primary would be consistent with its strategy of undermining Americans' faith in democratic institutions and processes.\"<ref name=\"wapo-2020-02-21\"/>\n\nIn March 2020, the [[University of Wisconsin\u2013Madison]] and the [[Brennan Center for Justice]] published a report indicating that Russia-linked social media accounts have been spreading [[Instagram]] posts calculated to sow division among American voters.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://apnews.com/0db953743c56cd6fd6e4ef73e02f120c|title=Report: Russian social accounts sow election discord - again|last=Seitz|first=Amanda|last2=Ortutay|first2=Barbara|date=2020-03-05|website=[[Associated Press]]|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200309180450/https://apnews.com/0db953743c56cd6fd6e4ef73e02f120c|archive-date=March 9, 2020|access-date=2020-03-09}}</ref><ref name=\"brennan\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.brennancenter.org/our-work/analysis-opinion/new-evidence-shows-how-russias-election-interference-has-gotten-more|title=New Evidence Shows How Russia's Election Interference Has Gotten More Brazen|last=Kim|first=Young Mie|date=2020-05-05|website=[[Brennan Center for Justice]]|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200311173959/https://www.brennancenter.org/our-work/analysis-opinion/new-evidence-shows-how-russias-election-interference-has-gotten-more|archive-date=March 11, 2020|access-date=2020-03-09}}</ref> According to the report, Russian operatives were increasingly impersonating real political candidates and groups rather than creating fictional groups.<ref name=\"brennan\" /> According to Twitter's head of site integrity, Russian agents also attempted in 2018 to create the impression of more election interference than is actually happening to undermine confidence in the process.<ref>[https://www.npr.org/2020/03/05/812497423/report-russian-election-trolling-becoming-subtler-tougher-to-detect Report: Russian Election Trolling Becoming Subtler, Tougher To Detect]</ref> Shortly thereafter, the ''New York Times'' reported that according to American intelligence officials Russian operatives have been promoting and pressuring [[hate group]]s, including [[neo-Nazis]], in order to create strife within American society.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Barnes|first=Julian E.|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/10/us/politics/russian-interference-race.html|title=Russia Trying to Stoke U.S. Racial Tensions Before Election, Officials Say|date=2020-03-10|work=[[The New York Times]]|access-date=2020-03-10|url-status=live|last2=Goldman|first2=Adam|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200310192420/https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/10/us/politics/russian-interference-race.html|archive-date=March 10, 2020}}</ref> A [[CNN]] investigation found that Russian efforts had partly been outsourced to [[troll farm]]s in [[Ghana]] and [[Nigeria]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.cnn.com/2020/03/12/world/russia-ghana-troll-farms-2020-ward/index.html |title=Russian election meddling is back \u2014 via Ghana and Nigeria \u2014 and in your feeds |date=2020-03-12 |accessdate=2020-03-12 |work=[[CNN]] |first1=Clarissa |last1=Ward |first2=Katie |last2=Polglase |first3=Sebastian |last3=Shukla |first4=Gianluca |last4=Mezzofiore |first5=Tim |last5=Lister |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200312232339/https://www.cnn.com/2020/03/12/world/russia-ghana-troll-farms-2020-ward/index.html |archive-date=March 12, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n==Government reaction==\n\n[[Dan Coats]] appointed [[Shelby Pierson]] as the U.S. election security [[Czar (political term)|czar]] in July 2019, creating a new position in a move seen as an acknowledgment that foreign influence operations against U.S. elections will be ongoing indefinitely.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Barnes |first1=Julian E. |title=Intelligence Chief Names New Election Security Oversight Official |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/07/19/us/politics/intelligence-election-security.html |work=[[The New York Times]] |date=July 19, 2019 |accessdate=July 26, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190723140612/https://www.nytimes.com/2019/07/19/us/politics/intelligence-election-security.html |archive-date=July 23, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.npr.org/2019/07/28/696376152/dan-coats-who-challenged-president-trump-to-depart-top-intelligence-job |title=Dan Coats, Who Challenged President Trump, Is Ousted From Top Intelligence Job |last=Myre |first=Greg |work=[[NPR]] |date=2019-07-28 |accessdate=2019-07-28 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190728220444/https://www.npr.org/2019/07/28/696376152/dan-coats-who-challenged-president-trump-to-depart-top-intelligence-job |archive-date=July 28, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> Election-security task forces established before the [[2018 United States elections|2018 midterm elections]] at the FBI, the [[Department of Homeland Security]], the [[National Security Agency]] and the [[United States Cyber Command]] have been expanded and \"made permanent\".<ref name=\"goldman-nyt\"/> The Department of Homeland Security indicated that the threat of [[ransomware]] attacks upon [[voter registration]] databases was a particular concern.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-usa-cyber-election-exclusive/exclusive-u-s-officials-fear-ransomware-attack-against-2020-election-idUSKCN1VG222 |title=U.S. officials fear ransomware attack against 2020 election |work=[[Reuters]] |date=2019-08-26 |accessdate=2019-08-27 |last=Bing |first=Christopher |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190827174333/https://www.reuters.com/article/us-usa-cyber-election-exclusive/exclusive-u-s-officials-fear-ransomware-attack-against-2020-election-idUSKCN1VG222 |archive-date=August 27, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nPrior to resigning as [[U.S. Secretary of Homeland Security]], [[Kirstjen Nielsen]] attempted to organize a meeting of the [[U.S. Cabinet]] to discuss how to address potential foreign interference in the 2020 elections. [[Mick Mulvaney]], the [[White House Chief of Staff]], reportedly warned her to keep the subject away from Trump, who views the discussion as questioning the legitimacy of his victory in 2016.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/04/24/us/politics/russia-2020-election-trump.html |work=[[The New York Times]] |date=2019-04-24 |title=In Push for 2020 Election Security, Top Official Was Warned: Don't Tell Trump |last1=Schmitt |first1=Eric |authorlink1=Eric P. Schmitt |last2=Sanger |first2=David E. |authorlink2=David E. Sanger |last3=Haberman |first3=Maggie |authorlink3=Maggie Haberman |access-date=July 27, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190727194235/https://www.nytimes.com/2019/04/24/us/politics/russia-2020-election-trump.html |archive-date=July 27, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> [[Mitch McConnell]], the [[Senate Majority Leader]], has blocked various bills intended to improve election security from being considered,<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.newsweek.com/2019/08/02/elections-2020-will-take-place-cyber-battleground-that-puts-us-disadvantage-says-expert-1450351.html |title=Russia Is Using Cold War Strategy to Undermine the Faith of Americans in the 2020 Election\u2014Will It Work? |website=[[Newsweek]] |date=2019-07-23 |last=Piore |first=Adam |accessdate=2019-07-27 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190727231644/https://www.newsweek.com/2019/08/02/elections-2020-will-take-place-cyber-battleground-that-puts-us-disadvantage-says-expert-1450351.html |archive-date=July 27, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last=Croucher |first=Shane |url=https://www.newsweek.com/moscow-mitch-trends-twitter-mcconnell-russia-election-interference-1451274 |title=#MoscowMitch Trends on Twitter as Mitch McConnell Blocks Election Security Bills Despite 'Unprecedented Level' of Russian Interference |publisher=Newsweek.com |date=July 26, 2019 |accessdate=2019-07-26 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190726192133/https://www.newsweek.com/moscow-mitch-trends-twitter-mcconnell-russia-election-interference-1451274 |archive-date=July 26, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.pbs.org/newshour/politics/how-the-u-s-is-trying-to-improve-election-security-ahead-of-2020 |title=How the U.S. is trying to improve election security ahead of 2020 |last=Martinez |first=Gabriela |date=2019-07-26 |accessdate=2019-07-27 |website=[[PBS Newshour]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190727232600/https://www.pbs.org/newshour/politics/how-the-u-s-is-trying-to-improve-election-security-ahead-of-2020 |archive-date=July 27, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> including some measures that have had bipartisan support.<ref>{{cite news |last=Dilanian |first=Ken |title=Hill push to battle foreign election interference is stuck at McConnell roadblock |url=https://www.nbcnews.com/politics/national-security/hill-push-battle-foreign-election-interference-stuck-mcconnell-roadblock-n1017361 |work=[[NBC News]] |date=2019-06-13 |accessdate=2019-07-30 |quote=In fact, some GOP senators have joined with Democrats to co-sponsor legislation designed to shore up voting machines and make it harder for foreign intelligence operatives to hack, leak and manipulate social media the way the Russians did in 2016. But those bills are going nowhere \u2014 because Senate Majority Leader Mitch McConnell, R-Ky., has not allowed a vote on any of them. |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190723050705/https://www.nbcnews.com/politics/national-security/hill-push-battle-foreign-election-interference-stuck-mcconnell-roadblock-n1017361 |archive-date=July 23, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |url=https://www.wired.com/story/russia-2020-election-security-mark-warner/ |title=Russia Is Going To Up Its Game For The 2020 Elections |journal=[[Wired (magazine)|Wired]] |last=Laslo |first=Matt |date=2019-07-31 |accessdate=2019-08-02 |quote=Both bills have bipartisan support\u2014Senator Susan Collins became the first Republican to cosponsor the Foreign Influence Reporting in Elections Act earlier this week. |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190801204804/https://www.wired.com/story/russia-2020-election-security-mark-warner/ |archive-date=August 1, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> Election-security legislation remains stalled in the Senate as of February 2020.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://thehill.com/homenews/house/482569-senate-gop-blocks-three-election-security-bills|title=Senate GOP blocks three election security bills|last=Balluck|first=Kyle|date=2020-02-11|website=[[The Hill (newspaper)|The Hill]]|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200211215724/https://thehill.com/homenews/house/482569-senate-gop-blocks-three-election-security-bills|archive-date=February 11, 2020|access-date=2020-02-11}}</ref> However, various states have implemented changes, such as [[paper ballot]]s.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/07/26/us/politics/states-voting-systems.html |work=[[The New York Times]] |title=States Rush to Make Voting Systems More Secure as New Threats Emerge |date=2019-07-26 |last1=Sanger |first1=David E. |authorlink1=David E. Sanger |last2=Epstein |first2=Reid J. |last3=Wines |first3=Michael |authorlink3=Michael Wines |access-date=July 27, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190727001938/https://www.nytimes.com/2019/07/26/us/politics/states-voting-systems.html |archive-date=July 27, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> [[Florida]] has expanded its paper-ballot backup system since 2016, but experts warn that its voting systems are still vulnerable to manipulation, a particular concern being the electronic poll books that store lists of registered voters.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2019/aug/27/florida-russian-hackers-target-2020-election |title=Russian hackers likely to target Florida again in 2020 election, experts warn |work=[[The Guardian]] |date=2019-08-27 |accessdate=2019-08-27 |last=Stone |first=Peter |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190827143332/https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2019/aug/27/florida-russian-hackers-target-2020-election |archive-date=August 27, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> All 67 election supervisors in Florida have been required to sign [[nondisclosure agreement]]s, and consequently, information such as the identity of which four counties had been hacked by Russian intelligence in 2016 remains unknown to the public.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.usatoday.com/in-depth/news/investigations/2020/02/25/voting-access-florida-sunshine-state-election-security/4866141002/ |title=Will your vote count? Veil of secrecy makes it impossible for Florida voters to know |first=Jeffrey |last=Schweers |date=2020-02-25 |accessdate=2020-02-26 |work=[[USA Today]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200226204743/https://www.usatoday.com/in-depth/news/investigations/2020/02/25/voting-access-florida-sunshine-state-election-security/4866141002/ |archive-date=February 26, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]] members of Congress cited the lack of effort to secure U.S. elections against foreign interference, particularly from Russia, as among grounds to begin an [[impeachment]] inquiry.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.cnn.com/2019/07/25/politics/jackie-speier-take-action-impeachment-shut-it-down-cnntv/index.html |title=Dem lawmaker to her party: 'Take action' on impeachment by September or 'shut it down' |last=Sullivan |first=Kate |work=[[CNN]] |date=2019-07-25 |accessdate=2019-07-29 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190727145555/https://www.cnn.com/2019/07/25/politics/jackie-speier-take-action-impeachment-shut-it-down-cnntv/index.html |archive-date=July 27, 2019 |url-status=live }}<br/>{{cite news |url=https://www.wbur.org/news/2019/07/25/ed-markey-trump-impeachment-probe |title=Rep. Clark Backs Impeachment Probe, Putting Pressure On Pelosi |work=[[WBUR]] |last1=Swasey |first1=Benjamin |last2=Atkins |first2=Kimberley |date=2019-07-25 |accessdate=2019-07-29 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190727170338/https://www.wbur.org/news/2019/07/25/ed-markey-trump-impeachment-probe |archive-date=July 27, 2019 |url-status=live }}<br/>{{cite news |url=https://www.seattletimes.com/seattle-news/all-washington-house-democrats-now-favor-impeachment-inquiry-of-trump/ |title=All Washington House Democrats now favor Trump impeachment inquiry |last=Romano |first=Benjamin |work=[[The Seattle Times]] |date=2019-07-29 |accessdate=2019-07-29 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190729131505/https://www.seattletimes.com/seattle-news/all-washington-house-democrats-now-favor-impeachment-inquiry-of-trump/ |archive-date=July 29, 2019 |url-status=live }}<br/>{{cite news |url=https://www.theolympian.com/news/local/article233239221.html |title=U.S. Reps Heck, Kilmer, Schreir, and Del Bene announce support of impeachment inquiry |work=[[The Olympian]] |last=Boone |first=Rolf |date=2019-07-28 |accessdate=2019-07-29 }}</ref>\n\nOn September 30, 2019, the United States issued economic sanctions against seven Russians affiliated with the [[Internet Research Agency]], an organization that manipulates social media for misinformation purposes. The sanctions were described as a warning against foreign interference in United States elections.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/09/30/us/politics/us-russia-sanctions-election-meddling.html |title=With Sanctions on Russians, U.S. Warns Against Foreign Election Meddling |work=[[The New York Times]] |date=September 30, 2019 |last=Jakes |first=Lara |access-date=October 1, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191001022221/https://www.nytimes.com/2019/09/30/us/politics/us-russia-sanctions-election-meddling.html |archive-date=October 1, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nOn December 9, 2019, FBI Director [[Christopher A. Wray]] told ABC News: \"as far as the [2020] election itself goes, we think Russia represents the most significant threat.\"<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://abcnews.go.com/Politics/fbi-director-chris-wray-reacts-doj-watchdog-report/story?id=67605418|title=FBI Director Chris Wray reacts to DOJ watchdog report on Russia investigation: Exclusive|website=ABC News|language=en|access-date=2019-12-10|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191219051108/https://abcnews.go.com/Politics/fbi-director-chris-wray-reacts-doj-watchdog-report/story?id=67605418|archive-date=December 19, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> According to [[William Evanina]], director of the [[National Counterintelligence and Security Center]], Russia is \"using social media and many other tools to inflame social divisions, promote conspiracy theories and sow distrust in our democracy and elections.\"<ref name=\"bloomberg-jan2020\">{{cite news |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2020-01-10/u-s-probes-if-russia-targeting-biden-in-2020-election-meddling |title=U.S. Probes If Russia Is Targeting Biden in 2020 Election Meddling |first=Chris |last=Strohm |date=January 10, 2020 |accessdate=January 10, 2020 |work=[[Bloomberg News]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200110210442/https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2020-01-10/u-s-probes-if-russia-targeting-biden-in-2020-election-meddling |archive-date=January 10, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n''Bloomberg News'' reported in January 2020 that American intelligence and law enforcement were examining whether Russia was involved in promoting disinformation to undermine Joe Biden as part of a campaign to disrupt the 2020 election.<ref name=\"bloomberg-jan2020\"/> The following month, the [[Estonian Foreign Intelligence Service]] warned that Russia would attempt to interfere in the [[Georgia (country)|Georgian]] [[2020 Georgian parliamentary election|parliamentary election]] in October 2020 as well as the US election in November.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.nbcnews.com/politics/national-security/russia-will-try-meddle-2020-u-s-election-intelligence-report-n1134446 |title=Russia will try to meddle in 2020 U.S. election, intelligence report says |work=[[NBC News]] |date=February 12, 2020 |accessdate=February 12, 2020 |last=Kube |first=Courtney |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200213153143/https://www.nbcnews.com/politics/national-security/russia-will-try-meddle-2020-u-s-election-intelligence-report-n1134446 |archive-date=February 13, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n=== Trump administration reaction ===\n\nThe Trump administration reacted to the briefing by American intelligence officials to the House Intelligence Committee that Russia was interfering in the 2020 election in an effort to get Trump re-elected<ref name=\"Goldman_Barnes_Haberman_Fandos_2/20/2020\"/><ref name=\"Acosta_Cohen_Bash_Herb_2/20/2020\"/><ref name=\"Nakashima_Harris_Dawsey_Gearan_2/20/2020\"/>  by rejecting the efforts were in favor of Trump<ref name=\"Diamond_Tapper_Cohen_2/23/2020\">{{cite web | last=Diamond | first=Jeremy | last2=Tapper | first2=Jake | last3=Cohen | first3=Zachary | title=US intelligence briefer appears to have overstated assessment of 2020 Russian interference | publisher=[[CNN]] | date=February 23, 2020 | url=https://www.cnn.com/2020/02/23/politics/intelligence-briefer-russian-interference-trump-sanders/index.html | access-date=February 26, 2020 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200226015505/https://www.cnn.com/2020/02/23/politics/intelligence-briefer-russian-interference-trump-sanders/index.html | archive-date=February 26, 2020 | url-status=live }}</ref> and by firing Joseph Maguire, who was involved in those reports.<ref name=\"Goldman_Barnes_Haberman_Fandos_2/20/2020\"/><ref name=\"Acosta_Cohen_Bash_Herb_2/20/2020\"/><ref name=\"Nakashima_Harris_Dawsey_Gearan_2/20/2020\"/>\n\nBy contrast, Trump and his national security adviser [[Robert C. O'Brien (attorney)|Robert O'Brien]]<ref name=\"Sanger_2/24/2020\">{{cite web | last=Sanger | first=David E. | title=Dueling Narratives Emerge From Muddied Account of Russia's 2020 Interference | website=[[The New York Times]] | date=February 24, 2020 | url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/02/23/us/politics/russia-2020-election-interference.html | access-date=February 26, 2020 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200225231616/https://www.nytimes.com/2020/02/23/us/politics/russia-2020-election-interference.html | archive-date=February 25, 2020 | url-status=live }}</ref> accepted reports the Russians were supporting the nomination of Bernie Sanders.<ref name=\"Pengelly_2/22/2020\">{{cite web | last=Pengelly | first=Martin | title=Donald Trump pounces on reports Russia is seeking to help Bernie Sanders | website=[[The Guardian]] | date=February 22, 2020 | url=http://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2020/feb/22/donald-trump-bernie-sanders-russia | access-date=February 26, 2020 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200225170801/https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2020/feb/22/donald-trump-bernie-sanders-russia | archive-date=February 25, 2020 | url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=\"wapo-2020-02-21\">{{cite news |title=Bernie Sanders briefed by U.S. officials that Russia is trying to help his presidential campaign |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/national-security/bernie-sanders-briefed-by-us-officials-that-russia-is-trying-to-help-his-presidential-campaign/2020/02/21/5ad396a6-54bd-11ea-929a-64efa7482a77_story.html |work=The Washington Post |date=February 21, 2020 |access-date=February 22, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200222124440/https://www.washingtonpost.com/national-security/bernie-sanders-briefed-by-us-officials-that-russia-is-trying-to-help-his-presidential-campaign/2020/02/21/5ad396a6-54bd-11ea-929a-64efa7482a77_story.html |archive-date=February 22, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nThree weeks after Trump loyalist [[Richard Grenell]] was appointed acting [[Director of National Intelligence]], intelligence officials briefed members of Congress behind closed doors that they had \"not concluded that the Kremlin is directly aiding any candidate\u2019s re-election or any other candidates\u2019 election,\" which differed from testimony they had provided the previous month indicating that Russia was working to aid Trump's candidacy. Two intelligence officials pushed back on suggestions the new testimony was politically motivated. One intelligence official asserted the earlier testimony had overreached and that Democrats had mischaracterized it. [[Trump\u2013Ukraine scandal#Kashyap Patel|Kash Patel]], a former aide to congressman [[Devin Nunes]] who joined Grenell at the ODNI, imposed limits on what intelligence officials could tell Congress about foreign influence operations. The briefers reportedly did not intend to contradict their previous testimony, though they avoided repeating it.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/10/us/politics/election-interference-briefing-trump.html |title=Archived copy |access-date=March 11, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200311165910/https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/10/us/politics/election-interference-briefing-trump.html |archive-date=March 11, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/02/20/us/politics/russian-interference-trump-democrats.html |title=Archived copy |access-date=February 21, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200221010559/https://www.nytimes.com/2020/02/20/us/politics/russian-interference-trump-democrats.html |archive-date=February 21, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n==Presidency of Donald Trump==\n\nIn a June 2019 interview with [[George Stephanopoulos]], [[President of the United States|President]] [[Donald Trump]] said that he would accept information from other nations about his opponents in the [[2020 United States presidential election]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Baker |first1=Peter |authorlink1=Peter Baker (journalist) |title=Trump Says 'I'd Take It' if Russia Again Offered Dirt on Opponent |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/06/12/us/politics/trump-russia-fbi.html |work=The New York Times |date=June 12, 2019 |accessdate=July 26, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190724184644/https://www.nytimes.com/2019/06/12/us/politics/trump-russia-fbi.html |archive-date=July 24, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://abcnews.go.com/Politics/transcript-abc-news-george-stephanopoulos-exclusive-interview-president/story?id=63749144 |title=Transcript: ABC News' George Stephanopoulos' exclusive interview with President Trump |author=<!--Not stated--> |date=June 16, 2019 |website=ABC News |access-date=31 July 2019 |quote=[[George Stephanopoulos|STEPHANOPOULOS]]: Your campaign this time around, if foreigners, if Russia, if China, if someone else offers you information on opponents, should they accept it or should they call the FBI?  TRUMP: I think maybe you do both. I think you might want to listen, I don't, there's nothing wrong with listening. If somebody called from a country, Norway, \"We have information on your opponent.\" Oh, I think I'd want to hear it.  STEPHANOPOULOS: You want that kind of interference in our elections?  TRUMP: It's not an interference, they have information. I think I'd take it. If I thought there was something wrong, I'd go maybe to the FBI. If I thought there was something wrong. But when somebody comes up with oppo research, right, that they come up with oppo research. Oh, let's call the FBI. The FBI doesn't have enough agents to take care of it, but you go and talk honestly to congressmen, they all do it, they always have. And that's the way it is. It's called oppo research.  STEPHANOPOULOS: Surprising. Thank you.  TRUMP: Thank you. Okay. Fine. |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190801032648/https://abcnews.go.com/Politics/transcript-abc-news-george-stephanopoulos-exclusive-interview-president/story?id=63749144 |archive-date=August 1, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nAccording to reporting by ''The Wall Street Journal'', ''The Washington Post'' and ''The New York Times'', Trump and his personal attorney [[Rudy Giuliani]] repeatedly pressed the [[Government of Ukraine|Ukrainian government]] to investigate [[Hunter Biden]], the son of [[Joe Biden]], leading to the {{As of|2020|1|9|df=US|alt=ongoing}} [[Trump\u2013Ukraine scandal]].<ref name=\"auto4\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/trump-defends-conversation-with-ukraine-leader-11568993176|title=WSJ News Exclusive &#124; Trump Repeatedly Pressed Ukraine President to Investigate Biden's Son|first=Alan Cullison, Rebecca Ballhaus and Dustin|last=Volz|website=WSJ|access-date=September 23, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190923092317/https://www.wsj.com/articles/trump-defends-conversation-with-ukraine-leader-11568993176|archive-date=September 23, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"auto5\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/national-security/trump-pressed-ukrainian-leader-to-investigate-bidens-son-according-to-people-familiar-with-the-matter/2019/09/20/7fa39b20-dbdc-11e9-bfb1-849887369476_story.html|title=Trump pressed Ukrainian leader to investigate Biden's son, according to people familiar with the matter|website=Washington Post|access-date=September 23, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190922233816/https://www.washingtonpost.com/national-security/trump-pressed-ukrainian-leader-to-investigate-bidens-son-according-to-people-familiar-with-the-matter/2019/09/20/7fa39b20-dbdc-11e9-bfb1-849887369476_story.html|archive-date=September 22, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/09/20/us/politics/trump-whistle-blower-ukraine.html|title=Trump Pressed Ukraine's Leader on Inquiry Into Biden's Son|first1=Julian E.|last1=Barnes|first2=Michael S.|last2=Schmidt|first3=Kenneth P.|last3=Vogel|first4=Adam|last4=Goldman|first5=Maggie|last5=Haberman|date=September 20, 2019|via=NYTimes.com|access-date=September 23, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190923114022/https://www.nytimes.com/2019/09/20/us/politics/trump-whistle-blower-ukraine.html|archive-date=September 23, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> Biden is a potentially strong Trump challenger in the 2020 presidential election.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/trump-defends-conversation-with-ukraine-leader-11568993176|title=WSJ News Exclusive {{!}} Trump Repeatedly Pressed Ukraine President to Investigate Biden's Son|last=Volz|first=Alan Cullison, Rebecca Ballhaus and Dustin|website=WSJ|language=en-US|access-date=September 20, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190923092317/https://www.wsj.com/articles/trump-defends-conversation-with-ukraine-leader-11568993176|archive-date=September 23, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/09/20/world/europe/ukraine-trump-zelensky.html|title=Ukraine Pressured on U.S. Political Investigations|last=Kramer|first=Andrew E.|date=September 20, 2019|work=The New York Times|access-date=September 20, 2019|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190920171010/https://www.nytimes.com/2019/09/20/world/europe/ukraine-trump-zelensky.html|archive-date=September 20, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> The purpose of the requested investigation was alleged to be to damage [[Joe Biden 2020 presidential campaign|Biden's election campaign]] for president.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.axios.com/trump-whistleblower-ukraine-e57df07d-137d-41db-9adc-5c17b74013ab.html|title=WSJ: Trump urged Ukrainian president \"about 8 times\" to investigate Biden's son|website=Axios|language=en|access-date=September 20, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190920210637/https://www.axios.com/trump-whistleblower-ukraine-e57df07d-137d-41db-9adc-5c17b74013ab.html|archive-date=September 20, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"auto1\">{{Cite web|url=https://foreignpolicy.com/2019/09/20/is-trump-trying-to-get-ukraine-to-take-out-biden-for-him/|title=Is Trump Trying to Get Ukraine to Take Out Biden for Him?|last=Mackinnon|first=Amy|website=Foreign Policy|language=en-US|access-date=September 20, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190920210034/https://foreignpolicy.com/2019/09/20/is-trump-trying-to-get-ukraine-to-take-out-biden-for-him/|archive-date=September 20, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> Reports suggested that Trump threatened to withhold [[military aid]] from [[Ukraine]] unless they investigate Biden.<ref name=\"auto1\" /><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.newyorker.com/news/our-columnists/did-trump-try-to-extort-the-president-of-ukraine-into-investigating-joe-biden|title=Did Trump Try to Extort the President of Ukraine Into Investigating Joe Biden?|last=Cassidy|first=John|date=September 20, 2019|access-date=September 20, 2019|language=en|issn=0028-792X|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190920205009/https://www.newyorker.com/news/our-columnists/did-trump-try-to-extort-the-president-of-ukraine-into-investigating-joe-biden|archive-date=September 20, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> The controversy triggered the commencement of the [[Impeachment inquiry against Donald Trump|formal process of impeachment inquiries against Trump]] on September 24, with House speaker [[Nancy Pelosi]] directing six House committee chairmen to proceed \"under that umbrella of impeachment inquiry\".<ref name = formal>{{cite web |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/powerpost/pelosi-top-democrats-privately-discuss-creation-of-select-committee-for-impeachment/2019/09/24/af6f735a-dedf-11e9-b199-f638bf2c340f_story.html |title=House Speaker Nancy Pelosi announces formal impeachment inquiry of Trump, says his actions were a 'betrayal of national security' |work=The Washington Post |date= |accessdate=2019-09-24 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190924201421/https://www.washingtonpost.com/powerpost/pelosi-top-democrats-privately-discuss-creation-of-select-committee-for-impeachment/2019/09/24/af6f735a-dedf-11e9-b199-f638bf2c340f_story.html |archive-date=September 24, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nOn October 3, 2019, Trump said that \"[[China]] should start an investigation\" into [[2020 Democratic Party presidential primaries|presidential candidate]] Joe Biden and his son Hunter Biden. Moments before, while discussing negotiations on a possible agreement in the ongoing [[China\u2013United States trade war]], he said that \"if they [China] don't do what we want, we have tremendous power.\" Chair of the [[Federal Election Commission]] [[Ellen Weintraub]] then retweeted a June statement explaining that \"it is illegal for any person to solicit, accept, or receive anything of value from a foreign national in connection with a U.S. election\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nbcnews.com/politics/2020-election/trump-publicly-urges-china-ukraine-investigate-bidens-amid-impeachment-inquiry-n1061956|title=Trump publicly urges China to investigate Bidens amid impeachment inquiry|publisher=NBC News|date=October 3, 2019|accessdate=October 3, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191003160859/https://www.nbcnews.com/politics/2020-election/trump-publicly-urges-china-ukraine-investigate-bidens-amid-impeachment-inquiry-n1061956|archive-date=October 3, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n{{As of|2019|10|alt=As of early October 2019}}, there is evidence President Trump, Vice President [[Mike Pence]], U.S. Attorney General [[William Barr]], as well as Trump's personal attorney Giuliani have solicited help from Ukraine, Australia, Italy, the United Kingdom, and China for assistance in discrediting Trump's political opponents.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/trump-impeachment-inquiry-live-updates/2019/10/03/5f81ec5a-e55c-11e9-a6e8-8759c5c7f608_story.html|title=Trump ordered removal of ambassador over Biden probe; president calls for China to investigate Bidens|first1=Colby|last1=Itkowitz|first2=John|last2=Wagner|first3=Felicia|last3=Sonmez|date=October 4, 2019|via=www.washingtonpost.com|access-date=October 4, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191004204355/https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/trump-impeachment-inquiry-live-updates/2019/10/03/5f81ec5a-e55c-11e9-a6e8-8759c5c7f608_story.html|archive-date=October 4, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/10/03/us/politics/trump-china-bidens.html|title=Trump Publicly Urges China to Investigate the Bidens|first1=Peter|last1=Baker|first2=Eileen|last2=Sullivan|date=October 3, 2019|via=NYTimes.com|access-date=October 4, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191004231604/https://www.nytimes.com/2019/10/03/us/politics/trump-china-bidens.html|archive-date=October 4, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/trump-urges-ukraine-china-to-investigate-the-bidens-11570114755|title=Trump Administration Used Potential Meeting to Pressure Ukraine on Biden, Texts Indicate|first=Rebecca Ballhaus, Siobhan Hughes and Dustin|last=Volz|website=WSJ|access-date=October 4, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191004172356/https://www.wsj.com/articles/trump-urges-ukraine-china-to-investigate-the-bidens-11570114755|archive-date=October 4, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnn.com/2019/10/03/politics/donald-trump-ukraine-china-investigate-2020/index.html|title=Trump now says both China and Ukraine should investigate Bidens|author=Kevin Liptak|website=CNN|access-date=October 4, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191004193006/https://www.cnn.com/2019/10/03/politics/donald-trump-ukraine-china-investigate-2020/index.html|archive-date=October 4, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://apnews.com/c4fc388b22f549e0a67925cab8cd7e93|title=Not just Ukraine: Trump now calls for China to probe Bidens|date=October 3, 2019|website=AP NEWS|access-date=October 4, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191004175445/https://www.apnews.com/c4fc388b22f549e0a67925cab8cd7e93|archive-date=October 4, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.axios.com/trump-china-investigate-joe-biden-f7d034bf-91ea-4ede-a879-6b86c36e719a.html|title=Trump says China should investigate Bidens|website=Axios|access-date=October 4, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191004081222/https://www.axios.com/trump-china-investigate-joe-biden-f7d034bf-91ea-4ede-a879-6b86c36e719a.html|archive-date=October 4, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nbcnews.com/politics/2020-election/trump-publicly-urges-china-ukraine-investigate-bidens-amid-impeachment-inquiry-n1061956|title=Trump publicly urges China to investigate Bidens amid impeachment inquiry|website=NBC News|access-date=October 3, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191003205659/https://www.nbcnews.com/politics/2020-election/trump-publicly-urges-china-ukraine-investigate-bidens-amid-impeachment-inquiry-n1061956|archive-date=October 3, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnbc.com/2019/10/03/trump-calls-for-ukraine-china-to-investigate-the-bidens.html|title=Trump says China should investigate the Bidens, doubles down on Ukraine probe|first=Kevin|last=Breuninger|date=October 3, 2019|website=CNBC|access-date=October 4, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191004193118/https://www.cnbc.com/2019/10/03/trump-calls-for-ukraine-china-to-investigate-the-bidens.html|archive-date=October 4, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2019/oct/03/trump-biden-china-investigation-demand|title=Trump calls on China to investigate Biden in extraordinary demand|first1=Julian|last1=Borger|first2=Lauren|last2=Gambino|date=October 3, 2019|via=www.theguardian.com|access-date=October 4, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191027153313/https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2019/oct/03/trump-biden-china-investigation-demand|archive-date=October 27, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n\n*[[Impeachment inquiry against Donald Trump]]\n*[[Second American Civil War#Culture war as Second American Civil War|Cold Civil war]]\n*[[Cold War II]]\n*[[Cyberwarfare and Iran]]\n*[[Cyberwarfare by Russia]]\n*[[Democratic National Committee cyber attacks]]\n*[[Foreign electoral intervention]]\n*[[Presidency of Donald Trump]]\n*[[Russian espionage in the United States]]\n*[[Russian interference in the 2018 United States elections]]\n*[[Social media in the 2016 United States presidential election]]\n*[[Social media in the 2020 United States presidential election]]\n*2016 interference timeline\n**[[Timeline of Russian interference in the 2016 United States elections]]\n**[[Timeline of Russian interference in the 2016 United States elections (July 2016\u2013election day)]]\n**[[Timeline of post-election transition following Russian interference in the 2016 United States elections]]\n**[[Timeline of investigations into Trump and Russia (January\u2013June 2017)]]\n**[[Timeline of investigations into Trump and Russia (July\u2013December 2017)]]\n**[[Timeline of investigations into Trump and Russia (January\u2013June 2018)]]\n**[[Timeline of investigations into Trump and Russia (July\u2013December 2018)]]\n**[[Timeline of investigations into Trump and Russia (2019\u20132020)]]\n*[[1996 United States campaign finance controversy]]\n\n==References==\n\n{{Reflist}}\n{{Russian interference in the 2016 United States elections}}\n{{2020 United States elections}}\n\n<!--[[Category:2020 controversies in the United States]]-->\n[[Category:2020 elections in the United States]]\n[[Category:Russia\u2013United States relations]]\n[[Category:Foreign electoral intervention]]\n[[Category:Internet manipulation and propaganda]]\n[[Category:Trump administration controversies]]\n[[Category:Information operations and warfare]]